{"title_page": "Cliodynamics", "text_new": "{{short description|Mathematical modeling of historical processes}}\n[[File:clio.jpg|thumb|Clio\u2014detail from ''[[The Art of Painting|The Allegory of Painting]]'' by [[Johannes Vermeer]]]]\n\n'''Cliodynamics''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|k|l|i\u02d0|o\u028a|d|a\u026a|\u02c8|n|\u00e6|m|\u026a|k|s}}) is a transdisciplinary area of research integrating [[cultural evolution]], [[economic history]]/[[cliometrics]], [[macrosociology]], the mathematical modeling of historical processes during the ''[[longue dur\u00e9e]]'', and the construction and analysis of historical databases.{{sfn|Turchin|2008}} Cliodynamics treats history as science. Its practitioners develop theories that explain such dynamical processes as the rise and fall of empires, population booms and busts, spread and disappearance of religions.{{sfn|Sussan|2013}}{{sfn|Schrodt|2005}} These theories are translated into mathematical models. Finally, model predictions are tested against data. Thus, building and analyzing massive databases of historical and archaeological information is one of the most important goals of cliodynamics.{{sfn|Spinney|2012}}\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word ''cliodynamics'' is composed of ''clio-'' and ''-dynamics''. In Greek mythology, [[Clio]] is the [[muse]] of history. [[Dynamics (mechanics)|Dynamics]], most broadly, is the study of how and why phenomena change with time.{{sfn|Parry|2013}}\n\n==Origins==\nThe term was originally coined by [[Peter Turchin]] in 2003,{{sfn|Orf|2013}} and can be traced to the work of such figures as [[Ibn Khaldun]]{{sfn|Tainter|2004|p=488}} [[Alexandre Deulofeu]], [[Jack Goldstone]], [[Sergey Kapitsa]], [[Randall Collins]], [[John Komlos]], and [[Andrey Korotayev]].\n\n==Mathematical modeling of historical dynamics==\n\n[[File:Http mikebert.neocities.org Amer-sec-cycles.gif|thumb|Cliodynamics attempts to analyze historical trends from sociological data.]]\nMany historical processes are dynamic (a dynamic process is one that changes with time). [[Population]]s increase and decline, economies expand and contract, states grow and collapse. A very common approach, which has proved its worth in innumerable applications (particularly, but not exclusively, in the [[natural sciences]]), consists of taking a holistic phenomenon and splitting it up into separate parts that are assumed to interact with each other. This is the [[dynamical systems|dynamical systems approach]], because the whole phenomenon is represented as a [[system]] consisting of several elements (or [[subsystem]]s) that interact and change dynamically; that is, over time. In the dynamical systems approach, one sets out explicitly with mathematical formulae how different subsystems interact with each other. This mathematical description is the model of the system, and one can use a variety of methods to study the [[Dynamics (mechanics)|dynamics]] predicted by the model, as well as attempt to test the model by comparing its predictions with observed [[Empirical evidence|empirical]], dynamic evidence. Cliodynamics is the application of this same approach to the [[social sciences]] in general and to the study of historical dynamics in particular.\n\nCliodynamics practitioners apply [[mathematical model]]s to explain [[macrohistory|macrohistorical]] patterns \u2013 things like the rise of [[empire]]s, social discontent, [[civil war]]s, and [[Failed state|state collapse]].{{sfn|Spinney|2012}}{{sfn|Seabright|2004|p=806-7}}{{sfn|Keen|Owen|2017}} Although the focus is usually on the dynamics of large conglomerates of people, the approach of cliodynamics does not preclude the inclusion of human agency in its explanatory theories. Such questions can be explored with agent-based computer simulations.\n\n==Databases and data sources==\nCliodynamics relies on large bodies of evidence to test competing theories on a wide range of historical processes. This typically involves building massive stores of evidence.{{sfn|Spinney|2016}} The rise of [[digital history]] and various research technologies have allowed huge databases to be constructed in recent years. Some prominent databases utilized by cliodynamics practitioners include the following:\n* The [[Seshat (project)|Seshat: Global History Databank]], which systematically collects state-of-the-art accounts of the political and social organization of human groups and how societies have evolved through time into an authoritative databank.{{sfn|Turchin|Brennan|Currie|Feeney|2015}} Seshat is affiliated also with the [[Evolution Institute]], a non-profit think-tank that \"uses evolutionary science to solve real-world problems\".\n* D-PLACE: the Database of Places, Languages, Culture and Environment, which provides data on over 1,400 human social formations{{sfn|Kirby|Gray|Greenhill|Jordan|2016}}\n* The Atlas of Cultural Evolution, an archaeological database created by [[Peter N. Peregrine]]{{sfn|Peregrine|2003}}\n* CHIA: The Collaborative Information for Historical Analysis, a multidisciplinary collaborative endeavor hosted by the [[University of Pittsburgh]] with the goal of archiving historical information and linking data as well as academic/research institutions around the globe<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chia.pitt.edu/ |title=CHIA: The Collaborative Information for Historical Analysis |website=www.chia.pitt.edu}}</ref>\n* International Institute of Social History, which collects data on the global social history of labour relations, workers, and labour<ref>{{cite web |url=https://socialhistory.org/en/research/specials/about-iish-research-programme |title=International Institute of Social History |website=socialhistory.org}}</ref>\n* [[Human Relations Area Files]] eHRAF Archaeology<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yale.edu/hraf/archaeology.htm|publisher=[[Human Relations Area Files]]| title=eHRAF Archaeology |website=www.yale.edu}}</ref>\n* Human Relations Area Files eHRAF World Cultures<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ehrafworldcultures.yale.edu/ehrafe/|publisher=[[Human Relations Area Files]]| title=eHRAF World Cultures |website=www.yale.edu}}</ref>\n* Clio-Infra, a database of measures of economic performance and other aspects of societal well-being on a global sample of societies from 1800 CE to the present<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.clio-infra.eu/ |title=Clio-Infra |website=www.clio-infra.eu}}</ref>\n* The [[Google Ngram Viewer]], an online search engine that charts frequencies of sets of comma-delimited search strings using a yearly count of n-grams as found in the largest online body of human knowledge, the [[Google Books]] corpus.\n\n==Research==\nAs of 2016, the main directions of academic study in cliodynamics are:\n* The coevolutionary model of [[social complexity]] and warfare, based on the theoretical framework of cultural [[Multilevel selection#Multilevel selection theory|multilevel selection]]{{sfn|Turchin|2003}}{{sfn|Turchin|2005}}{{sfn|Turchin|2009}}{{sfn|Turchin|2011}}{{sfn|Koyama|2016}}\n* The study of revolutions and rebellions{{sfn|Goldstone|1991}}{{sfn|Turchin|2003}}{{sfn|Turchin|2005}}\n* [[Structural-demographic theory]] and secular cycles{{sfn|Turchin|Nefedov|2009}}{{sfn|Korotayev|Malkov|Khaltourina|2006b}}{{sfn|Korotayev|Khaltourina|2006}}{{sfn|Greby|2016}}{{sfn|Zeigler|2010}}{{sfn|Graber|2008}}\n* Explanations of the global distribution of languages benefitted from the empirical finding that the geographic area in which a language is spoken is more closely associated with the political complexity of the speakers than with all other variables under analysis.{{sfn|Currie|Mace|2009}}\n* [[mathematical modeling]] of the long-term (\"millennial\") trends of [[World-systems theory|world-systems analysis]],{{sfn|Tsirel|2004}}{{sfn|Korotayev|Malkov|Khaltourina|2006a}}{{sfn|Korotayev|2006|p=44-62 etc.}}\n* structural-demographic models of the [[Modern Age]] revolutions, including the Arab revolutions of 2011.{{sfn|Korotayev|Zinkina|2011}}\n* The analysis of vast quantities of historical newspaper content has been pioneered by,{{sfn|Dzogang|Lansdall-Welfare|FindMyPast Newspaper Team|Cristianini|2016}}{{sfn|Burkhart|2016}} which showed how periodic structures can be automatically discovered in historical newspapers. A similar analysis was performed on social media, again revealing strongly periodic structures.{{sfn|Dzogang|Lansdall-Welfare|Cristianini|2016}}\n\nThere are several established venues of peer reviewed cliodynamics research: \n* ''[[Cliodynamics_(journal)|Cliodynamics: The Journal of Quantitative History and Cultural Evolution]]''<ref>[http://escholarship.org/uc/irows_cliodynamics ''Cliodynamics: The Journal of Quantitative History and Cultural Evolution'']</ref> is a peer-reviewed web-based (open-access) journal that publishes on the transdisciplinary area of cliodynamics. It seeks to integrate historical models with data to facilitate theoretical progress. The first issue was published in December 2010. Cliodynamics is a member of [[Scopus]] and the [[Directory of Open Access Journals]] (DOAJ).\n* The [[University of Hertfordshire]]'s Cliodynamics Lab<ref>[http://www.herts.ac.uk/digital-history/cliodynamics-lab ''The University of Hertfordshire's Cliodynamics Lab'']</ref> is the first lab in the world dedicated explicitly to the new research area of cliodynamics. It is directed by Pieter Fran\u00e7ois, who founded the Lab in 2015.\n* The [[Santa Fe Institute]]<ref>[http://www.santafe.edu/ Santa Fe Institute]</ref> is a private, not-for-profit research and education center where leading scientists grapple with compelling and complex problems. The institute supports work in complex modeling of networks and dynamical systems. One of the areas of SFI research is cliodynamics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.santafe.edu/news-center/news/cliodynamics-special-issue |title=History as Science:Journal for theoretical & mathematical history features 5 papers by SFI authors |website=www.santafe.edu}}</ref> In the past the institute has sponsored a series of conversations and meetings on theoretical history.<ref>For example, {{cite journal |url=http://escholarship.org/uc/search?entity=irows_cliodynamics;volume=2;issue=1 |title=An Inquiry into History, Big History, and Metahistory |website=www.santafe.edu}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nCritics of the cliodynamic approach often argue that the complex social formations of the past cannot and should not be reduced to quantifiable, analyzable 'data points', for doing so overlooks each historical society's peculiar circumstances and dynamics.{{sfn|Zhao|2006|p=309\u2013310}}{{sfn|Lange|2012}}{{sfn|Tainter|2004|p=488\u2013489}} Many historians and social scientists contend that there are no generalizable causal factors that can explain large numbers of cases, but that historical investigation should focus on the unique trajectories of each case, highlighting commonalities in outcomes where they exist. As Zhao notes, \"most historians believe that the importance of any mechanisms in history changes, and more important, there is no time-invariant structure that can organize all the historical mechanisms into a system\".{{sfn|Zhao|2006|p=309\u2013310}}{{sfn|Lange|2012}} Cliodynamicists, on the other hand, contend that there are large-scale, macrohistorical patterns that can explain the historical dynamics of the majority of known cases, and that these patterns can be uncovered through systematic, mathematical analysis. They argue that the ability of cliodynamics research to expose these patterns and to explain historical events demonstrates the feasibility of the approach.{{sfn|Turchin|2008}}\n\n==Fiction==\n[[Isaac Asimov]] employed a fictional version of this discipline, what he called [[Psychohistory (fictional)|psychohistory]], as a major [[plot device]] in his [[Foundation series|Foundation]] series of science fiction novels.<ref>Finley, Klint. 2013. [https://www.wired.com/2013/04/cliodynamics-peter-turchin/ \"Mathematicians Predict The Future With Data from the Past.\"] ''Wired''.</ref> Psychohistory differs from cliodynamics in its attempt to connect individuals directly to societal dynamics. In contrast, cliodynamics analyses societies as groups of individuals nested within ever-larger groups, ultimately and indirectly comprising a society.{{sfn|Turchin|2015}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Generations (book)|''Generations'' (book)]]\n* [[Historical geographic information system]]\n* [[Sociocultural evolution]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n* Burkhart, Richard H. 2016. [https://sinews.siam.org/Details-Page/applied-mathematics-and-political-crises-1 \"Applied Mathematics and Political Crises\".] ''Siam News''.\n* {{cite journal |last=Currie |first=Thomas E. |last2=Mace |first2=Ruth |date=2009 |title=Political complexity predicts the spread of ethnolinguistic groups |journal=PNAS |volume=106 |issue=18 |pages=7339\u20137344 |doi=10.1073/pnas.0804698106 |pmid=19380740 |pmc=2670878 |bibcode=2009PNAS..106.7339C |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite journal |last=Dzogang |first=Fabon |last2=Lansdall-Welfare |first2=Thomas |author3=FindMyPast Newspaper Team |last4=Cristianini |first4=Nello |date=2016-11-08 |title=Discovering Periodic Patterns in Historical News |journal=PLOS One |volume=11 |issue=11 |pages=e0165736 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0165736 |issn=1932-6203 |pmc=5100883 |pmid=27824911 |bibcode=2016PLoSO..1165736D |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |vauthors=Dzogang F, Lansdall-Welfare T, Cristianini N |year=2016 |chapter=Seasonal Fluctuations in Collective Mood Revealed by Wikipedia Searches and Twitter Posts |title=Proceedings of the 2016 IEEE international conference on data mining workshop (SENTIRE), Barcelona |p=12\u201315 |chapter-url=http://sentic.net/sentire2016cristianini.pdf |ref=harv}}\n* Finley, Klint. 2013. [https://www.wired.com/2013/04/cliodynamics-peter-turchin/ \"Mathematicians Predict The Future With Data from the Past.\"] ''Wired''.\n* [[Jack Goldstone|Goldstone J.]] 1991. ''Revolution and Rebellion in the Early Modern World''. Berkeley, California: University of California Press.\n* {{cite journal |last=Graber |first=Robert B. |year=2008 |url=https://www.sociostudies.org/journal/articles/140571/ |title=Review of Andrey Korotayev, Artemy Malkov, and Darkia Khaltourina, Introduction to Social Macrodynamics (Three Volumes) |journal=Journal of Social Evolution and History |volume=7 |issue=2 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite magazine |last=Greby |first=James |date=2016 |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/23750-cliodynamics-america-cycle-of-violence-donald-trump |title='Cliodynamics' Research Proves American Freaks Out Every 50 Years |magazine=Inverse |ref=harv}}\n* Keen, Steven, and Charles Owen. 2017.[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ajrWM6RSWBc&t=47m18s \"The Value of Everything: E120. Professor Steve Keen Interview.\"] The Future of Money (segment starts at 47:18)\n* {{cite journal |last1=Kirby |first1=Kathryn R. |last2=Gray |first2=Russell D. |last3=Greenhill |first3=Simon J. |last4=Jordan |first4=Fiona M. |last5=Gomes-Ng |first5=Stephanie |last6=Bibiko |first6=Hans-J\u00f6rg |last7=Blasi |first7=Dami\u00e1n E. |last8=Botero |first8=Carlos A. |last9=Bowern |first9=Claire |last10=Ember |first10=Carol R. |last11=Leehr |first11=Dan |last12=Low |first12=Bobbi S. |last13=McCarter |first13=Joe |last14=Divale |first14=William |title=D-PLACE: A Global Database of Cultural, Linguistic and Environmental Diversity |journal=PLOS One |date=2016 |volume=11 |issue=7 |pages=e0158391 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0158391 |pmid=27391016 |pmc=4938595 |bibcode=2016PLoSO..1158391K |ref=harv}}\n* [[John Komlos|Komlos]] J., Nefedov S. 2002. Compact Macromodel of Pre-Industrial Population Growth. ''Historical Methods''. (35): 92\u201394.\n* {{cite book |last=Korotayev |first=Andrey V. |chapter-url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=1703534 |chapter=The World System urbanization dynamics |p=44\u201362 |editor-last=Turchin |editor-first=Peter |editor-last2=Grinin |editor-first2=Leonid Efimovich |editor-last3=Korotayev 