: Journal of Comparative and Cross-Cultural Research |volume=14 |issue=1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Schrodt |first=Philip A. |title=Historical Dynamics: Why States Rise and FallHistorical Dynamics: Why States Rise and Fall by Peter Turchin |journal=Contemporary Sociology: A Journal of Reviews |volume=34 |issue=2 |year=2005 |issn=0094-3061 |doi=10.1177/009430610503400268 |pages=213\u2013215 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Seabright |first=Paul |title=Book Review: Historical Dynamics: Why States Rise and Fall by Peter Turchin |journal=The Economics of Transition |volume=12 |issue=4 |year=2004 |issn=0967-0750 |doi=10.1111/j.0967-0750.2004.00203.x |pages=801\u2013809 |ref=harv}}\n* Spinney, Laura. 2012 [http://www.nature.com/news/human-cycles-history-as-science-1.11078 \"Human cycles: History as Science.\"] ''Nature''.\n* Spinney, Laura. 2016. [https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg23230950-600-the-database-that-is-rewriting-history-to-predict-the-future/ \"The database that is rewriting history to predict the future.\"] ''New Scientist''.\n* Sussan, Remi. 2013. [http://www.internetactu.net/2013/04/17/au-coeur-de-la-cliodynamique-12-les-cycles-historiques/ \"Au coeur de la cliodynamique (1/2): les cycles historiques\"]. ''Internet Actu''.\n* {{cite journal |last=Tainter |first=Joseph A. |year=2004 |url=https://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v427/n6974/pdf/427488a.pdf |title=Plotting the downfall of society: Review of Historical Dynamics: Why States Rise and Fall by Peter Turchin |journal=Nature |volume=427 |issue=6974 |pages=488\u2013489 |ref=harv|doi=10.1038/427488a }}\n* {{anchor|{{sfnref|Tsirel|2004}}}}Tsirel, S. V. 2004. On the Possible Reasons for the Hyperexponential Growth of the Earth Population. ''Mathematical Modeling of Social and Economic Dynamics'' / Ed. by M. G. Dmitriev and A. P. Petrov, pp.&nbsp;367\u20139. Moscow: Russian State Social University, 2004.\n* {{cite book |authorlink=Peter Turchin |last=Turchin |first=P. |year=2003 |url=http://cliodynamics.ru/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=123&Itemid=70 |title=Historical Dynamics: Why States Rise and Fall |location=Princeton, NJ |publisher=Princeton University Press |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |authorlink=Peter Turchin |last=Turchin |first=P. |year=2005 |title=War and Peace and War |publisher=Plume |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1 = Turchin |first1 = P. |authorlink = Peter Turchin |year = 2009 |title = A theory for formation of large states |url = http://peterturchin.com/PDF/Turchin_JGH_2009.pdf |journal = Journal of Global History |volume = 4 |issue = 2|pages = 191\u2013217 |doi=10.1017/s174002280900312x |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1 = Turchin |first1 = P. |authorlink = Peter Turchin |year = 2011 |title = Warfare and the Evolution of Social Complexity: A Multilevel-Selection Approach |url = http://escholarship.org/uc/item/7j11945r |journal = Structure and Dynamics |volume = 4 |issue = 3 |pages = 1\u201337 |ref=harv}}\n* [[Peter Turchin|Turchin P.]] 2006. [http://peterturchin.com/PDF/Turchin_Korotayev_SEH_2006.pdf Population Dynamics and Internal Warfare: A Reconsideration]. ''[[Social Evolution & History]]'' 5(2): 112\u2013147 (with [[Andrey Korotayev]]).\n* {{cite book |editor-last=Turchin |editor-first=Peter |editor-last2=Grinin |editor-first2=Leonid Efimovich |editor-last3=Korotayev |editor-first3=Andrey V. |editor-last4=de Munck |editor-first4=Victor C. |title=History & mathematics: Historical dynamics and development of complex societies |series=History & mathematics |location=Moscow |publisher=KomKniga/URSS |year=2006 |isbn=978-5-484-01002-8 |url=http://urss.ru/cgi-bin/db.pl?page=Book&id=53185&lang=en&blang=en |ref=harv}} (on [https://books.google.com/books?id=iX-TlWlnC3IC Google Books])\n* {{cite journal |last=Turchin |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Turchin |title=Arise 'cliodynamics' |journal=Nature |volume=454 |issue=7200 |date=<!--3 July--> 2008 |issn=0028-0836 |doi=10.1038/454034a |pmid=18596791 |bibcode=2008Natur.454...34T |pages=34\u201335 |url=https://www.sott.net/article/161508-Transforming-history-into-science-Arise-cliodynamics |ref=harv}}\n* [[Peter Turchin|Turchin P.]], Nefedov S. 2009. ''Secular Cycles.'' Princeton, NJ: Princeton University Press.\n* {{cite journal |last1=Turchin |first1=Peter |last2=Brennan |first2=Rob |last3=Currie |first3=Thomas E. |last4=Feeney |first4=Kevin C. |last5=Francois |first5=Pieter |last6=Hoyer |first6=Daniel |last7=Manning |first7=Joseph G. |last8=Marciniak |first8=Arkadiusz |last9=Mullins |first9=Daniel |last10=Palmisano |first10=Alessio |last11=Peregrine |first11=Peter |last12=Turner |first12=Edward A. L. |last13=Whitehouse |first13=Harvey |date=<!--4 July--> 2015 |title=Seshat: The Global History Databank |journal=Cliodynamics: The Journal of Quantitative History and Cultural Evolution |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=77\u2013107 |issn=2373-7530 |doi=10.21237/c7clio6127917 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Turchin |first=Peter |date=2015 |title=Ultrasociety: How 10,000 Years of War Made Humans the Greatest Cooperators on Earth |url= |location= |publisher=Beresta Books |page= |isbn=978-0996139519 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Zeigler |first=Donald |year=2010 |jstor=41887467 |title=Book Review: Secular Cycles by Peter Turchin, Sergey A. Nefedov |journal=International Social Science Review |volume=85 |issue=3/4 |pages=165\u2013166 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Zhao |first=Dingxin |title=Historical Dynamics: Why States Rise and Fall. By Peter Turchin |journal=American Journal of Sociology |volume=112 |issue=1 |year=2006 |issn=0002-9602 |doi=10.1086/507802 |pages=308\u2013310 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Library resources box}}\n\n*[https://escholarship.org/uc/irows_cliodynamics Cliodynamics: The Journal of Quantitative History and Cultural Evolutio]\n*[http://seshatdatabank.info/ Seshat: Global History Databank] \n*[http://peterturchin.com/cliodynamics/ Peter Turchin's Cliodynamics Page]\n* [http://cliodynamics.ru/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=133&Itemid=70 Why do we need mathematical models of historical processes?]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110217151303/http://www.oeaw.ac.at/byzanz/historicaldynamics.htm Historical Dynamics in a time of Crisis: Late Byzantium, 1204-1453 (a discussion of some concepts of cliodynamics from the point of view of medieval studies)]\n* [http://www.nature.com/news/human-cycles-history-as-science-1.11078 \"Nature\" article (August 2012): Human cycles: History as science]\n*[https://evolution-institute.org/ Evolution Institute]\n\n[[Category:Dynamical systems]]\n[[Category:Econometric modeling]]\n[[Category:Economic history studies]]\n[[Category:Social history]]\n[[Category:Theories of history]]\n", "name_user": "Jsaiya", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cliodynamics"}
{"title_page": "St. Leon (novel)", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=September 2012}}\n{{Italic title}}\n[[Image:GodwinStLeon.jpg|right|thumb|Title page from the first edition of ''St. Leon'']]\n'''''St. Leon: A Tale of the Sixteenth Century''''' (1799) is eighteenth-century British philosopher [[William Godwin|William Godwin's]] second novel.\n\nFollowing the success of ''[[Things as They Are; or, The Adventures of Caleb Williams]]'' (1794), Godwin searched for a topic that would capture his imagination as much as his earlier work. ''St. Leon'' is the tale of a French aristocrat, Count Reginald de St. Leon, who loses his wealth gambling and experiences guilt that drives him almost to madness. He accepts the secret of the elixir of life and of the power of multiplying wealth from a dying stranger, ultimately causing him to wander separated from humankind.\n\n==Plot==\n\nCount Reginald narrates the story of his life, beginning with the death of his father when he was an infant. He was brought up by his mother, \"a woman of rather a masculine understanding, and full of the prejudices of nobility and magnificence.\"<ref>William Godwin. St. Leon: A Tale of the Sixteenth Century, ed. William D. Brewer (Peterborough, Ontario: Broadview, 2006), 55.</ref> \n\nReginald has grand notions of aristocratic honour, and, inspired by his uncle, the Marquis de Villeroy, he joins the Italian war of 1521\u20136, hoping to achieve military renown in the battle of [[Pavia]]. Reginald is knighted by King [[Francis I of France|Francis I]], while fighting for the French against the Spanish Imperial army, but the King is captured and imprisoned by [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]]. The King's exile changes the climate in France from one in which \"the activity of the field\" is exchanged \"for the indulgences of the table.\" <ref>Godwin, 75.</ref> \n\nOn his return home, Reginald, now twenty years old is forced by the death of his mother to take charge of his own affairs. He is quickly led astray by a life of spending too much, keeping mistresses, and gambling. He lives like this for two years and quickly depletes his fortune. He meets the beautiful and accomplished nineteen-year-old Marguerite Louise Isabeau de Damville, whose education has benefited from the society of [[Clement Marot]], [[Rabelais]], [[Erasmus]], and [[Scaliger]], and whose drawing has been encouraged by [[Leonardo da Vinci]]. Reginald courts Marguerite, who is the daughter of the Marquis de Damville, but Reginald's reputation as a gambler causes the Marquis to warn him that he should be careful not to ruin himself and his daughter. The Marquis allows them to marry, but by the time he is in his thirties, Reginald is living beyond his means and has returned to gambling. The Marquis does not live to see this development. \n\nMarguerite moves their family to Switzerland and pays off her husband's debts by selling their possessions. She tries to convince him that the simpler life of a peasant will make the whole family happier and more virtuous. However, while they are beginning their farming life, their crops and animals are unexpectedly destroyed in a fierce storm. Disturbed by the sight of a dead woman and child, Reginald realizes he is fortunate when he returns home to find his family is safe. He dismisses his former love of money and rank. Seeing the casualties of a fierce storm reveals to him that his new life as a subsistence farmer is more valuable than he imagined, but that it is a life subject to the precarious whims of fortune. This development gives Godwin scope to expatiate on the Swiss system of storing corn in public reserves in case of natural disasters. \n\nReginald applies for national relief and a disbursement from the public treasury to enable him to restock his farm. But relief is refused on the grounds that he is not Swiss. Government officials are sent to remove the family from the country altogether without giving them time to sell their cottage. A compassionate neighbour lends them money against the house and they leave for [[Lake Constance]]. The neighbour dies, and his estate passes to a relative, Monsieur Grimseld, who steals their house. Reginald risks imprisonment to return to Switzerland to reclaim his cottage as his family are beginning to starve. Grimseld is fined for fraud, and Reginald is given the money for his farm.\n\nVolume 2 begins in the year 1544. An old man arrives at the family's house at Lake Constance, claiming to be a Venetian called Francesco Zampieri, but his true identity remains a mystery. He is being pursued by the Inquisition. Zampieri reveals to Reginald the secret of immortality and the art of multiplying gold. Only one person is permitted to know these secrets at any one time. The secret of immortality is an [[elixir of life|elixir]] made from herbs that when consumed bring youth and vigour. It cures sickness, but cannot save anyone from injury. Reluctant to keep a secret from his wife, Reginald is forced to remain silent about the gift and Zampieri dies shortly afterwards. \n\n[[Francis I of France|Francis I]] returns to France from his imprisonment in Spain, finding the country in a great upheaval, with [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] and [[Henry VIII]] in the process of invading northern France. Unwilling to return to his simple domestic life, Reginald plans to repurchase the estate that he lost, but in order to make it seem like he has regained his wealth gradually and not in suspicious circumstances, he moves to the city of [[Konstanz|Constance]] and pretends that Zampieri had given him 3,000 crowns. Constance is in the process of becoming Protestant. \n\nReginald is quickly seduced into spending a great deal of money and arouses the suspicion of his countryman, [[Gaspard II de Coligny|Gaspard de Coligny]]. Reginald's son, Charles, becomes aware of the shame that wealth with an inexplicable origin has brought and disowns his father and leaves. Marguerite is also suspicious and guesses that he has found the [[Philosopher's Stone]]. Reginald tells her not to reveal this and not to enquire further about it. She is ill, but as the elixir can only be drunk by an \"adept\", he cannot give it to her. \n\nThe suspicions about Reginald's wealth grow to such a height that the magistrate has him arrested and questioned. He is asked about the disappearance of the stranger and about his new wealth, but refuses to cooperate. Monsieur Monluc, a Frenchman, arrives, and Reginald appeals to him for help. Monluc investigates the case, interviews Marguerite. Reginald tells him the honorable name of St. Leon which removes the necessity for an explanation and he does not provide a reason. Monluc refuses to help him further. \n\nMarguerite advises Reginald to escape from the prison. He attempts to bribe a turnkey, Hector, but he refuses to help because he is loyal to the keeper and he reveals this to the keeper. The keeper asks for a bribe. Reginald hands over a large sum but is led to a dungeon instead and chained to a wall. Hector is imprisoned because he is the only person who knows about the bribe. The keeper asks for more money, and Reginald is forced to trust him, and this time he is released provided he takes Hector with him in order to make the latter appear to be an accomplice.\n\nIn volume 3, Reginald, his family, and Hector set out for Italy. One evening, while Hector and Reginald are taking an evening walk while the family are at an inn in the Alps, Reginald hears a man shrieking and is attacked by a large black dog. The dog takes him to a man who is wounded and dying. Reginald and Hector dress his wounds, and Hector runs back to the inn to get help. \n\nThe man's name is Andrea Filosanto. He had been taking his mother's dower to her and was robbed. He dies, and the dog grieves for him. Reginald takes the dog, Charon, into his family. A few months later, the dog finds the assailant, who is apprehended, confesses to being one of the robbers, is tried, convicted, and executed. \n\nReginald settles in [[Pisa]], and is protected by the Filosanto family and the family of the woman Andrea was about to marry, the Carracciuoli, who are powerful in the Pisan territory. Reginald spends some time practicing alchemy in a grotto, employing Hector as an assistant. Hector tells his girlfriend about the experiments, and Reginald quickly gains the reputation of being a sorcerer. His girlfriend's other lover, Agostino, is jealous and seeks revenge. \n\nReginald is shunned, and someone shoots at their house at night. The dog is killed, and Hector is attacked. The attack is motivated by the suspicions about magic and by Hector's being of African origin. Reginald addresses the mob in an attempt to vindicate himself, but they throw mud at him and accuse him of witchcraft. \n\nHe leaves to consult with the Marchese Filosanto, and the rest of the family leave for [[Lucca]], heading for Spain. They leave Hector in charge of their house in Pisa. When Reginald goes back to Pisa, he finds that the mob have burned his house down, that Hector has gone mad and has escaped his carers and has died defending the house. Hector was tortured by the mob, and it is clear that the crime is racially motivated. \n\nMarguerite has a miscarriage in Lucca. The family continue to Spain, and Marguerite dies in [[Barcelona]]. Distraught, the family continues to Madrid. Here, the daughters are looked after by Mariana, a former companion of their mother's. Reginald repurchases his family's French estate, and he gradually separates himself from his children, considering this to be a virtuous action. They are told to think and speak of him as if he were dead. The family still do not know the whereabouts of Charles. \n\nReginald moves to [[Madrid]] and spends time studying natural philosophy and ethics. He is followed by two men, who are eventually revealed to be informers for the Inquisition. He is arrested and imprisoned for sorcery. [[Philip II of Spain|Philip II]] returns to Spain after his marriage to [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]], and he oversees an [[auto da F\u00e9]] in Seville. Philip then travels to [[Valladolid]] for another [[auto da F\u00e9]], at which Reginald is to be burned alive. The elixir of life cannot protect him from this punishment. \n\nWhile processing to Valladolid from Madrid, a horse is frightened and kicks, and in the confusion, Reginald escapes and breaks into the house of a Jewish convert to Christianity, Mordecai. Just as he had appealed to the turnkey as a member of an oppressed minority, so Reginald appeals to Mordecai to help him escape the [[Inquisition]]. Mordecai helps him change his clothes and fetches the herbs needed for the elixir of immortality. Reginald, how has visibly aged such that he looks like a man of eighty. He drinks the elixir and becomes as young and healthy as he was on his wedding day. He leaves without Mordecai's knowledge. During his escape, Reginald accidentally witnesses the auto da f\u00e9 and is horrified.\n\nAt the beginning of volume 4, Reginald visits his daughters disguised as an Armenian merchant. He has now been away from them for twelve years. Louisa is 28, Marguerite is 24 {{Disputed inline|Talk page section|date=February 2020}}, and Julia died four years previously after her fianc\u00e9 had been imprisoned by his father for intending to marry her. Reginald pretends to have known their father and informs them of his own death. He hopes that the death certificate that he gives them will remove the dishonour from his family. \n\nReginald leaves for Hungary and takes a house in [[Buda]], intending to use his money to revitalize the economy after the devastation of a long war. He gives charity to poor people, becomes a corn-dealer and an architect, and takes a new name: \"the sieur de Chatillon\" (p.&nbsp;366). Problems occur, however, when demand for corn becomes too great and the people suspect him of manipulating the market for personal gain. \n\nReginald presents himself to the Turkish Pasha of Buda, Muzaffer Bey. But Bey blames him for causing civil unrest and investigates the unknown origins of Reginald's wealth. Reginald is forced to bribe him. He then meets Bethlem Gabor, a misanthropic arms dealer, and a native of [[Hungary]], whose wife and children have been murdered. Like Reginald, Bethlem spends a great deal of time wandering, and they share their sorrows and become friends. \n\nThe civil unrest eases as the crops that Reginald has ordered to be sown are ripening and are being successfully protected by soldiers. Three months have passed since Reginald first became acquainted with Bethlem. After expecting to meet him while travelling, Reginald is captured by Austro-Hungarian freebooters. He escapes and finds Bethlem, but without warning, Bethlem takes him to one of his castles and puts him in the dungeon. Reginald is left without food for thirty-six hours, and then he is given food and chained to a wall. \n\nBethlem gives as his reason for his hostility: that Reginald had helped an enemy of his, unknowingly, and that although he and Reginald had suffered the same loss of their families, Reginald had reacted to it by being kind to a great number of people and Bethlem had done the reverse. Bethlem feels shamed by this. Reginald tries to pay Bethlem to let him go, and requests a chest from his house. Bethlem opens the chest and discovers that it contains alchemical equipment. He demands gold, making it clear that he intends to keep Reginald locked up forever in order to supply it. \n\nIn the dungeon Reginald dreams that he is rescued by a knight in armour, who turns into a female angel, and that they fly away together leaving the castle in flames. Something close to this vision comes true. Bethlem visits Reginald's cell to tell him that the castle is under siege, and that he is experiencing remorse for keeping him captive. Bethlem gives Reginald the means to escape, making him promise not to do so for twenty-four hours. Reginald waits six hours, justifying his inability to keep his promise with the argument that it was extorted under duress. He spends two hours trying to get out of the caverns, but finds that the aids he left on the walls on his way in are no longer helpful. \n\nHe hears a loud shout and is startled, and concludes that he is near the outside. But a large amount of smoke convinces him to wait before he attempts to leave and he returns to the dungeons risking suffocation. He hides in a different cell from the one to which he was confined in case Bethlem returns. Eventually, Reginald leaves the castle in ruins and approaches some soldiers. He immediately recognizes his son Charles, who has changed his surname to de Damville. Charles is now thirty-two. Ruminating over what has happened, Reginald cannot account for Bethlem's hostile actions or his remorse and he forgives him. Charles does not recognize his father, who appears to be twenty-two, even though the other soldiers notice their similarity. \n\nIntending not to disgrace his son, Reginald adopts the name Henry d'Aubigny. Charles and Reginald quickly become friends, and Charles reveals his history. He is fighting the Turks, and prefers not to fight in the wars between Protestants and Catholics. He is also in search of Chatillon because of his known friendship with Bethlem Gabor. Reginald does not reveal that he is Chatillon. Charles recounts that he fought with General Castaldo in the [[battle of Muhlberg]] in 1547, whom he served for seven years. He recalls the siege of Erlau ([[Eger]], Hungary) and notes the bravery of the women of the city, and the siege of Ziget ([[Sisak]] in Croatia). Ziget was governed by Horvati, a Christian, and was besieged by the Turkish [[Pasha]] of Buda. \n\nThe Pasha lost the siege and died of grief and mortification. While Charles sympathizes a great deal with his son and is proud of his achievements, he regards his role as a Christian warrior as religious fanaticism. Charles has fallen in love with Pandora, the niece of the palatine of Hungary, Nadasti, whom he first met when she was fourteen. Pandora's father died in the siege of Ziget, leaving her a poor orphan and Nadasti prefers Charles to marry one of his own daughters. Charles realizes that he cannot support a wife on his pay, and he needs the uncle's consent. Reginald sees Pandora and is struck by her beauty, good sense and naturalness. He is determined to use his wealth to enable them to marry, but needs to find a way to make it seem appropriate. Reginald discovers that Pandora's mother had been a Venetian, and that her mother's uncle sailed with the Spanish explorer [[Francisco Pizarro]] to conquer [[Peru]]. Her uncle having died during the mission, he did not receive a portion of the treasure. Pandora being his sole surviving relative would have inherited this treasure. \n\nReginald finds, by chance, a man who had sailed on the same ship, Benedetto Cabriera, who has lost all of his money due to a series of calamities. Reginald pays him to pretend that Pandora's uncle had received his share, and that it had been bequeathed to her. While waiting for Benedetto to appear with the money in Hungary, Reginald learns that Charles has rejected Pandora because he thinks, incorrectly, that she is in love with Reginald and is an \u2018unfeeling coquette\u2019. Pandora explains to Reginald that they must no longer see each other, and is interrupted by Charles's arrival, faints and is caught by Reginald increasing Charles's suspicions. Charles remonstrates with them both and leaves them speechless. \n\nReginald yearns to tell his son the truth about his identity and learns his greatest lesson about solitude: more than a dungeon, solitude is alienation from your child. Reginald leaves for [[Presburg]] and meets Charles, who is on his way to accompany Mary, Queen of Scots back to her native land. Charles confronts his father with a letter from Andrew, Count of Bathori, accusing Reginald of being Chatillon and an alchemist. He tells Reginald that he lost his father to alchemy and challenges Reginald to a duel. Reginald agrees, but leaves Presburg before the appointed time. \n\nCharles and Pandora are reconciled, and the remainder of Reginald's story is devoted to tracing the development of Charles's virtues and to expressing his own regret at realizing the importance of his family too late.\n\n==Themes==\n\nThe novel explores the themes of immortality, the domestic affections (love and friendship), honour, and religion. Into a historical novel of vast range and violence Godwin melds elements of the domestic novel, the philosophical novel, and fantasy. More so than the earlier ''[[Things as They Are; or, The Adventures of Caleb Williams|Caleb Williams]]'', this novel tests Godwin's philosophical premises, showing the tensions between the aspiration to greatness and family affections and the disintegration of effective social responsibility.\n\n===Money===\n\nThe novel deals with a range of issues connected with wealth. Firstly, it moralizes against gambling, viewing it as a waste of resources and a drain on the time of people who could be doing something more useful with their wealth. Secondly, it traces the effects of poverty, suggesting that there is a nobility in the simple life. While the peasant life is favoured, the novel emphasizes that education is also important, and so the aristocratic family who are living in reduced circumstances have the benefit of having developed their minds and of living in a way that does not oppress anyone. Thirdly, the novel reflects on the power of wealth. The ideas expressed in the novel follow those of Godwin's ''[[Enquiry Concerning Political Justice and its Influence on Modern Morals and Manners]]'' (1793). Reginald reflects that \"[w]eakness and want are the parents of vice\".<ref>Godwin, 187.</ref> When Reginald is finally in a position to put his new ability to multiply gold to good use, he secures the future of his daughters, and then travels to Buda to help stimulate the post-war economy with a building program. When he finds his son Charles, he is able to give his intended wife a dowry without them knowing it. Wherever Reginald goes, he confronts problems with appearing to have excessive wealth that comes from no discernible origin. Here Godwin addresses the topic of the surveillance society, the problem of secrecy, and the traditional motif of cursed gold.\n\n===Liberty and intolerance===\n\nThe novel asks the questions: what do we need in order to be truly free? And what is oppression? Reginald's lost money may appear to him to be a disaster, but his wife, Marguerite, philosophizes that its loss makes them less able to oppress people by engaging them as servants, and it makes them more free themselves. She argues that people who are educated and live the life of a peasant are the happiest because they do not reduce the people below them \u201cto a state of servitude\u201d and in turn become themselves enslaved to their own homes and lifestyle.<ref>Godwin, 124.</ref> Intolerance is further explored through the persecutions of the Inquisition. Both the stranger who gives Reginald the secrets and Reginald himself are pursued by the Inquisition for sorcery. At several points in the narrative, Godwin expatiates on the power and unthinking qualities of mob-like behavior. He also explores racial intolerance through the torture and murder of Hector, the African servant, and the fear expressed by Mordechai, the Spanish convert from Judaism to Christianity. Reginald appeals to both for help on the grounds that they have experienced the same kind of oppression as him. Godwin also devotes a great deal of time to exploring the difficulties of immigrants and refugees. The St. Leon family is displaced several times, and they learn that the \"prepossessions of mankind are clearly unfavourable to a newcomer, an emigrant who has quitted his former connections and the scenes of his youth. They are unavoidably impelled to believe, that his taking up his abode in another country must be owing to a weak and discreditable caprice, if it be not owing to something still more disadvantageous in his character.\"<ref>Godwin, 133.</ref>\n\n===Honour and merit===\n\nHonour and merit are central themes in ''[[Things as They Are; or, The Adventures of Caleb Williams|Caleb Williams]]''. Again, Godwin pits aristocratic reputation against intrinsic merit. Like Falkland, in ''Caleb Williams'', Reginald has been brought up to think of himself as worthy of admiration and homage. He learns that the \"value of a man is in his intrinsic qualities\" and that honour is not inherited, it must be earned and displayed in one's actions.<ref>Godwin, 130.</ref> While Godwin associates aristocratic honour with vanity and ostentation, there remains in the novel a sense in which honourable behaviour is valued insofar as it signals loyalty, equitable action, and acting in an open manner.\n\n===Gender===\n\nTo some extent the novel preserves traditional ideas about the differences between men and women. Women are commended for their beauty and men for their bravery. Marguerite, however, is presented as an exceptional woman in that she is unusually brave, rational, and independent. Marguerite suggests that as a wife she should be \"a human being and an equal\" and that this means that they should be open with each other. In accordance with Godwin's views in Political Justice, Reginald attacks what he regards as effeminacy in men, and in particular, men who are inactive or who are emotional or cowardly. Zampieri, the stranger, criticizes Reginald for arguing that he could not keep a secret from his wife, calling him \"[f]eeble and effeminate\" and \"the puppet of a woman\".<ref>Godwin, 157.</ref> Reginald agrees to keep the secret, but still holds that his wife and he are two halves of one soul and rightly fears that the secret will lead to an emotional separation.\n\n==Influence==\n\n''St. Leon'' influenced the Gothic novel ''[[St. Irvyne; or, The Rosicrucian]]'' (1811) by Godwin's future son-in-law [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]] and ''[[Frankenstein]]'' (1818), which was dedicated to Godwin, and written by his daughter [[Mary Shelley]].<ref>Mary Shelley. ''Frankenstein. The 1818 Text, Contexts, Nineteenth-Century Responses, Modern Criticism''. Ed. J. Paul Hunter. New York: Norton, 1996, 4.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=lSO63P-AnZAC&pg=PA486&lpg=PA486&dq=st+leon+william+godwin&source=web&ots=zJ9R3E_4EJ&sig=ME0PeGaZmjy8FBZuM3AsVkXWCsU&hl=en#PPP1,M1 ''St. Leon''] at [[Google Books]]\n* [https://archive.org/stream/stleontaleofsixt00godwuoft#page/n13/mode/2up ''St. Leon''] unedited version at The [[Internet Archive]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:1799 novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by William Godwin]]\n[[Category:English novels]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the Reformation]]\n[[Category:1790s fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Italy]]\n[[Category:Pisa in fiction]]\n[[Category:Novels set in France]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Budapest in fiction]]\n[[Category:Fictional alchemists]]\n[[Category:18th-century British novels]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=September 2012}}\n{{Italic title}}\n[[Image:GodwinStLeon.jpg|right|thumb|Title page from the first edition of ''St. Leon'']]\n'''''St. Leon: A Tale of the Sixteenth Century''''' (1799) is eighteenth-century British philosopher [[William Godwin|William Godwin's]] second novel.\n\nFollowing the success of ''[[Things as They Are; or, The Adventures of Caleb Williams]]'' (1794), Godwin searched for a topic that would capture his imagination as much as his earlier work. ''St. Leon'' is the tale of a French aristocrat, Count Reginald de St. Leon, who loses his wealth gambling and experiences guilt that drives him almost to madness. He accepts the secret of the elixir of life and of the power of multiplying wealth from a dying stranger, ultimately causing him to wander separated from humankind.\n\n==Plot==\n\nCount Reginald narrates the story of his life, beginning with the death of his father when he was an infant. He was brought up by his mother, \"a woman of rather a masculine understanding, and full of the prejudices of nobility and magnificence.\" <ref>William Godwin. St. Leon: A Tale of the Sixteenth Century, ed. William D. Brewer (Peterborough, Ontario: Broadview, 2006), 55.</ref> \n\nReginald has grand notions of aristocratic honour, and, inspired by his uncle, the Marquis de Villeroy, he joins the Italian war of 1521\u20136, hoping to achieve military renown in the battle of [[Pavia]]. Reginald is knighted by King [[Francis I of France|Francis I]], while fighting for the French against the Spanish Imperial army, but the King is captured and imprisoned by [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]]. The King's exile changes the climate in France from one in which \"the activity of the field\" is exchanged \"for the indulgences of the table.\" <ref>Godwin, 75.</ref> \n\nOn his return home, Reginald, now twenty years old is forced by the death of his mother to take charge of his own affairs. He is quickly led astray by a life of spending too much, keeping mistresses, and gambling. He lives like this for two years and quickly depletes his fortune. He meets the beautiful and accomplished nineteen-year-old Marguerite Louise Isabeau de Damville, whose education has benefited from the society of [[Clement Marot]], [[Rabelais]], [[Erasmus]], and [[Scaliger]], and whose drawing has been encouraged by [[Leonardo da Vinci]]. Reginald courts Marguerite, who is the daughter of the Marquis de Damville, but Reginald's reputation as a gambler causes the Marquis to warn him that he should be careful not to ruin himself and his daughter. The Marquis allows them to marry, but by the time he is in his thirties, Reginald is living beyond his means and has returned to gambling. The Marquis does not live to see this development. \n\nMarguerite moves their family to Switzerland and pays off her husband's debts by selling their possessions. She tries to convince him that the simpler life of a peasant will make the whole family happier and more virtuous. However, while they are beginning their farming life, their crops and animals are unexpectedly destroyed in a fierce storm. Disturbed by the sight of a dead woman and child, Reginald realizes he is fortunate when he returns home to find his family is safe. He dismisses his former love of money and rank. Seeing the casualties of a fierce storm reveals to him that his new life as a subsistence farmer is more valuable than he imagined, but that it is a life subject to the precarious whims of fortune. This development gives Godwin scope to expatiate on the Swiss system of storing corn in public reserves in case of natural disasters. \n\nReginald applies for national relief and a disbursement from the public treasury to enable him to restock his farm. But relief is refused on the grounds that he is not Swiss. Government officials are sent to remove the family from the country altogether without giving them time to sell their cottage. A compassionate neighbour lends them money against the house and they leave for [[Lake Constance]]. The neighbour dies, and his estate passes to a relative, Monsieur Grimseld, who steals their house. Reginald risks imprisonment to return to Switzerland to reclaim his cottage as his family are beginning to starve. Grimseld is fined for fraud, and Reginald is given the money for his farm.\n\nVolume 2 begins in the year 1544. An old man arrives at the family's house at Lake Constance, claiming to be a Venetian called Francesco Zampieri, but his true identity remains a mystery. He is being pursued by the Inquisition. Zampieri reveals to Reginald the secret of immortality and the art of multiplying gold. Only one person is permitted to know these secrets at any one time. The secret of immortality is an [[elixir of life|elixir]] made from herbs that when consumed bring youth and vigour. It cures sickness, but cannot save anyone from injury. Reluctant to keep a secret from his wife, Reginald is forced to remain silent about the gift and Zampieri dies shortly afterwards. \n\n[[Francis I of France|Francis I]] returns to France from his imprisonment in Spain, finding the country in a great upheaval, with [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] and [[Henry VIII]] in the process of invading northern France. Unwilling to return to his simple domestic life, Reginald plans to repurchase the estate that he lost, but in order to make it seem like he has regained his wealth gradually and not in suspicious circumstances, he moves to the city of [[Konstanz|Constance]] and pretends that Zampieri had given him 3,000 crowns. Constance is in the process of becoming Protestant. \n\nReginald is quickly seduced into spending a great deal of money and arouses the suspicion of his countryman, [[Gaspard II de Coligny|Gaspard de Coligny]]. Reginald's son, Charles, becomes aware of the shame that wealth with an inexplicable origin has brought and disowns his father and leaves. Marguerite is also suspicious and guesses that he has found the [[Philosopher's Stone]]. Reginald tells her not to reveal this and not to enquire further about it. She is ill, but as the elixir can only be drunk by an \"adept\", he cannot give it to her. \n\nThe suspicions about Reginald's wealth grow to such a height that the magistrate has him arrested and questioned. He is asked about the disappearance of the stranger and about his new wealth, but refuses to cooperate. Monsieur Monluc, a Frenchman, arrives, and Reginald appeals to him for help. Monluc investigates the case, interviews Marguerite. Reginald tells him the honorable name of St. Leon which removes the necessity for an explanation and he does not provide a reason. Monluc refuses to help him further. \n\nMarguerite advises Reginald to escape from the prison. He attempts to bribe a turnkey, Hector, but he refuses to help because he is loyal to the keeper and he reveals this to the keeper. The keeper asks for a bribe. Reginald hands over a large sum but is led to a dungeon instead and chained to a wall. Hector is imprisoned because he is the only person who knows about the bribe. The keeper asks for more money, and Reginald is forced to trust him, and this time he is released provided he takes Hector with him in order to make the latter appear to be an accomplice.\n\nIn volume 3, Reginald, his family, and Hector set out for Italy. One evening, while Hector and Reginald are taking an evening walk while the family are at an inn in the Alps, Reginald hears a man shrieking and is attacked by a large black dog. The dog takes him to a man who is wounded and dying. Reginald and Hector dress his wounds, and Hector runs back to the inn to get help. \n\nThe man's name is Andrea Filosanto. He had been taking his mother's dower to her and was robbed. He dies, and the dog grieves for him. Reginald takes the dog, Charon, into his family. A few months later, the dog finds the assailant, who is apprehended, confesses to being one of the robbers, is tried, convicted, and executed. \n\nReginald settles in [[Pisa]], and is protected by the Filosanto family and the family of the woman Andrea was about to marry, the Carracciuoli, who are powerful in the Pisan territory. Reginald spends some time practicing alchemy in a grotto, employing Hector as an assistant. Hector tells his girlfriend about the experiments, and Reginald quickly gains the reputation of being a sorcerer. His girlfriend's other lover, Agostino, is jealous and seeks revenge. \n\nReginald is shunned, and someone shoots at their house at night. The dog is killed, and Hector is attacked. The attack is motivated by the suspicions about magic and by Hector's being of African origin. Reginald addresses the mob in an attempt to vindicate himself, but they throw mud at him and accuse him of witchcraft. \n\nHe leaves to consult with the Marchese Filosanto, and the rest of the family leave for [[Lucca]], heading for Spain. They leave Hector in charge of their house in Pisa. When Reginald goes back to Pisa, he finds that the mob have burned his house down, that Hector has gone mad and has escaped his carers and has died defending the house. Hector was tortured by the mob, and it is clear that the crime is racially motivated. \n\nMarguerite has a miscarriage in Lucca. The family continue to Spain, and Marguerite dies in [[Barcelona]]. Distraught, the family continues to Madrid. Here, the daughters are looked after by Mariana, a former companion of their mother's. Reginald repurchases his family's French estate, and he gradually separates himself from his children, considering this to be a virtuous action. They are told to think and speak of him as if he were dead. The family still do not know the whereabouts of Charles. \n\nReginald moves to [[Madrid]] and spends time studying natural philosophy and ethics. He is followed by two men, who are eventually revealed to be informers for the Inquisition. He is arrested and imprisoned for sorcery. [[Philip II of Spain|Philip II]] returns to Spain after his marriage to [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]], and he oversees an [[auto da F\u00e9]] in Seville. Philip then travels to [[Valladolid]] for another [[auto da F\u00e9]], at which Reginald is to be burned alive. The elixir of life cannot protect him from this punishment. \n\nWhile processing to Valladolid from Madrid, a horse is frightened and kicks, and in the confusion, Reginald escapes and breaks into the house of a Jewish convert to Christianity, Mordecai. Just as he had appealed to the turnkey as a member of an oppressed minority, so Reginald appeals to Mordecai to help him escape the [[Inquisition]]. Mordecai helps him change his clothes and fetches the herbs needed for the elixir of immortality. Reginald, how has visibly aged such that he looks like a man of eighty. He drinks the elixir and becomes as young and healthy as he was on his wedding day. He leaves without Mordecai's knowledge. During his escape, Reginald accidentally witnesses the auto da f\u00e9 and is horrified.\n\nAt the beginning of volume 4, Reginald visits his daughters disguised as an Armenian merchant. He has now been away from them for twelve years. Louisa is 28, Marguerite is 24 {{Disputed inline|Talk page section|date=February 2020}}, and Julia died four years previously after her fianc\u00e9 had been imprisoned by his father for intending to marry her. Reginald pretends to have known their father and informs them of his own death. He hopes that the death certificate that he gives them will remove the dishonour from his family. \n\nReginald leaves for Hungary and takes a house in [[Buda]], intending to use his money to revitalize the economy after the devastation of a long war. He gives charity to poor people, becomes a corn-dealer and an architect, and takes a new name: \"the sieur de Chatillon\" (p.&nbsp;366). Problems occur, however, when demand for corn becomes too great and the people suspect him of manipulating the market for personal gain. \n\nReginald presents himself to the Turkish Pasha of Buda, Muzaffer Bey. But Bey blames him for causing civil unrest and investigates the unknown origins of Reginald's wealth. Reginald is forced to bribe him. He then meets Bethlem Gabor, a misanthropic arms dealer, and a native of [[Hungary]], whose wife and children have been murdered. Like Reginald, Bethlem spends a great deal of time wandering, and they share their sorrows and become friends. \n\nThe civil unrest eases as the crops that Reginald has ordered to be sown are ripening and are being successfully protected by soldiers. Three months have passed since Reginald first became acquainted with Bethlem. After expecting to meet him while travelling, Reginald is captured by Austro-Hungarian freebooters. He escapes and finds Bethlem, but without warning, Bethlem takes him to one of his castles and puts him in the dungeon. Reginald is left without food for thirty-six hours, and then he is given food and chained to a wall. \n\nBethlem gives as his reason for his hostility: that Reginald had helped an enemy of his, unknowingly, and that although he and Reginald had suffered the same loss of their families, Reginald had reacted to it by being kind to a great number of people and Bethlem had done the reverse. Bethlem feels shamed by this. Reginald tries to pay Bethlem to let him go, and requests a chest from his house. Bethlem opens the chest and discovers that it contains alchemical equipment. He demands gold, making it clear that he intends to keep Reginald locked up forever in order to supply it. \n\nIn the dungeon Reginald dreams that he is rescued by a knight in armour, who turns into a female angel, and that they fly away together leaving the castle in flames. Something close to this vision comes true. Bethlem visits Reginald's cell to tell him that the castle is under siege, and that he is experiencing remorse for keeping him captive. Bethlem gives Reginald the means to escape, making him promise not to do so for twenty-four hours. Reginald waits six hours, justifying his inability to keep his promise with the argument that it was extorted under duress. He spends two hours trying to get out of the caverns, but finds that the aids he left on the walls on his way in are no longer helpful. \n\nHe hears a loud shout and is startled, and concludes that he is near the outside. But a large amount of smoke convinces him to wait before he attempts to leave and he returns to the dungeons risking suffocation. He hides in a different cell from the one to which he was confined in case Bethlem returns. Eventually, Reginald leaves the castle in ruins and approaches some soldiers. He immediately recognizes his son Charles, who has changed his surname to de Damville. Charles is now thirty-two. Ruminating over what has happened, Reginald cannot account for Bethlem's hostile actions or his remorse and he forgives him. Charles does not recognize his father, who appears to be twenty-two, even though the other soldiers notice their similarity. \n\nIntending not to disgrace his son, Reginald adopts the name Henry d'Aubigny. Charles and Reginald quickly become friends, and Charles reveals his history. He is fighting the Turks, and prefers not to fight in the wars between Protestants and Catholics. He is also in search of Chatillon because of his known friendship with Bethlem Gabor. Reginald does not reveal that he is Chatillon. Charles recounts that he fought with General Castaldo in the [[battle of Muhlberg]] in 1547, whom he served for seven years. He recalls the siege of Erlau ([[Eger]], Hungary) and notes the bravery of the women of the city, and the siege of Ziget ([[Sisak]] in Croatia). Ziget was governed by Horvati, a Christian, and was besieged by the Turkish [[Pasha]] of Buda. \n\nThe Pasha lost the siege and died of grief and mortification. While Charles sympathizes a great deal with his son and is proud of his achievements, he regards his role as a Christian warrior as religious fanaticism. Charles has fallen in love with Pandora, the niece of the palatine of Hungary, Nadasti, whom he first met when she was fourteen. Pandora's father died in the siege of Ziget, leaving her a poor orphan and Nadasti prefers Charles to marry one of his own daughters. Charles realizes that he cannot support a wife on his pay, and he needs the uncle's consent. Reginald sees Pandora and is struck by her beauty, good sense and naturalness. He is determined to use his wealth to enable them to marry, but needs to find a way to make it seem appropriate. Reginald discovers that Pandora's mother had been a Venetian, and that her mother's uncle sailed with the Spanish explorer [[Francisco Pizarro]] to conquer [[Peru]]. Her uncle having died during the mission, he did not receive a portion of the treasure. Pandora being his sole surviving relative would have inherited this treasure. \n\nReginald finds, by chance, a man who had sailed on the same ship, Benedetto Cabriera, who has lost all of his money due to a series of calamities. Reginald pays him to pretend that Pandora's uncle had received his share, and that it had been bequeathed to her. While waiting for Benedetto to appear with the money in Hungary, Reginald learns that Charles has rejected Pandora because he thinks, incorrectly, that she is in love with Reginald and is an \u2018unfeeling coquette\u2019. Pandora explains to Reginald that they must no longer see each other, and is interrupted by Charles's arrival, faints and is caught by Reginald increasing Charles's suspicions. Charles remonstrates with them both and leaves them speechless. \n\nReginald yearns to tell his son the truth about his identity and learns his greatest lesson about solitude: more than a dungeon, solitude is alienation from your child. Reginald leaves for [[Presburg]] and meets Charles, who is on his way to accompany Mary, Queen of Scots back to her native land. Charles confronts his father with a letter from Andrew, Count of Bathori, accusing Reginald of being Chatillon and an alchemist. He tells Reginald that he lost his father to alchemy and challenges Reginald to a duel. Reginald agrees, but leaves Presburg before the appointed time. \n\nCharles and Pandora are reconciled, and the remainder of Reginald's story is devoted to tracing the development of Charles's virtues and to expressing his own regret at realizing the importance of his family too late.\n\n==Themes==\n\nThe novel explores the themes of immortality, the domestic affections (love and friendship), honour, and religion. Into a historical novel of vast range and violence Godwin melds elements of the domestic novel, the philosophical novel, and fantasy. More so than the earlier ''[[Things as They Are; or, The Adventures of Caleb Williams|Caleb Williams]]'', this novel tests Godwin's philosophical premises, showing the tensions between the aspiration to greatness and family affections and the disintegration of effective social responsibility.\n\n===Money===\n\nThe novel deals with a range of issues connected with wealth. Firstly, it moralizes against gambling, viewing it as a waste of resources and a drain on the time of people who could be doing something more useful with their wealth. Secondly, it traces the effects of poverty, suggesting that there is a nobility in the simple life. While the peasant life is favoured, the novel emphasizes that education is also important, and so the aristocratic family who are living in reduced circumstances have the benefit of having developed their minds and of living in a way that does not oppress anyone. Thirdly, the novel reflects on the power of wealth. The ideas expressed in the novel follow those of Godwin's ''[[Enquiry Concerning Political Justice and its Influence on Modern Morals and Manners]]'' (1793). Reginald reflects that \"[w]eakness and want are the parents of vice\".<ref>Godwin, 187.</ref> When Reginald is finally in a position to put his new ability to multiply gold to good use, he secures the future of his daughters, and then travels to Buda to help stimulate the post-war economy with a building program. When he finds his son Charles, he is able to give his intended wife a dowry without them knowing it. Wherever Reginald goes, he confronts problems with appearing to have excessive wealth that comes from no discernible origin. Here Godwin addresses the topic of the surveillance society, the problem of secrecy, and the traditional motif of cursed gold.\n\n===Liberty and intolerance===\n\nThe novel asks the questions: what do we need in order to be truly free? And what is oppression? Reginald's lost money may appear to him to be a disaster, but his wife, Marguerite, philosophizes that its loss makes them less able to oppress people by engaging them as servants, and it makes them more free themselves. She argues that people who are educated and live the life of a peasant are the happiest because they do not reduce the people below them \u201cto a state of servitude\u201d and in turn become themselves enslaved to their own homes and lifestyle.<ref>Godwin, 124.</ref> Intolerance is further explored through the persecutions of the Inquisition. Both the stranger who gives Reginald the secrets and Reginald himself are pursued by the Inquisition for sorcery. At several points in the narrative, Godwin expatiates on the power and unthinking qualities of mob-like behavior. He also explores racial intolerance through the torture and murder of Hector, the African servant, and the fear expressed by Mordechai, the Spanish convert from Judaism to Christianity. Reginald appeals to both for help on the grounds that they have experienced the same kind of oppression as him. Godwin also devotes a great deal of time to exploring the difficulties of immigrants and refugees. The St. Leon family is displaced several times, and they learn that the \"prepossessions of mankind are clearly unfavourable to a newcomer, an emigrant who has quitted his former connections and the scenes of his youth. They are unavoidably impelled to believe, that his taking up his abode in another country must be owing to a weak and discreditable caprice, if it be not owing to something still more disadvantageous in his character.\"<ref>Godwin, 133.</ref>\n\n===Honour and merit===\n\nHonour and merit are central themes in ''[[Things as They Are; or, The Adventures of Caleb Williams|Caleb Williams]]''. Again, Godwin pits aristocratic reputation against intrinsic merit. Like Falkland, in ''Caleb Williams'', Reginald has been brought up to think of himself as worthy of admiration and homage. He learns that the \"value of a man is in his intrinsic qualities\" and that honour is not inherited, it must be earned and displayed in one's actions.<ref>Godwin, 130.</ref> While Godwin associates aristocratic honour with vanity and ostentation, there remains in the novel a sense in which honourable behaviour is valued insofar as it signals loyalty, equitable action, and acting in an open manner.\n\n===Gender===\n\nTo some extent the novel preserves traditional ideas about the differences between men and women. Women are commended for their beauty and men for their bravery. Marguerite, however, is presented as an exceptional woman in that she is unusually brave, rational, and independent. Marguerite suggests that as a wife she should be \"a human being and an equal\" and that this means that they should be open with each other. In accordance with Godwin's views in Political Justice, Reginald attacks what he regards as effeminacy in men, and in particular, men who are inactive or who are emotional or cowardly. Zampieri, the stranger, criticizes Reginald for arguing that he could not keep a secret from his wife, calling him \"[f]eeble and effeminate\" and \"the puppet of a woman\".<ref>Godwin, 157.</ref> Reginald agrees to keep the secret, but still holds that his wife and he are two halves of one soul and rightly fears that the secret will lead to an emotional separation.\n\n==Influence==\n\n''St. Leon'' influenced the Gothic novel ''[[St. Irvyne; or, The Rosicrucian]]'' (1811) by Godwin's future son-in-law [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]] and ''[[Frankenstein]]'' (1818), which was dedicated to Godwin, and written by his daughter [[Mary Shelley]].<ref>Mary Shelley. ''Frankenstein. The 1818 Text, Contexts, Nineteenth-Century Responses, Modern Criticism''. Ed. J. Paul Hunter. New York: Norton, 1996, 4.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=lSO63P-AnZAC&pg=PA486&lpg=PA486&dq=st+leon+william+godwin&source=web&ots=zJ9R3E_4EJ&sig=ME0PeGaZmjy8FBZuM3AsVkXWCsU&hl=en#PPP1,M1 ''St. Leon''] at [[Google Books]]\n* [https://archive.org/stream/stleontaleofsixt00godwuoft#page/n13/mode/2up ''St. Leon''] unedited version at The [[Internet Archive]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:1799 novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by William Godwin]]\n[[Category:English novels]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the Reformation]]\n[[Category:1790s fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Italy]]\n[[Category:Pisa in fiction]]\n[[Category:Novels set in France]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Budapest in fiction]]\n[[Category:Fictional alchemists]]\n[[Category:18th-century British novels]]\n", "name_user": "John the Absurd", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Leon_(novel)"}
{"title_page": "Great Unity Party", "text_new": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Great Unity Party\n| logo = [[File:Logo of the Great Unity Party.svg|150px]]\n| colorcode = {{Great Union Party/meta/color}}\n| leader = [[Mustafa Destici]]\n| foundation = {{start date|1993|01|29|df=y}}\n| ideology = [[Turkish-Islamic synthesis]]<br>[[Sunni]] [[Islamism]]<br />[[Turkish nationalism|Turkish]] [[ultranationalism]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Denial of Violence|year=2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=402|first=Fatma Muge|last=Gocek}}</ref><br />[[Social conservatism]]\n| headquarters = [[Ankara]], [[Turkey]]\n| native_name = {{Nobold|B\u00fcy\u00fck Birlik Partisi}}\n| native_name_lang = tr\n| national = [[People's Alliance (Turkey)|People's Alliance]]\n| position = [[Far-right politics|Far-right]]\n| colours = {{Colorbox|#ee161f|border=darkgray}} [[Red]] {{Colorbox|white|border=darkgray}} [[White]]\n| youth_wing = [[Alperen Ocaklar\u0131]]\n| seats1_title = [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|Grand National Assembly]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|1|600|hex={{Great Union Party/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[Metropolitan municipalities in Turkey|Metropolitan municipalities]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|0|30|hex={{Great Union Party/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[List of municipalities in Turkey|District municipalities]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|6|1351|hex={{Great Union Party/meta/color}}}}\n| seats5_title = [[2014 Turkish local elections|Provincial councillors]]\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|4|1251|hex={{Great Union Party/meta/color}}}}\n| seats6_title = [[2014 Turkish local elections|Municipal Assemblies]]\n| seats6 = {{Composition bar|165|20498|hex={{Great Union Party/meta/color}}}}\n| split = {{nowrap|[[Nationalist Movement Party]]}}\n| flag = [[File:Flag of the Great Unity Party.svg|200px|border|Flag of the Great Unity Party]]\n| website = {{ConditionalURL}}\n| country = Turkey\n}}\nThe '''Great Unity Party''' ({{lang-tr|B\u00fcy\u00fck Birlik Partisi}}, BBP) or '''Great Union Party''' is a [[far-right politics|far-right]] [[Islamism|Islamist]] and [[Nationalism|nationalist]] [[list of political parties in Turkey|political party in Turkey]], created on 29 January 1993.<ref name=bio>[http://www.bbp.org.tr/index.php?doc=ozgecmis Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu's biography] {{in lang|tr}}</ref> It is considered to be close to the [[Grey Wolves (organization)|Grey Wolves]]  organization,<ref name=\"Sendika\">[http://www.sendika.org/english/yazi.php?yazi_no=9394  Turkey/Istanbul \u2013 Istanbul Police Chief claims there was no political motivation behind Hrant Dink\u2019s murder!], ''Sendika'' {{in lang|en}}</ref> and is related to the \"[[Turkish nationalism#Turkish Islamic synthesis|Alperen Ocaklar\u0131]]\" tendency, which operated a synthesis between [[cultural nationalism]] and [[Islamism]], and separated itself from the ''Nationalist Task Party'' (M\u00c7P), which was renamed to [[Nationalist Movement Party]] (MHP) in July 1992.<ref name=bio/>\n\nAlthough it is claimed that the founder of the party [[Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu]] left the MHP for lack of religious convictions, this should be seen rather as a speculation as Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu rarely blamed the MHP or talked about the separation. The rift between Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu and [[Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f]] actually started after the [[1980 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat]]. Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f defended himself in the infamous speech in which he declared \"My opinions and beliefs are of the same as the generals who organized the 1980 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat, yet I am in prison\" speech during trials after the coup. The ideological separation started then and reached the surface after Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f dismissed the Ankara headquarters of the MHP after the 1992 MHP Congress. The delegates had elected the candidate supported by [[Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu]] rather than the candidate of Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f environment. T\u00fcrke\u015f's dismissal, seen to show an anti-democratic approach, was the final blow to the relationship between the young clique who had suffered during the 1980 coup and were against anything anti-democratic, and the old clique which circled around Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f and believed in a nationalist-socialistic way of democracy.\n\nThe party has been represented in the [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|Parliament]] only via electoral coalitions with popular parties. At the 2002 [[legislative]] [[elections in Turkey|elections]], the party won 1.1% of the popular vote and no seats; in the [[2007 Turkish general election|2007 elections]] Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu was elected as an independent. In [[2009 Turkish local elections|2009 local elections]] the BBP's candidate was elected as the new mayor of [[Sivas]].\n\n==2009 helicopter crash and death of Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu==\n{{main|2009 Medair TC-HEK helicopter crash}}\nOn 25 March 2009, the leader of the BBP, [[Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu]], died in a [[2009 Medair TC-HEK helicopter crash|helicopter crash]] in south-eastern Turkey.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/six-including-far-right-turkish-party-leader-killed-in-helicopter-crash-11302582|title=Six including far-right Turkish party leader killed in helicopter crash|last=Online|first=Hurriyet Daily News|website=www.hurriyet.com.tr|language=tr|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref> A large search and rescue operation was conducted in the mountainous area around [[G\u00f6ksun]] in [[Kahramanmara\u015f Province]]. The helicopter wreckage was found 47 hours after the crash, and all six people on board were found dead. \u0130smail G\u00fcne\u015f, a reporter of the [[Ihlas News Agency]], who was accompanying Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu, initially survived the crash and placed a desperate call for help just after the crash, and reported a broken leg. By the time the search party located the crash site in the inclement weather, all six aboard, including G\u00fcne\u015f, were dead.<ref name=\":0\" /> Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu had been traveling from [[\u00c7a\u011flayancerit]] in [[Kahramanmara\u015f Province]] to [[Yerk\u00f6y]] in [[Yozgat Province]] in central Anatolia for another political rally before [[2009 Turkish local elections|local elections on 29 March]] when the chartered helicopter crashed.\n\n==2010 Gaza Freedom Flotilla==\n\nA delegation representing the BBP participated in the [[Gaza flotilla raid|Gaza Freedom Flotilla]] on board the ship [[MV Mavi Marmara]] in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbp.org.tr/haber_detail.php?haberid=474 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-06-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100604065615/http://www.bbp.org.tr/haber_detail.php?haberid=474 |archivedate=2010-06-04 }}</ref>\n\n==2016 gay pride march in Istanbul==\nIn 2016, the [[Grey Wolves (organization)|Alperen]] threatened to stop the [[Istanbul Pride|annual gay pride march in Istanbul]]. Alperen's Istanbul chief, Kursat Mican, stated:\n\n<blockquote>Degenerates will not be allowed to carry out their fantasies on this land...We're not responsible for what will happen after this point ... We do not want people to walk around half-naked with alcohol bottles in their hands in this [[sacred]] city watered by the blood of our ancestors.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news |title=Istanbul bans gay pride march after threats from hardline group |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-lgbt-pride/istanbul-bans-gay-pride-march-after-threats-from-hardline-group-idUSKCN0Z31I6?il=0 |accessdate=16 March 2019 |work=Reuters |date=17 June 2016 |language=en}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website}} {{in lang|tr}}\n{{Turkish nationalism}}\n{{Turkish political parties}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Islamic political parties in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Far-right political parties in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Nationalist parties in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Ankara]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Turkish nationalist organizations]]\n[[Category:Islamic nationalism]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Great Unity Party\n| logo = [[File:Logo of the Great Unity Party.svg|150px]]\n| colorcode = {{Great Union Party/meta/color}}\n| leader = [[Mustafa Destici]]\n| foundation = {{start date|1993|01|29|df=y}}\n| ideology = [[Turkish-Islamic synthesis]]<br>[[Sunni]] [[Islamism]]<br />[[Turkish nationalism|Turkish]] [[ultranationalism]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Denial of Violence|year=2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=402|first=Fatma Muge|last=Gocek}}</ref><br />[[Social conservatism]]\n| headquarters = [[Ankara]], [[Turkey]]\n| native_name = {{Nobold|B\u00fcy\u00fck Birlik Partisi}}\n| native_name_lang = tr\n| national = [[People's Alliance (Turkey)|People's Alliance]]\n| position = [[Far-right politics|Far-right]]\n| colours = {{Colorbox|#ee161f|border=darkgray}} [[Red]] {{Colorbox|white|border=darkgray}} [[White]]\n| youth_wing = [[Alperen Ocaklar\u0131]]\n| seats1_title = [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|Grand National Assembly]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|1|600|hex={{Great Union Party/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[Metropolitan municipalities in Turkey|Metropolitan municipalities]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|0|30|hex={{Great Union Party/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[List of municipalities in Turkey|District municipalities]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|6|1351|hex={{Great Union Party/meta/color}}}}\n| seats5_title = [[2014 Turkish local elections|Provincial councillors]]\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|4|1251|hex={{Great Union Party/meta/color}}}}\n| seats6_title = [[2014 Turkish local elections|Municipal Assemblies]]\n| seats6 = {{Composition bar|165|20498|hex={{Great Union Party/meta/color}}}}\n| split = {{nowrap|[[Nationalist Movement Party]]}}\n| flag = [[File:Flag of the Great Unity Party.svg|200px|border|Flag of the Great Unity Party]]\n| website = {{ConditionalURL}}\n| country = Turkey\n}}\nThe '''Great Unity Party''' ({{lang-tr|B\u00fcy\u00fck Birlik Partisi}}, BBP) or '''Great Union Party''' is a [[far-right politics|far-right]] [[Islamism|Islamist]] and [[Nationalism|nationalist]] [[list of political parties in Turkey|political party in Turkey]], created on 29 January 1993.<ref name=bio>[http://www.bbp.org.tr/index.php?doc=ozgecmis Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu's biography] {{in lang|tr}}</ref> It is considered to be close to the [[Grey Wolves (organization)|Grey Wolves]]  organization,<ref name=\"Sendika\">[http://www.sendika.org/english/yazi.php?yazi_no=9394  Turkey/Istanbul \u2013 Istanbul Police Chief claims there was no political motivation behind Hrant Dink\u2019s murder!], ''Sendika'' {{in lang|en}}</ref> and is related to the \"[[Turkish nationalism#Turkish Islamic synthesis|Alperen Ocaklar\u0131]]\" tendency, which operated a synthesis between [[cultural nationalism]] and [[Islamism]], and separated itself from the ''Nationalist Task Party'' (M\u00c7P), which was renamed to [[Nationalist Movement Party]] (MHP) in July 1992.<ref name=bio/>\n\nAlthough it is claimed that the founder of the party [[Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu]] left the MHP for lack of religious convictions, this should be seen rather as a speculation as Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu rarely blamed the MHP or talked about the separation. The rift between Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu and [[Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f]] actually started after the [[1980 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat]]. Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f defended himself in the infamous speech in which he declared \"My opinions and beliefs are of the same as the generals who organized the 1980 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat, yet I am in prison\" speech during trials after the coup. The ideological separation started then and reached the surface after Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f dismissed the Ankara headquarters of the MHP after the 1992 MHP Congress. The delegates had elected the candidate supported by [[Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu]] rather than the candidate of Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f environment. T\u00fcrke\u015f's dismissal, seen to show an anti-democratic approach, was the final blow to the relationship between the young clique who had suffered during the 1980 coup and were against anything anti-democratic, and the old clique which circled around Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f and believed in a nationalist-socialistic way of democracy.\n\nThe party has been represented in the [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|Parliament]] only via electoral coalitions with popular parties. At the 2002 [[legislative]] [[elections in Turkey|elections]], the party won 1.1% of the popular vote and no seats; in the [[2007 Turkish general election|2007 elections]] Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu was elected as an independent. In [[2009 Turkish local elections|2009 local elections]] the BBP's candidate was elected as the new mayor of [[Sivas]].\n\n==2009 helicopter crash and death of Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu==\n{{main|2009 Medair TC-HEK helicopter crash}}\nOn 25 March 2009, the leader of the BBP, [[Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu]], died in a [[2009 Medair TC-HEK helicopter crash|helicopter crash]] in south-eastern Turkey.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/six-including-far-right-turkish-party-leader-killed-in-helicopter-crash-11302582|title=Six including far-right Turkish party leader killed in helicopter crash|last=Online|first=Hurriyet Daily News|website=www.hurriyet.com.tr|language=tr|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref> A large search and rescue operation was conducted in the mountainous area around [[G\u00f6ksun]] in [[Kahramanmara\u015f Province]]. The helicopter wreckage was found 47 hours after the crash, and all six people on board were found dead. \u0130smail G\u00fcne\u015f, a reporter of the [[Ihlas News Agency]], who was accompanying Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu, initially survived the crash and placed a desperate call for help just after the crash, and reported a broken leg. By the time the search party located the crash site in the inclement weather, all six aboard, including G\u00fcne\u015f, were dead.<ref name=\":0\" /> Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu had been traveling from [[\u00c7a\u011flayancerit]] in [[Kahramanmara\u015f Province]] to [[Yerk\u00f6y]] in [[Yozgat Province]] in central Anatolia for another political rally before [[2009 Turkish local elections|local elections on 29 March]] when the chartered helicopter crashed.\n\n==2010 Gaza Freedom Flotilla==\n\nA delegation representing the BBP participated in the [[Gaza flotilla raid|Gaza Freedom Flotilla]] on board the ship [[MV Mavi Marmara]] in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbp.org.tr/haber_detail.php?haberid=474 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-06-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100604065615/http://www.bbp.org.tr/haber_detail.php?haberid=474 |archivedate=2010-06-04 }}</ref>\n\n==2016 gay pride march in Istanbul==\nIn 2016, the [[Grey Wolves (organization)|Alperen]] threatened to stop the [[Istanbul Pride|annual gay pride march in Istanbul]]. Alperen's Istanbul chief, Kursat Mican, stated:\n\n<blockquote>Degenerates will not be allowed to carry out their fantasies on this land...We're not responsible for what will happen after this point ... We do not want people to walk around half-naked with alcohol bottles in their hands in this [[sacred]] city watered by the blood of our ancestors.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news |title=Istanbul bans gay pride march after threats from hardline group |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-lgbt-pride/istanbul-bans-gay-pride-march-after-threats-from-hardline-group-idUSKCN0Z31I6?il=0 |accessdate=16 March 2019 |work=Reuters |date=17 June 2016 |language=en}}</ref><blockquote/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website}} {{in lang|tr}}\n{{Turkish nationalism}}\n{{Turkish political parties}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Islamic political parties in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Far-right political parties in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Nationalist parties in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Ankara]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Turkish nationalist organizations]]\n[[Category:Islamic nationalism]]\n", "name_user": "Davide King", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2016 gay pride march in Istanbul:fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Unity_Party"}
{"title_page": "The Strokes", "text_new": "{{short description|American rock band}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = The Strokes\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = The Strokes by Roger Woolman.jpg\n| landscape        = Yes\n| caption          = The Strokes in 2002; left to right: [[Nick Valensi]], [[Albert Hammond Jr.]], [[Julian Casablancas]], [[Fabrizio Moretti]], and [[Nikolai Fraiture]]\n| origin           = [[New York City|New York, New York]], U.S.\n| genre            = <!-- these genres are sourced in the musical style section of the text -->{{hlist|[[Indie rock]]|[[garage rock revival]]|[[post-punk revival]]}}\n| years_active     = {{start date|1998}}\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Cult Records|Cult]]|[[RCA Records|RCA]]|[[Rough Trade Records|Rough Trade]]}}\n| associated_acts  = <!--The Voidz are NOT an associated act per Template:Infobox musical artist#associated_acts; please follow the guidelines there for what belongs in this field-->\n| website          = {{URL|thestrokes.com}}\n| current_members  = {{unbulleted list|[[Julian Casablancas]]|[[Nick Valensi]]|[[Albert Hammond Jr.]]|[[Nikolai Fraiture]]|[[Fabrizio Moretti]]}}\n}}\n\n'''The Strokes''' are an American [[Rock music|rock]] band from [[New York City]]. Formed in 1998, the band is composed of singer [[Julian Casablancas]],   guitarists [[Nick Valensi]] and [[Albert Hammond, Jr.|Albert Hammond Jr.]], bassist [[Nikolai Fraiture]], and drummer [[Fabrizio Moretti]]. Following the conclusion of five-album deals with [[RCA Records|RCA]] and [[Rough Trade Records|Rough Trade]], the band has continued to release new music through Casablancas' [[Cult Records]].\n\nThe band's debut album, ''[[Is This It]]'' (2001),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infoplease.com/biography/var/thestrokes.html |title=The Strokes at |publisher=Infoplease.com |date= |accessdate=October 22, 2011}}</ref> was met with widespread critical acclaim and helped usher in the [[garage rock revival]] movement of the early 21st century; it was ranked No. 8 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s 100 \"Best Debut Albums of All Time\",<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-100-greatest-debut-albums-of-all-time-20130322 |title=The 100 Best Debut Albums of All Time |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=June 17, 2013}}</ref> No. 2 on ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s \"100 Best Albums of the '00s\",<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-best-albums-of-the-2000s-20110718/the-strokes-is-this-it-20110715 |title=100 Best Albums of the 2000s: The Strokes, 'Is This It' |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=July 11, 2014}}</ref> No. 199 on ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s \"[[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]]\", and No. 4 on ''[[NME]]''{{'s}} \"Top 500 Albums of All Time\".\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation and ''The Modern Age'' EP (1998\u20132001)===\nLead singer-songwriter [[Julian Casablancas]], guitarist [[Nick Valensi]], and drummer [[Fabrizio Moretti]] started playing together while attending [[Dwight School]] in [[Manhattan]]. Bassist [[Nikolai Fraiture]] befriended Casablancas while the two attended the [[Lyc\u00e9e Fran\u00e7ais de New York]]. At age 13, Casablancas was sent to [[Institut Le Rosey|Le Rosey]], a boarding school in [[Switzerland]], to improve his academic performance. There, he met guitarist [[Albert Hammond, Jr.]] Later, when Hammond came to New York to attend [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]], he shared an apartment with Casablancas. The roommates started a band, first performing at HiFi Bar, then The Spiral, followed by the [[Luna Lounge]] on the [[Lower East Side]] of New York, and then at Manhattan's popular [[Mercury Lounge]]. The Mercury Lounge's booker, [[Ryan Gentles]], quit his job to become the band's manager.<ref>Bush, B. (August 2002). The strokes. Music Connection, 26, 32\u201335.</ref>\n\nThe band began rehearsing a fourteen-song set (an early blueprint of the Strokes\u2019 2001 debut, ''Is This It'')\u2014including, \"Alone, Together,\" \"Barely Legal,\" \"[[Last Nite]],\" \"[[The Modern Age]],\" \"New York City Cops,\" \"Soma,\" \"[[Someday (The Strokes song)|Someday]],\" \"Take It or Leave It,\" and \"This Life\" (an early version of \"Trying Your Luck\"). Most of these songs now feature different [[lyrics]]. The band sent a demo to the newly reformed [[Rough Trade Records]] in the UK, sparking interest there, and leading to their first release (via the website of the UK magazine, ''[[NME]],'' who gave away a free mp3 download of \"[[Last Nite]]\" a week prior to the physical release as part of ''[[The Modern Age]]'' [[Extended play|EP]] in 2001). The EP sparked a bidding war among [[record label]]s, the largest for a rock band in years.<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtve.com/article.php?ArticleId=4690|title=the Strokes: \"We Just Do Our Own Thing\"|accessdate=January 23, 2007|year=2001|author=Joe D'Angelo|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211070125/http://www.mtve.com/article.php?ArticleId=4690|archivedate=February 11, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In August 2001, the Strokes made their first appearance on the cover of the publication ''[[The Fader]]'' in its ninth issue.<ref>{{cite magazine\n  | title = Fader 50: New York Rock\n  | magazine = The Fader\n  | date = November 26, 2007\n  | url = http://www.thefader.com/2007/11/26/fader-50-new-york-rock/\n  | accessdate=November 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===''Is This It''  (2001\u20132002) ===\n\nThe Strokes released their debut album, ''[[Is This It]],'' in the US in October 2001. The album was produced by Gordon Raphael, as was their follow-up album ''[[Room On Fire]]''. [[RCA]] delayed the North American (US) release over concerns with the album's cover and lyrics. The UK-released cover features a [[black-and-white]] photo of a gloved hand on a woman's naked backside, shown in semi-profile (photographer Colin Lane's then-girlfriend)<ref>The strokes: Never mind the buttocks ... (August 12, 2006). ''NME'' \u2013 ''New Musical Express'', 27.</ref> while the North American version replaced it with a photo of particle collisions in the [[Big European Bubble Chamber]]. RCA replaced the track \"New York City Cops\" with \"When It Started\", as the former featured potentially inflammatory lyrics in the wake of the  [[September 11 attacks]]. The track \"New York City Cops\"\u2014featuring the refrain, \"New York City Cops, they ain't too smart\"\u2014was listed as No. 12 on ''New York'' magazine's \"Ultimate New York Playlist\" on March 1, 2010. Despite its delayed release (and the potential controversy), ''Is This It'' received critical acclaim\u2014among other accolades, four stars from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', and a 9.1 from [[Pitchfork Media]]. The album made many critics' top-ten lists, was named the best album of the year by ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' and ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', and (in an article previewing summer concerts) ''[[NME]]'' urged readers to attend the Strokes\u2019 shows\u2014as they were touring some of the \"best pop songs ever\". While critics noted the influence of [[CBGB]] stalwarts [[Television (band)|Television]], Casablancas and bandmates said they had never heard the band, instead citing [[the Velvet Underground]] as a reference point.\n\nAfter the release of ''Is This It'', the band toured around the world\u2014including [[Japan]], [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[Europe]], and [[North America]] (the band opened for the [[Rolling Stones]] on numerous occasions during the North American leg of their tour). The self-made mini-documentary \"In Transit\" was filmed during the summer tour of Europe. In August 2002, the band headlined the UK's [[Carling Weekend]] festivals for the second time, subsequently playing at New York's [[Radio City Music Hall]] on a bill with [[the White Stripes]]. [[Jack White (musician)|Jack White]] joined the Strokes on stage to perform the guitar solo on \"New York City Cops\". During that period, the band also appeared as musical guests on numerous late-night talk shows. ''Is This It'' yielded several singles and music videos, all of which were directed by [[Roman Coppola]].\n\n[[File:Nick valensi 2dollarbill.jpg|thumb|left|Valensi at [[MTV]] 2 Dollar Bill 2002]]\n''Is This It'' has had an enduring impact on fans and critics alike. In 2009, ''NME'' named ''Is This It'' as the Greatest Album of the Decade (2000s).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/48412 |title=The Strokes' 'Is This It' tops NME albums of the decade list &#124; News |publisher=Nme.Com |date=November 17, 2009 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref>  The album placed second on a similar list compiled by ''Rolling Stone'' (the same issue featured a list of the '100 Best Songs of the 00's', featuring \"[[Hard to Explain]]\" and \"[[Last Nite]]\"  at Nos.&nbsp;59 and&nbsp;16, respectively).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stereogum.com/105081/rolling_stones_100_best_albums_songs_of_the_00s/list/ |title=Rolling Stone's 100 Best Albums, Songs Of The '00s |website=Stereogum |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> In January 2011, Rolling Stone conducted a survey among their [[Facebook]] fans to determine the top ten debut albums of all time. ''Is This It'' came in at number ten and was also the most recent behind [[Pearl Jam]]'s 1991 [[Ten (Pearl Jam album)|debut]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/photos/rolling-stones-facebook-fans-name-top-10-debut-albums-20110126/10-the-strokes-is-this-it-0071099 |title=Rolling Stone's Facebook Fans Name Top 10 Debut Albums: 10. The Strokes, 'Is This It' &#124; Rolling Stone Music &#124; Photos |magazine=Rollingstone.com |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> As of 2010, ''Is This It'' had sold over 3.5{{Citation needed|date=April 2012}}&nbsp;million copies worldwide.\n\n===''Room on Fire'' (2003\u20132004)===\nThe group began recording their follow-up in 2002 with producer [[Nigel Godrich]] (best known for his work with [[Radiohead]]), but later split with him in favor of Gordon Raphael, the producer of ''Is This It''. Recordings with Godrich were never revealed.<ref>Molenda, M. (2003, 12). Electric warriors: The strokes' albert hammond, jr. and nick valensi play it like it is. Guitar Player, 37, 70\u201376, 78.</ref> In August 2003, the band toured Japan, playing a couple of the upcoming songs: \"[[Reptilia (song)|Reptilia]]\", \"Meet Me In The Bathroom\", \"The Way It Is\", \"Between Love & Hate\" (formerly known as \"Ze Newie\") and \"[[12:51 (The Strokes song)|12:51]]\" (formerly known as \"Supernova\"). The band also played [[Paul Anka]]'s \"My Way\" with Japanese lyrics. The Strokes released their second album ''[[Room on Fire]]'' in October 2003. It received praise from critics but was less commercially successful, although it still went gold. The album's sound maintained the Strokes' familiar reference points{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}}, while also evoking groups such as [[the Cars]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mitchum |first1=Rob |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/7538-room-on-fire/ |title=The Strokes: Room On Fire |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=October 26, 2003 |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref> [[Bob Marley]],<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Tyrangiel |first1=Josh |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,524476,00.html |title=Different Strokes? |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]] |date=October 19, 2003 |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref> and [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]]<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Milner |first1=Greg |url=https://www.spin.com/2003/11/strokes-room-fire-rca/ |title=The Strokes, 'Room On Fire' (RCA) |magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date=November 21, 2003 |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref> In the process, they made the cover of ''[[Spin Magazine]]'' for the second time, with each member receiving his own cover. They also made the cover of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' for the first time. Additional media coverage of the band came from the relationship between Moretti and actress [[Drew Barrymore]], which ended in January 2007. The first single taken from ''Room on Fire'' was the song \"[[12:51 (The Strokes song)|12:51]]\", which used distinct keyboard-like sounds produced by Valensi's guitar. The video was also directed by Roman Coppola, and was inspired by the futuristic look of the 1980s film ''[[Tron]]''. This consisted of a mainly black scene, with instances of glowing picton blue and riptide.\n\nIn November 2003, the Strokes played on ''Late Night with Conan O'Brien'', performing \"[[Reptilia (song)|Reptilia]]\", \"What Ever Happened\", \"Under Control\" and \"I Can't Win\".<ref>DeRogatis, J. (2004, 04). The strokes' fabrizio moretti: Sculpting rock 'N' roll. Modern Drummer, 28, 62\u201366, 68, 70.</ref> During the 2003/2004 \"''Room on Fire'' Tour\", the band played with [[Kings of Leon]] as support act and [[Regina Spektor]]. While on tour, Spektor and the Strokes recorded the song \"[[Modern Girls & Old Fashion Men]]\", released as a B-side on the \"Reptilia\" single. Also during the tour, the band included [[the Clash]]'s \"Clampdown\" as a cover, which was released as the B-side for \"[[The End Has No End]]\".\n\nIn late 2004, the Strokes revealed plans to release a live album. The ''Live in London'' LP was planned for release in October 2004, but was abandoned, reportedly due to recording quality problems. The chosen gig was one held at the legendary [[Alexandra Palace]] in North London.\n\n=== ''First Impressions of Earth'' and hiatus (2005\u20132007) ===\n[[File:The Strokes in concert.jpg|right|250px|thumb|The Strokes in concert, 2006]]\nIn late September 2005, \"[[Juicebox (song)|Juicebox]]\", the first single from the Strokes' then unreleased third album, was leaked online, forcing the single's release date to be advanced. The single was then released as an exclusive on online download services. \"Juicebox\" became the Strokes' second UK Top 10 hit, as well as their second US Modern Rock Top 10 success. During November and December 2005 the Strokes did a promotional tour for the still unreleased album, which involved doing one-off shows in major cities around the world. Their third album, ''[[First Impressions of Earth]]'', was released on December 30, 2005, in Germany<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.laut.de/The-Strokes/Alben/First-Impressions-Of-Earth-11120 |title=\"First Impressions of Earth\" von The Strokes |last=Butscher |first=Vicky |website=[[Laut.de]] |language=German |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> and January 3, 2006, elsewhere.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/first-impressions-of-earth-mw0000339306 |title=First Impressions of Earth - The Strokes |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> It received mixed reviews and debuted at number four in the US and number one in the UK, the latter being a first for the band. In Japan, it went gold within the first week of release. It was also the most downloaded album for two weeks on iTunes. Fraiture claimed that the album was \"like a scientific breakthrough\". In January 2006, the band then made their second appearance on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' playing \"Juicebox\" and \"[[You Only Live Once (The Strokes song)|You Only Live Once]]\". The album was somewhat a departure from the band's two previous albums. One reason for this was a switch of producers from Gordon Raphael to David Kahne.<ref>Marchese, D. (January 2006). Music: Onward and into the audioscape \u2013 the strokes upgrade their cute dischevelment but leave a few too many sexy hooks behind. The Village Voice, 51, C81.</ref> Despite its initial strong sales, ''First Impressions of Earth'' received the worst reception, both commercially and critically, of all their albums.\n\nIn 2006, the band played 18 sold-out shows during their UK tour. In February 2006, the Strokes won \"Best International Band\" at the NME Awards. In March, the band returned to the US with their longest tour yet. The second single off ''First Impressions of Earth'', \"Heart in a Cage\", was released in March 2006. During the summer of 2006, the Strokes played several festival dates in Europe, including the Hultsfred Festival in Sweden, [[Roskilde Festival]] in Denmark, the [[Oxegen Festival]] in Ireland, the [[Montreux Jazz Festival]] in Switzerland, the FIB ([[Festival Internacional de Benic\u00e0ssim]]), [[Fuji Rock Festival]] and headlined the [[Pentaport Rock Festival]] in South Korea. They then toured Australia and Mexico in late August and early September, followed by the second leg of the United States tour. While in the US, the Strokes opened for [[Tom Petty & the Heartbreakers]] for five shows during their Highway Companion tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2006/07/tom-petty-adds-sept-dates-strokes-frank-black/ |title=Tom Petty Adds Sept. Dates with Strokes, Frank Black |publisher=Spin.com |date=July 7, 2006 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> The Strokes went on to complete another US tour. During this final tour Casablancas stated to fans that the band would be taking an extensive break after it finished. An e-mail was sent out soon afterwards by Strokes manager [[Ryan Gentles]], confirming that \"much needed break\". A new band website went online in May 2007 along with the release of an alternate video to their single \"You Only Live Once\" directed by [[Warren Fu]]. The video also featured a brief interlude with \"Ize of the World\", also from ''First Impressions of Earth''. The song \"You Talk Way Too Much\" was used in a commercial for the Ford Sync. Aleksandra Cisneros became the Strokes' assistant manager in late 2007.\n\n===''Angles'' (2009\u20132011)===\n[[File:Julian Casablancas Belfort 2010.jpg|thumb|right|Julian Casablancas, frontman of The Strokes, at [[Eurock\u00e9ennes]] 2010]]\nThe Strokes frontman Julian Casablancas and guitarist Nick Valensi started writing material for the album in January 2009, intent on entering the studio that February.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/42301|title=NME: The Strokes: 'We've started writing our fourth album'|publisher=NME.com|author=NME Staff|date=|accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref> Julian commented in ''Rolling Stone'' that they had completed about three songs that sounded like a mixture of [[Rock music#Post-punk|1970s rock]] and \"music from the future\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/blogs/smokingsection/2009/03/the-strokes-are-back-in-action.php |title=Blogs |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> On March 31, 2009 from their MySpace account, the band announced the end of their \"much needed hibernation period\" and the commencement of new writing and rehearsing for a fourth full-length album, entitled ''[[Angles (The Strokes album)|Angles]]''. This album would be different from the first three in that it would feature music written by the other four Strokes, rather than Casablancas writing ninety-five percent of the material again: \"It's supercollaborative, and it sounds different,\" said Valensi, \"but it has a Strokes vibe to it.\"<ref>Scaggs, A. (April 29, 2010). 40 reasons to be excited about music: No. 21 \u2013 the strokes are getting it back together. Rolling Stone, 80.</ref> In an ''NME'' article, [[Pharrell Williams]] expressed interest in producing this upcoming album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/pharrell-williams/37303 |title=Pharrell Williams: 'I want to produce the Strokes' new album' &#124; News |publisher=Nme.Com |date=June 13, 2008 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> This followed the news that Casablancas had collaborated with Williams and [[Santigold]] on \"[[My Drive Thru]]\", a track commemorating the 100th anniversary of [[Converse (company)|Converse]]'s [[Chuck Taylor All-Stars]] shoe. The song was available as a free download from the official Converse site.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stereogum.com/archives/new-santogold-julian-casablances-pharrell-my-drive_010274.html |title=New Santogold, Julian Casablancas & Pharrell \u2013 \"My Drive Thru\" |website=Stereogum |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> The album was due to be released in late 2009, but disagreements about the songs' readiness forced the Strokes to scale back this date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/news/the-strokes-disagreement-over-new-album |title=The Strokes' \"Disagreement\" Over New Album \u2013 23 Oct 2009 &#124; Clash Music Latest Breaking Music News |publisher=Clashmusic.com |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> On February 1, 2010, the Strokes announced on their website that the recording of the fourth album was being helmed by award-winning producer [[Joe Chiccarelli]]. According to Chiccarelli in an interview with [[HitQuarters]], the two camps first met in 2009 and, after finding they shared a similar mind space and similar thoughts on the potential direction of the new record, tried out some tracking.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_Joe_Chiccarelli_Interview.html |title=Interview with Joe Chiccarelli |publisher=[[HitQuarters]]|date=June 14, 2010 |accessdate=August 17, 2010}}</ref>  Not long after recording began, however, the band became frustrated with Chiccarelli's reserved production style.  Only one song from these recording sessions, \"Life Is Simple in the Moonlight\", remained on the album's track listing.  Inspired, in part, by bands like [[MGMT]], [[Arctic Monkeys]], and [[Crystal Castles (band)|Crystal Castles]], the Strokes decided to experiment with various production techniques,<ref>{{cite web |last=Costigan |first=Mark |url=http://oregonmusicnews.com/blog/2011/02/02/the-strokes-nikolai-fraiture-talks-about-new-album-reveals-track-listing/ |title=The Strokes' Nikolai Fraiture talks about new album, reveals track listing |publisher=Oregon Music News |date=February 2, 2011 |accessdate=July 9, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723203937/http://oregonmusicnews.com/blog/2011/02/02/the-strokes-nikolai-fraiture-talks-about-new-album-reveals-track-listing/ |archivedate=July 23, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and recorded the rest of the album's material at Albert Hammond, Jr.'s home studio in upstate New York with award-winning engineer Gus Oberg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/49559 |title=The Strokes begin recording fourth album with U2, Beck producer &#124; News |publisher=Nme.Com |date=February 3, 2010 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Strokes confirmed that they would be headlining the [[Isle of Wight Festival]], [[Lollapalooza]], [[Roskilde Festival]],<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2010/03/11/the-strokes-confirm-lollapalooza-slot-report-in-on-next-album/|title=The Stokes Confirm Lollapalooza Slot, Report In on Next Album|magazine=Rolling Stone|last=Kreps|first=Daniel|date=March 11, 2010|accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> [[Hurricane Festival]], [[Splendour In The Grass]], [[Rockness]], [[Outside Lands Music and Arts Festival]],<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/abraham/detail??blogid=95&entry_id=64802 | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | title=Outside Lands Festival San Francisco schedule released today | date=June 1, 2010}}</ref> On The Bright Side,<ref>{{cite web |author=gea-interactive.com.au |url=http://www.onthebrightside.com.au/ |title=Splash |publisher=On The Bright Side |accessdate=July 9, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110822050858/http://onthebrightside.com.au/ |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and [[Austin City Limits Music Festival]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://2010.aclfestival.com/ |title=ACL 2010 |publisher=2010.aclfestival.com |accessdate=July 9, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120707161957/http://2010.aclfestival.com/ |archivedate=July 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> in 2010.  Additionally, the Strokes were announced as the 2011 headliner for the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]] and the [[New Orleans Jazz & Heritage Festival]] in May, [[Festival Internacional de Benic\u00e0ssim]], [[Oxegen]], [[Pal\u00e9o Festival|Pal\u00e9o]], [[Peace & Love (festival)|Peace & Love]] and [[Super Bock Super Rock]] in July, and [[Reading Festival]] and [[Summer Sonic]] in August. They were also sub-headliners to [[Pulp (band)|Pulp]] at [[Leeds Festival]] during the bank holiday weekend in August. On June 9, 2010, at [[Dingwalls]] London, England, the band played a secret show under the name 'Venison' to a crowd of just 487. This was their first live gig since October 2006. The band did not play any new material.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/51445 |title=The Strokes play first gig in four years at intimate London venue &#124; News |publisher=Nme.Com |date=June 9, 2010 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe lead single from the new album, \"[[Under Cover of Darkness]]\", was released on February 9, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/54874 |title=The Strokes to release 'Under Cover Of Darkness' as free download &#124; News |publisher=Nme.Com |date=February 8, 2011 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> The 7\" was officially released on March 1, 2011 and contained another track from ''[[Angles (The Strokes album)|Angles]]'', \"You're So Right\", as the B-side, followed by the album on March 18, 2011.\n\"[[Taken for a Fool]]\" was confirmed as the second single, which was sent to U.S. radio on May 24, 2011. On June 9, the Strokes announced that a music video for \"Taken For a Fool\" was in the works, and that it is directed by Laurent Briet. They revealed that the music video should be finished by the end of the month. The Strokes put out the music video for \"Taken For a Fool\" on July 8, 2011. In mid-March 2011, an interview with ''[[ShortList]]'' magazine revealed that the Strokes had already begun working on their fifth studio album. However, sessions were delayed due to the mixing process of ''Angles''. Julian Casablancas and Nick Valensi both confirmed that there was material in the works as well as plenty of leftover material.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shortlist.com/entertainment/music/article/1144/the-strokes-return#image-rotator-3|title=The Strokes Return / Music / ShortList Magazine|date=February 17, 2011|publisher=Shortlist.com|accessdate=July 9, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110401121042/http://www.shortlist.com/entertainment/music/article/1144/the-strokes-return#image-rotator-3|archive-date=April 1, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Frontman Julian Casablancas claimed that the band was eager to begin working on new material<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/56306|title=The Strokes hit the studio to work on 'new ideas'|date=April 25, 2011|publisher=Nme.com|accessdate=October 22, 2011}}</ref> and were already supposed to, but it took longer than expected to master ''Angles''.\n\n===''Comedown Machine'' (2012\u22122015)===\n[[File:Thestrokes2010.jpg|thumb|320px|left|The Strokes at Austin City Limits Festival in 2010]]\nIn April 2012, bassist Nikolai Fraiture posted a tweet announcing that the band was heading into the studio to work on some new ideas.<ref>{{cite web|last=Breihan |first=Tom |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/42351-the-strokes-at-work-on-new-music/ |title=The Strokes at Work on New Music |website=Pitchfork |date=April 27, 2011 |accessdate=October 22, 2011}}</ref> The Strokes later revealed that they were planning to record a new album as soon as possible. Fraiture added that the band would record their fifth album in the same manner as they put together ''Angles'', with each member bringing in his own ideas and putting them together in the studio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/57464 |title=The Strokes planning to record new album 'as soon as possible' &#124; News |publisher=Nme.Com |date=June 21, 2011 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> On January 17, 2013, Seattle alternative radio station [[KNDD|107.7 The End]] posted on their Facebook page that they were previewing a new song by the Strokes entitled \"[[All the Time (The Strokes song)|All the Time]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Previewing brand new Strokes \"All the Time\" thanks to RCA Records. We'll have to \"leak\" this soon. You won't be disappointed...|url=http://www.facebook.com/1077theend/posts/10151266805345073|accessdate=January 17, 2013}}</ref> It was later confirmed that \"All the Time\" would be the lead single from the untitled fifth album.<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite magazine|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|title=The Strokes To Release Fifth Album Later This Year: Update|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1501292/the-strokes-to-release-fifth-album-later-this-year-update|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=January 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"consequence\">{{cite web|last=Roffman|first=Michael|title=The Strokes to release new single, 'All the Time'|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/01/the-strokes-to-release-new-single-all-the-time/|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|accessdate=January 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"KNDD\">{{cite web|title=Details: New Strokes Album On The Way|url=http://www.1077theend.com/Details--New-Strokes-Album-On-The-Way/11684758?pid=290511|work=[[KNDD|107.7 The End]]|publisher=[[Entercom Communications]]|accessdate=January 17, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121103407/http://www.1077theend.com/Details--New-Strokes-Album-On-The-Way/11684758?pid=290511|archivedate=January 21, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On January 25, 2013, the song \"[[One Way Trigger]]\" was published on their official website, and made available for free download.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/68365|title=The Strokes unveil new song 'One Way Trigger'&nbsp;\u2013 listen|date=January 25, 2013|publisher=NME.com}}</ref> The song was initially met with a mixed reaction from fans of the band.<ref>{{cite web| title = Fans react to \"weird\" return of The Strokes| work = [[NME]]| publisher = [[IPC Media]]| date = January 26, 2013| url = http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/68374| accessdate = January 28, 2013}}</ref> On January 28, a [[Reddit]] user discovered what he correctly assumed to be the new album cover within the subpages of the band's official website, which led to a widespread rumor that the new album would be titled ''Comedown Machine''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/68438|title=The Strokes name new album 'Comedown Machine'?|date=January 30, 2013|publisher=NME.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jan/31/strokes-scooped-new-comedown-machine-album|title=The Strokes scooped on new Comedown Machine album|date=January 31, 2013|work=guardian.co.uk}}</ref> On January 30, the title for the fifth album was revealed to be ''[[Comedown Machine]]'', set to be released on March 26 in the U.S. and March 25 in the UK.<ref name=\"CoS\">{{cite web|last=Young|first=Alex|title=The Strokes to release new album Comedown Machine on March 26th|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/01/the-strokes-to-release-new-album-comedown-machine-on-march-26th/|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|accessdate=January 30, 2013}}</ref> On February 13, 2013, the first single from the band's fifth album premiered on the radio, named \"All the Time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stereogum.com/1259602/the-strokes-all-the-time/mp3s/ |title=The Strokes \u2013 \"All The Time\" |website=Stereogum |date=February 13, 2013 |accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref> The single was released for download on February 19, and was described as a return to the classic Strokes sound of first albums ''Is This It'' and ''Room on Fire''. The album was released on March 25, 2013 in the UK and March 26 in the United States. The band decided to pull a media blackout with the album: no promotion in the form of TV appearances, interviews, photos, shows, or tours. On October 15, 2013, the band revealed that they were looking to \"return to the scene\" in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicblogged.com/the-strokes-new-album-and-tour-2014/ |title=The Strokes new album and tour 2014|publisher=Music Blogged |date=October 15, 2013 |accessdate=October 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, the Strokes performed their first U.S. show in three years at the [[Capitol Theatre (Port Chester, New York)|Capitol Theatre]] in [[Port Chester, New York]], performing songs from ''Comedown Machine'' for the first time. The band played at three other shows in 2014, including two headlining slots at [[Governors Ball Music Festival]] in [[New York City]] and [[FYF Fest]] in [[Los Angeles]]. On November 12, 2014, it was announced the band would headline [[Primavera Sound]] in 2015 for the festival's 15th anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nme.Com |url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/81023 |title=The Strokes confirmed for Primavera Sound festival 2015 |website=Nme.com |date= |accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> On March 2, 2015, the band announced their second 2015 European festival headline appearance would be at [[London]]'s annual [[Hyde Park, London#Events|British Summer Time: Hyde Park festival]] on June 18, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neverenoughnotes.co.uk/2015/03/the-strokes-british-summer-time-hyde-park/ |title=The Strokes to play British Summer Time Hyde Park this summer|publisher=Never Enough Notes |date=October 15, 2013 |accessdate=March 2, 2015}}</ref> the band's first London show in five years.<ref>{{cite news|author=Daisy Wyatt |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/bst-hyde-park-2015-the-strokes-join-taylor-swift-and-blur-as-headliners-10079399.html |title=The Strokes join Blur and Taylor Swift to headline BST Hyde Park 2015 &#124; News &#124; Culture |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date= |accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> The announcement takes the band's number of appearances slated for 2015 up to six, with them also playing Big Guava Music Festival in [[Tampa, Florida]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestrokes.com/us/news/big-guava-music-festival |title=Archived copy |accessdate=March 9, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150303204717/http://www.thestrokes.com/us/news/big-guava-music-festival |archivedate=March 3, 2015 }}</ref> Shaky Knees Festival in [[Atlanta, Georgia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestrokes.com/us/news/shaky-knees-festival |title=Archived copy |accessdate=March 9, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217031553/http://www.thestrokes.com/us/news/shaky-knees-festival |archivedate=February 17, 2015 }}</ref> Landmark Festival in [[Washington, D.C.]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestrokes.com/us/event/2015/09/26/landmark-music-festival |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 15, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150715115725/http://www.thestrokes.com/us/event/2015/09/26/landmark-music-festival |archivedate=July 15, 2015 }}</ref> and Austin City Limits in [[Austin, Texas]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestrokes.com/us/event/2015/10/02/acl-2015 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 15, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150715111805/http://www.thestrokes.com/us/event/2015/10/02/acl-2015 |archivedate=July 15, 2015 }}</ref> as well as the previously announced Primavera Sound 15th Anniversary. During their performance at Landmark Music Festival lead singer Julian Casablancas stated that the band is back in the studio working on a follow up to their 2013 album ''Comedown Machine''. In late 2015, the Strokes announced another date; at Monterrey, Mexico, during the festivities of the newborn festival Live Out.\n\n===''Future Present Past'' EP (2016\u20132017)===\nThe Strokes played their first show of 2016 at Samsung's Galaxy Life Fest in Austin, Texas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sxsw.com/news/2016/samsung-announces-galaxy-life-fest-sxsw-interactive|title=Samsung Reveals Galaxy Life Fest at SXSW Interactive With Public Enemy, The Strokes, and More|website=South by Southwest 2016 Music, Film and Interactive Festivals - Austin Texas|access-date=April 17, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160428040404/http://www.sxsw.com/news/2016/samsung-announces-galaxy-life-fest-sxsw-interactive|archivedate=April 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \nOn May 24, 2016, the Strokes announced another New York show on 31 May at the [[Capitol Theatre (Port Chester, New York)|Capitol Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/thestrokes/status/735146115847200771 |title=The Strokes on Twitter: \"New York\u2026don't make plans next Tuesday. We're playing @capitoltheatre on 5/31, can't wait to see y'all!\" |publisher=Twitter |date=May 24, 2016 |accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:StrokesCorona161119-49 (49081371357).jpg|thumb|320px|right|The Strokes performing at Corona Capital, 2019]]\nOn May 26, 2016, Julian Casablancas premiered \u201cOBLIVIUS\u201d on the debut of his monthly radio show, \"Culture Void\", on [[Sirius XMU]]. [[Cult Records]] announced the release of ''[[Future Present Past]]'', a four-song EP by the Strokes, in addition to the exclusive signing of the band to its roster. The EP includes three original songs (\u201cDrag Queen\u201d, \u201cOBLIVIUS\u201d, and \u201cThreat of Joy\u201d), along with an additional remix of \u201cOBLIVIUS\u201d by drummer, Fab Moretti. The EP was released on June 3, in both digital and physical formats to coincide with the band's headlining performance at [[Governors Ball Music Festival]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/90667|title=The Strokes confirm first live date of 2016 {{!}} NME.COM|last=NME.COM|website=NME.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=April 17, 2016}}</ref> \"Future Present Past\" was recorded over the past year in Austin and New York with the help of producer, Gus Oberg.\n\nThe band played at the [[Splendour in the Grass]] festival in [[Byron Bay, New South Wales|Byron Bay,]] [[Australia]] on July 22, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diymag.com/2016/04/13/the-strokes-james-blake-the-cure-splendour-in-the-grass-2016|title=The Strokes, James Blake and The Cure to play Splendour In The Grass 2016|website=DIY|access-date=April 17, 2016}}</ref> They followed this performance with the inaugural City of Angels Benefit concert in Los Angeles to support charities such as Waste Not Want Not Now, the Center in Hollywood, and the Downtown's Women's Center on July 25, 2016.\n\nThe band performed a series of festival dates taking place throughout early 2017. Festival dates include performances in [[Est\u00e9reo Picnic Festival]] as well as [[Lollapalooza|Lollapalooza Brasil]], [[Lollapalooza Chile]], and [[Lollapalooza Argentina]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thestrokes.com/|title=The Strokes|website=The Strokes|language=en-US|access-date=April 20, 2017}}</ref> The band's first live performance of the year took place headlining the [[Est\u00e9reo Picnic Festival]]. The crowd in attendance of their Argentina show was reportedly a volume of 90,000 people. After the Lollapalooza Argentina show it was revealed that their headlining slot at the festival was, to this day, their \"biggest show ever\" by Fraiture on social media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/the-strokes-biggest-show-of-career-lollapalooza-argentina-footage-2032607|title=Watch The Strokes play the \"biggest show\" of their career in Argentina - NME|date=April 4, 2017|work=NME|access-date=April 20, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===''The New Abnormal'' (2019\u2013present)===\nIn October 2016, guitarist Valensi indicated that the band were \"slowly but surely working on an album, we\u2019re kind of just in writing sessions\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://diymag.com/2016/10/11/the-strokes-new-album-2017-nick-valensi-interview|title=The Strokes are \"slowly but surely working on an album\"|last=Konemann|first=Liam|date=October 11, 2016|website=DIY|publisher=|access-date=November 16, 2016}}</ref> In July 2017 Albert Hammond Sr. said the Strokes are working with Rick Rubin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewest.com.au/entertainment/music/albert-hammond-strokes-recording-with-rick-rubin-ng-b88549060z|title=Albert Hammond: Strokes recording with Rick Rubin|last=Collins|first=Simon|date=July 27, 2017|website=The West}}</ref> Albert Hammond Jr. took to Twitter to clarify that \u201cwe met and played a few music ideas for Rick to feel out a vibe but even a theoretical album plan would be years away, if at all.\u201d He also tweeted, \"Sorry everyone we are not in the studio recording\" and that there were \"a lot of unknowns and nothing worth speaking about at this time.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7882102/the-strokes-not-recording-rick-rubin-album|title=The Strokes Are Not Recording With Rick Rubin After All|last=Helman|first=Peter|date=July 30, 2017|website=The West}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, the band performed for the first time in over two years at a benefit show in Los Angeles. At this venue, the band debuted a new song entitled \"The Adults Are Talking\".<ref>https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-the-strokes-perform-new-song-the-adults-are-talking</ref> The show kicked off the band's \"global comeback\" tour.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Maicki |first1=Salavatore |title=The Strokes are planning a \"global comeback\" tour for 2019 |url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/12/18/the-strokes-2019-comeback-tour-bilbao |magazine=[[The Fader]] |accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Michallon |first1=Clemence |title=The Strokes 2019 concert: How to get tickets for the 'global comeback' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/the-strokes-tickets-buy-concert-spain-bilbao-bbk-festival-julian-casablancas-albert-hammond-jr-a8687931.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref> However, this tour was met with many obstacles early on, from sound issues<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Connor |first1=Roisin |title=All Points East: The Strokes gig compared to 'underwater karaoke' by fans annoyed over sound issues |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/the-strokes-all-points-east-gig-sound-quality-issues-fans-complaints-a8930761.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> to rained-out shows<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Aswad |first1=Jem |last2=Sabla |first2=Elvin |title=Governors Ball Festival Evacuated Due to Thunderstorms, Multiple Acts Cancelled |url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/governors-ball-evacuated-festival-thunderstorm-cancelled-1203231235/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> to entire festivals being cancelled.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Cantor-Navas |first1=Judy |title=Doctor Music Festival Canceled After Move From Mountain Pastures to Barcelona Racetrack |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/festivals/8515958/doctor-music-festival-canceled-barcelona |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> In September 2019, Valensi, in an interview on C104.3 Out of the Box, hinted at the production of a sixth studio album, stating \"When, I don\u2019t know. If \u2014 I would say, it\u2019s a strong likelihood.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://faroutmagazine.co.uk/the-strokes-new-album-is-finished-teases-guitarist-nick-valensi/|title=The Strokes' new album is \"finished\" according to guitarist Nick Valensi|last=Ellis|first=Nathan|date=2019-09-08|website=Far Out Magazine|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref> During the band's 2019 New Year's Eve show in Brooklyn, Casablancas announced that the band's sixth studio album would be released sometime in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/strokes-confirm-new-album-2020-2591853 |title=The Strokes confirm they have a new album coming in 2020 at New Year's Eve show |last=Lavin |first=Will |date=January 1, 2020 |website=NME |access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref> At the show, they also debuted a new song, titled \"Ode to the Mets\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2068691/the-strokes-confirm-new-album-debut-new-song-mac-demarco/video/ |title=Watch The Strokes Debut New Song \"Ode To The Mets,\" Confirm 2020 Album at Brooklyn NYE Show |last=DeVille |first=Chris |date=January 1, 2020 |website=[[Stereogum]] |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February 2020, the band performed at a rally for presidential candidate [[Bernie Sanders]] at the [[University of New Hampshire]]. At this performance, Casablancas formally announced the band's sixth studio album and that the title would be ''The New Abnormal''. He confirmed the release date of the album to be April 10 of that year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-strokes-announce-new-album-debut-songs-at-bernie-sanders-rally-watch/ |title=The Strokes Announce New Album, Debut Songs at Bernie Sanders Rally: Watch |work=Pitchfork |date=February 10, 2020 |accessdate=February 10, 2020 |author=Bloom, Madison}}</ref> The band reportedly played two new songs at this show. On February 11th, the band released a new song, \"[[At the Door]]\", the first single off of their sixth studio album.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/the-strokes-at-the-door/ |title=\"At The Door\" by The Strokes review |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=February 14, 2020 |accessdate=February 14, 2020 |author=Yoo, Noah}}</ref> Two more singles followed, \"[[Bad Decisions (The Strokes song)|Bad Decisions]]\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-the-strokes-new-song-bad-decisions/|title=Listen to the Strokes' New Song \"Bad Decisions\" |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=February 18, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |author1=Bloom, Madison |author2=Torres, Eric}}</ref> and \"[[Brooklyn Bridge to Chorus]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-strokes-brooklyn-bridge-to-chorus-978812/|title=The Strokes Go New Wave on Latest Single \u2018Brooklyn Bridge to Chorus\u2019|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=April 6, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |author=Shaffer, Claire}}</ref> Their sixth studio album, ''[[The New Abnormal]]'', was released worldwide on April 10, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2079865/the-strokes-the-new-abnormal/music/album-stream/|title=Stream The Strokes\u2019 First Album In 7 Years, The New Abnormal|work=[[Stereogum]]|date=April 10, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020|author=DeVille, Chris}}</ref>\n\n== Musical style ==\n[[File:StrokesOhana270919-79 (48829452577).jpg|right|300px|thumb|[[Eddie Vedder]] singing with The Strokes in Ohana Festival, 2019]]\nThe band's sound has been described as [[indie rock]],<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/artists/the-strokes|title=The Strokes \u2013 They saved Indie!|magazine=[[Clash Magazine|Clash]]|accessdate=March 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/7704-the-decade-in-indie/|title=The Decade in Indie|work=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=May 2, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2012/jan/16/indie-rock-slow-painful-death|title=Indie rock's slow and painful death|last=Lynskey|first=Dorian|date=January 16, 2012|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=April 26, 2012}}</ref> [[garage rock revival]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/472408/top-10-garage-rock-revival-bands-where-are-they-now|title=Top 10 Garage Rock Revival Bands: Where Are They Now?|date=March 23, 2011|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 28, 2016|author=Lipshutz, Jason}}</ref> and [[post-punk revival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/kayley-kravitz/post-punk-revival-_b_2003987.html|title=Revisiting the Post-Punk Revival|date=December 23, 2015|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=December 28, 2016|author=Kravitz, Kayley}}</ref> by the media. Casablancas has cited [[Lou Reed]] of [[The Velvet Underground]] as a major influence on his lyrics and singing style. \"The way Lou Reed wrote and sang about drugs and sex, about the people around him \u2014 it was so matter-of-fact,\" Casablancas stated in a ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' interview. \"Reed could be romantic in the way he portrayed these crazy situations, but he was also intensely real. It was poetry and journalism.\" Additionally, he has stated that [[Bob Marley]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2010/08/drinks-with-julian-casablancas/|title=Drinks With: Julian Casablancas|last=Matheny|first=Skip|date=August 2, 2010|website=American Songwriter|publisher=AmericanSongwriter.com|accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref> [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] and [[Pearl Jam]] are major influences on his work, the latter being the reason that he started making music after hearing the song \"[[Yellow Ledbetter]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-strokes-elegantly-wasted-20031113|title=The Strokes: Elegantly Wasted|last=Strauss|first=Neil|date=November 13, 2003|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=September 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy and influence ==\nThe Strokes' debut album ''Is This It'' was named number one album of the year by [[NME]] and number two by ''[[Rolling Stone]],'' ''Is This It'' earned Casablancas and The Strokes tremendous respect across various artists in the alternative music scene''.''<ref name=\":5\" /> Lead singer of [[LCD Soundsystem]], [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]], has said, \"''Is This It'' was my record of the decade.\"<ref name=\":5\" /> The album won Best International Album in 2002, nominated by NME, and ASCAP College Vanguard Award.<ref>{{Citation|title=List of awards and nominations received by The Strokes|date=2017-11-25|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=List_of_awards_and_nominations_received_by_The_Strokes&oldid=811948429|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref>\n\nThe Strokes have been said to be, \"as influential to their era as the Velvet Underground or the Ramones were to theirs,\u201d by Lizzie Goodman in her book on the New York City music scene, claiming that, \"almost every artist I interviewed for this book \u2014 from all over the world \u2014 said it was the Strokes that opened the door for them.\"<ref name=\":7\" /> The band was named Band of the Year in 2002 by ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' and have heavily influenced bands like [[The Killers]], [[Arctic Monkeys]], and [[Franz Ferdinand (band)|Franz Ferdinand.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/nov/26/the-strokes-is-this-it|title=Albums of the decade No 4: The Strokes \u2013 Is This It|last=Mulholland|first=Garry|date=2009-11-26|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==Band members==\n* [[Julian Casablancas]] \u2013 lead vocals <small>(1998\u2013present)</small>, keyboards <small>(2010\u2013present)</small>\n*[[Nikolai Fraiture]] \u2013 bass <small>(1998\u2013present)</small>\n*[[Albert Hammond Jr.]] \u2013 guitars <small>(1998\u2013present)</small>, backing vocals <small>(2010\u2013present)</small>\n*[[Fabrizio Moretti]] \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(1998\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Nick Valensi]] \u2013 guitars <small>(1998\u2013present)</small>, backing vocals <small>(2010\u2013present)</small>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|The Strokes discography}}\n* ''[[Is This It]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Room on Fire]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[First Impressions of Earth]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Angles (The Strokes album)|Angles]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Comedown Machine]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[The New Abnormal]]'' (2020)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by The Strokes}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{The Strokes}}\n{{Julian Casablancas}}\n{{Albert Hammond Jr.}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Rock music|New York City}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Strokes, The}}\n[[Category:1998 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:The Strokes| ]]\n[[Category:Indie rock musical groups from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from New York City]]\n[[Category:Post-punk revival music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1998]]\n[[Category:RCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:Rough Trade Records artists]]\n[[Category:NME Awards winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American rock band}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = The Strokes\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = The Strokes by Roger Woolman.jpg\n| landscape        = Yes\n| caption          = The Strokes in 2002; left to right: [[Nick Valensi]], [[Albert Hammond Jr.]], [[Julian Casablancas]], [[Fabrizio Moretti]], and [[Nikolai Fraiture]]\n| origin           = [[New York City|New York, New York]], U.S.\n| genre            = <!-- these genres are sourced in the musical style section of the text -->{{hlist|[[Indie rock]]|[[garage rock revival]]|[[post-punk revival]]}}\n| years_active     = {{start date|1998}}\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Cult Records|Cult]]|[[RCA Records|RCA]]|[[Rough Trade Records|Rough Trade]]}}\n| associated_acts  = <!--The Voidz are NOT an associated act per Template:Infobox musical artist#associated_acts; please follow the guidelines there for what belongs in this field-->\n| website          = {{URL|thestrokes.com}}\n| current_members  = {{unbulleted list|[[Julian Casablancas]]|[[Nick Valensi]]|[[Albert Hammond Jr.]]|[[Nikolai Fraiture]]|[[Fabrizio Moretti]]}}\n}}\n\n'''The Strokes''' are an American [[Rock music|rock]] band from [[New York City]]. Formed in 1998, the band is composed of singer [[Julian Casablancas]],   guitarists [[Nick Valensi]] and [[Albert Hammond, Jr.|Albert Hammond Jr.]], bassist [[Nikolai Fraiture]], and drummer [[Fabrizio Moretti]]. Following the conclusion of five-album deals with [[RCA Records|RCA]] and [[Rough Trade Records|Rough Trade]], the band has continued to release new music through Casablancas' [[Cult Records]].\n\nThe band's debut album, ''[[Is This It]]'' (2001),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infoplease.com/biography/var/thestrokes.html |title=The Strokes at |publisher=Infoplease.com |date= |accessdate=October 22, 2011}}</ref> was met with widespread critical acclaim and helped usher in the [[garage rock revival]] movement of the early 21st century; it was ranked No. 8 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s 100 \"Best Debut Albums of All Time\",<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-100-greatest-debut-albums-of-all-time-20130322 |title=The 100 Best Debut Albums of All Time |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=June 17, 2013}}</ref> No. 2 on ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s \"100 Best Albums of the '00s\",<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-best-albums-of-the-2000s-20110718/the-strokes-is-this-it-20110715 |title=100 Best Albums of the 2000s: The Strokes, 'Is This It' |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=July 11, 2014}}</ref> No. 199 on ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s \"[[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]]\", and No. 4 on ''[[NME]]''{{'s}} \"Top 500 Albums of All Time\".\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation and ''The Modern Age'' EP (1998\u20132001)===\nLead singer-songwriter [[Julian Casablancas]], guitarist [[Nick Valensi]], and drummer [[Fabrizio Moretti]] started playing together while attending [[Dwight School]] in [[Manhattan]]. Bassist [[Nikolai Fraiture]] befriended Casablancas while the two attended the [[Lyc\u00e9e Fran\u00e7ais de New York]]. At age 13, Casablancas was sent to [[Institut Le Rosey|Le Rosey]], a boarding school in [[Switzerland]], to improve his academic performance. There, he met guitarist [[Albert Hammond, Jr.]] Later, when Hammond came to New York to attend [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]], he shared an apartment with Casablancas. The roommates started a band, first performing at HiFi Bar, then The Spiral, followed by the [[Luna Lounge]] on the [[Lower East Side]] of New York, and then at Manhattan's popular [[Mercury Lounge]]. The Mercury Lounge's booker, [[Ryan Gentles]], quit his job to become the band's manager.<ref>Bush, B. (August 2002). The strokes. Music Connection, 26, 32\u201335.</ref>\n\nThe band began rehearsing a fourteen-song set (an early blueprint of the Strokes\u2019 2001 debut, ''Is This It'')\u2014including, \"Alone, Together,\" \"Barely Legal,\" \"[[Last Nite]],\" \"[[The Modern Age]],\" \"New York City Cops,\" \"Soma,\" \"[[Someday (The Strokes song)|Someday]],\" \"Take It or Leave It,\" and \"This Life\" (an early version of \"Trying Your Luck\"). Most of these songs now feature different [[lyrics]]. The band sent a demo to the newly reformed [[Rough Trade Records]] in the UK, sparking interest there, and leading to their first release (via the website of the UK magazine, ''[[NME]],'' who gave away a free mp3 download of \"[[Last Nite]]\" a week prior to the physical release as part of ''[[The Modern Age]]'' [[Extended play|EP]] in 2001). The EP sparked a bidding war among [[record label]]s, the largest for a rock band in years.<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtve.com/article.php?ArticleId=4690|title=the Strokes: \"We Just Do Our Own Thing\"|accessdate=January 23, 2007|year=2001|author=Joe D'Angelo|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211070125/http://www.mtve.com/article.php?ArticleId=4690|archivedate=February 11, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In August 2001, the Strokes made their first appearance on the cover of the publication ''[[The Fader]]'' in its ninth issue.<ref>{{cite magazine\n  | title = Fader 50: New York Rock\n  | magazine = The Fader\n  | date = November 26, 2007\n  | url = http://www.thefader.com/2007/11/26/fader-50-new-york-rock/\n  | accessdate=November 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===''Is This It''  (2001\u20132002) ===\n\nThe Strokes released their debut album, ''[[Is This It]],'' in the US in October 2001. The album was produced by Gordon Raphael, as was their follow-up album ''[[Room On Fire]]''. [[RCA]] delayed the North American (US) release over concerns with the album's cover and lyrics. The UK-released cover features a [[black-and-white]] photo of a gloved hand on a woman's naked backside, shown in semi-profile (photographer Colin Lane's then-girlfriend)<ref>The strokes: Never mind the buttocks ... (August 12, 2006). ''NME'' \u2013 ''New Musical Express'', 27.</ref> while the North American version replaced it with a photo of particle collisions in the [[Big European Bubble Chamber]]. RCA replaced the track \"New York City Cops\" with \"When It Started\", as the former featured potentially inflammatory lyrics in the wake of the  [[September 11 attacks]]. The track \"New York City Cops\"\u2014featuring the refrain, \"New York City Cops, they ain't too smart\"\u2014was listed as No. 12 on ''New York'' magazine's \"Ultimate New York Playlist\" on March 1, 2010. Despite its delayed release (and the potential controversy), ''Is This It'' received critical acclaim\u2014among other accolades, four stars from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', and a 9.1 from [[Pitchfork Media]]. The album made many critics' top-ten lists, was named the best album of the year by ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' and ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', and (in an article previewing summer concerts) ''[[NME]]'' urged readers to attend the Strokes\u2019 shows\u2014as they were touring some of the \"best pop songs ever\". While critics noted the influence of [[CBGB]] stalwarts [[Television (band)|Television]], Casablancas and bandmates said they had never heard the band, instead citing [[the Velvet Underground]] as a reference point.\n\nAfter the release of ''Is This It'', the band toured around the world\u2014including [[Japan]], [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[Europe]], and [[North America]] (the band opened for the [[Rolling Stones]] on numerous occasions during the North American leg of their tour). The self-made mini-documentary \"In Transit\" was filmed during the summer tour of Europe. In August 2002, the band headlined the UK's [[Carling Weekend]] festivals for the second time, subsequently playing at New York's [[Radio City Music Hall]] on a bill with [[the White Stripes]]. [[Jack White (musician)|Jack White]] joined the Strokes on stage to perform the guitar solo on \"New York City Cops\". During that period, the band also appeared as musical guests on numerous late-night talk shows. ''Is This It'' yielded several singles and music videos, all of which were directed by [[Roman Coppola]].\n\n[[File:Nick valensi 2dollarbill.jpg|thumb|left|Valensi at [[MTV]] 2 Dollar Bill 2002]]\n''Is This It'' has had an enduring impact on fans and critics alike. In 2009, ''NME'' named ''Is This It'' as the Greatest Album of the Decade (2000s).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/48412 |title=The Strokes' 'Is This It' tops NME albums of the decade list &#124; News |publisher=Nme.Com |date=November 17, 2009 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref>  The album placed second on a similar list compiled by ''Rolling Stone'' (the same issue featured a list of the '100 Best Songs of the 00's', featuring \"[[Hard to Explain]]\" and \"[[Last Nite]]\"  at Nos.&nbsp;59 and&nbsp;16, respectively).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stereogum.com/105081/rolling_stones_100_best_albums_songs_of_the_00s/list/ |title=Rolling Stone's 100 Best Albums, Songs Of The '00s |website=Stereogum |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> In January 2011, Rolling Stone conducted a survey among their [[Facebook]] fans to determine the top ten debut albums of all time. ''Is This It'' came in at number ten and was also the most recent behind [[Pearl Jam]]'s 1991 [[Ten (Pearl Jam album)|debut]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/photos/rolling-stones-facebook-fans-name-top-10-debut-albums-20110126/10-the-strokes-is-this-it-0071099 |title=Rolling Stone's Facebook Fans Name Top 10 Debut Albums: 10. The Strokes, 'Is This It' &#124; Rolling Stone Music &#124; Photos |magazine=Rollingstone.com |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> As of 2010, ''Is This It'' had sold over 3.5{{Citation needed|date=April 2012}}&nbsp;million copies worldwide.\n\n===''Room on Fire'' (2003\u20132004)===\nThe group began recording their follow-up in 2002 with producer [[Nigel Godrich]] (best known for his work with [[Radiohead]]), but later split with him in favor of Gordon Raphael, the producer of ''Is This It''. Recordings with Godrich were never revealed.<ref>Molenda, M. (2003, 12). Electric warriors: The strokes' albert hammond, jr. and nick valensi play it like it is. Guitar Player, 37, 70\u201376, 78.</ref> In August 2003, the band toured Japan, playing a couple of the upcoming songs: \"[[Reptilia (song)|Reptilia]]\", \"Meet Me In The Bathroom\", \"The Way It Is\", \"Between Love & Hate\" (formerly known as \"Ze Newie\") and \"[[12:51 (The Strokes song)|12:51]]\" (formerly known as \"Supernova\"). The band also played [[Paul Anka]]'s \"My Way\" with Japanese lyrics. The Strokes released their second album ''[[Room on Fire]]'' in October 2003. It received praise from critics but was less commercially successful, although it still went gold. The album's sound maintained the Strokes' familiar reference points{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}}, while also evoking groups such as [[the Cars]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mitchum |first1=Rob |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/7538-room-on-fire/ |title=The Strokes: Room On Fire |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=October 26, 2003 |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref> [[Bob Marley]],<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Tyrangiel |first1=Josh |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,524476,00.html |title=Different Strokes? |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]] |date=October 19, 2003 |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref> and [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]]<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Milner |first1=Greg |url=https://www.spin.com/2003/11/strokes-room-fire-rca/ |title=The Strokes, 'Room On Fire' (RCA) |magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date=November 21, 2003 |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref> In the process, they made the cover of ''[[Spin Magazine]]'' for the second time, with each member receiving his own cover. They also made the cover of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' for the first time. Additional media coverage of the band came from the relationship between Moretti and actress [[Drew Barrymore]], which ended in January 2007. The first single taken from ''Room on Fire'' was the song \"[[12:51 (The Strokes song)|12:51]]\", which used distinct keyboard-like sounds produced by Valensi's guitar. The video was also directed by Roman Coppola, and was inspired by the futuristic look of the 1980s film ''[[Tron]]''. This consisted of a mainly black scene, with instances of glowing picton blue and riptide.\n\nIn November 2003, the Strokes played on ''Late Night with Conan O'Brien'', performing \"[[Reptilia (song)|Reptilia]]\", \"What Ever Happened\", \"Under Control\" and \"I Can't Win\".<ref>DeRogatis, J. (2004, 04). The strokes' fabrizio moretti: Sculpting rock 'N' roll. Modern Drummer, 28, 62\u201366, 68, 70.</ref> During the 2003/2004 \"''Room on Fire'' Tour\", the band played with [[Kings of Leon]] as support act and [[Regina Spektor]]. While on tour, Spektor and the Strokes recorded the song \"[[Modern Girls & Old Fashion Men]]\", released as a B-side on the \"Reptilia\" single. Also during the tour, the band included [[the Clash]]'s \"Clampdown\" as a cover, which was released as the B-side for \"[[The End Has No End]]\".\n\nIn late 2004, the Strokes revealed plans to release a live album. The ''Live in London'' LP was planned for release in October 2004, but was abandoned, reportedly due to recording quality problems. The chosen gig was one held at the legendary [[Alexandra Palace]] in North London.\n\n=== ''First Impressions of Earth'' and hiatus (2005\u20132007) ===\n[[File:The Strokes in concert.jpg|right|250px|thumb|The Strokes in concert, 2006]]\nIn late September 2005, \"[[Juicebox (song)|Juicebox]]\", the first single from the Strokes' then unreleased third album, was leaked online, forcing the single's release date to be advanced. The single was then released as an exclusive on online download services. \"Juicebox\" became the Strokes' second UK Top 10 hit, as well as their second US Modern Rock Top 10 success. During November and December 2005 the Strokes did a promotional tour for the still unreleased album, which involved doing one-off shows in major cities around the world. Their third album, ''[[First Impressions of Earth]]'', was released on December 30, 2005, in Germany<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.laut.de/The-Strokes/Alben/First-Impressions-Of-Earth-11120 |title=\"First Impressions of Earth\" von The Strokes |last=Butscher |first=Vicky |website=[[Laut.de]] |language=German |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> and January 3, 2006, elsewhere.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/first-impressions-of-earth-mw0000339306 |title=First Impressions of Earth - The Strokes |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> It received mixed reviews and debuted at number four in the US and number one in the UK, the latter being a first for the band. In Japan, it went gold within the first week of release. It was also the most downloaded album for two weeks on iTunes. Fraiture claimed that the album was \"like a scientific breakthrough\". In January 2006, the band then made their second appearance on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' playing \"Juicebox\" and \"[[You Only Live Once (The Strokes song)|You Only Live Once]]\". The album was somewhat a departure from the band's two previous albums. One reason for this was a switch of producers from Gordon Raphael to David Kahne.<ref>Marchese, D. (January 2006). Music: Onward and into the audioscape \u2013 the strokes upgrade their cute dischevelment but leave a few too many sexy hooks behind. The Village Voice, 51, C81.</ref> Despite its initial strong sales, ''First Impressions of Earth'' received the worst reception, both commercially and critically, of all their albums.\n\nIn 2006, the band played 18 sold-out shows during their UK tour. In February 2006, the Strokes won \"Best International Band\" at the NME Awards. In March, the band returned to the US with their longest tour yet. The second single off ''First Impressions of Earth'', \"Heart in a Cage\", was released in March 2006. During the summer of 2006, the Strokes played several festival dates in Europe, including the Hultsfred Festival in Sweden, [[Roskilde Festival]] in Denmark, the [[Oxegen Festival]] in Ireland, the [[Montreux Jazz Festival]] in Switzerland, the FIB ([[Festival Internacional de Benic\u00e0ssim]]), [[Fuji Rock Festival]] and headlined the [[Pentaport Rock Festival]] in South Korea. They then toured Australia and Mexico in late August and early September, followed by the second leg of the United States tour. While in the US, the Strokes opened for [[Tom Petty & the Heartbreakers]] for five shows during their Highway Companion tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2006/07/tom-petty-adds-sept-dates-strokes-frank-black/ |title=Tom Petty Adds Sept. Dates with Strokes, Frank Black |publisher=Spin.com |date=July 7, 2006 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> The Strokes went on to complete another US tour. During this final tour Casablancas stated to fans that the band would be taking an extensive break after it finished. An e-mail was sent out soon afterwards by Strokes manager [[Ryan Gentles]], confirming that \"much needed break\". A new band website went online in May 2007 along with the release of an alternate video to their single \"You Only Live Once\" directed by [[Warren Fu]]. The video also featured a brief interlude with \"Ize of the World\", also from ''First Impressions of Earth''. The song \"You Talk Way Too Much\" was used in a commercial for the Ford Sync. Aleksandra Cisneros became the Strokes' assistant manager in late 2007.\n\n===''Angles'' (2009\u20132011)===\n[[File:Julian Casablancas Belfort 2010.jpg|thumb|right|Julian Casablancas, frontman of The Strokes, at [[Eurock\u00e9ennes]] 2010]]\nThe Strokes frontman Julian Casablancas and guitarist Nick Valensi started writing material for the album in January 2009, intent on entering the studio that February.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/42301|title=NME: The Strokes: 'We've started writing our fourth album'|publisher=NME.com|author=NME Staff|date=|accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref> Julian commented in ''Rolling Stone'' that they had completed about three songs that sounded like a mixture of [[Rock music#Post-punk|1970s rock]] and \"music from the future\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/blogs/smokingsection/2009/03/the-strokes-are-back-in-action.php |title=Blogs |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> On March 31, 2009 from their MySpace account, the band announced the end of their \"much needed hibernation period\" and the commencement of new writing and rehearsing for a fourth full-length album, entitled ''[[Angles (The Strokes album)|Angles]]''. This album would be different from the first three in that it would feature music written by the other four Strokes, rather than Casablancas writing ninety-five percent of the material again: \"It's supercollaborative, and it sounds different,\" said Valensi, \"but it has a Strokes vibe to it.\"<ref>Scaggs, A. (April 29, 2010). 40 reasons to be excited about music: No. 21 \u2013 the strokes are getting it back together. Rolling Stone, 80.</ref> In an ''NME'' article, [[Pharrell Williams]] expressed interest in producing this upcoming album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/pharrell-williams/37303 |title=Pharrell Williams: 'I want to produce the Strokes' new album' &#124; News |publisher=Nme.Com |date=June 13, 2008 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> This followed the news that Casablancas had collaborated with Williams and [[Santigold]] on \"[[My Drive Thru]]\", a track commemorating the 100th anniversary of [[Converse (company)|Converse]]'s [[Chuck Taylor All-Stars]] shoe. The song was available as a free download from the official Converse site.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stereogum.com/archives/new-santogold-julian-casablances-pharrell-my-drive_010274.html |title=New Santogold, Julian Casablancas & Pharrell \u2013 \"My Drive Thru\" |website=Stereogum |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> The album was due to be released in late 2009, but disagreements about the songs' readiness forced the Strokes to scale back this date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/news/the-strokes-disagreement-over-new-album |title=The Strokes' \"Disagreement\" Over New Album \u2013 23 Oct 2009 &#124; Clash Music Latest Breaking Music News |publisher=Clashmusic.com |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> On February 1, 2010, the Strokes announced on their website that the recording of the fourth album was being helmed by award-winning producer [[Joe Chiccarelli]]. According to Chiccarelli in an interview with [[HitQuarters]], the two camps first met in 2009 and, after finding they shared a similar mind space and similar thoughts on the potential direction of the new record, tried out some tracking.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_Joe_Chiccarelli_Interview.html |title=Interview with Joe Chiccarelli |publisher=[[HitQuarters]]|date=June 14, 2010 |accessdate=August 17, 2010}}</ref>  Not long after recording began, however, the band became frustrated with Chiccarelli's reserved production style.  Only one song from these recording sessions, \"Life Is Simple in the Moonlight\", remained on the album's track listing.  Inspired, in part, by bands like [[MGMT]], [[Arctic Monkeys]], and [[Crystal Castles (band)|Crystal Castles]], the Strokes decided to experiment with various production techniques,<ref>{{cite web |last=Costigan |first=Mark |url=http://oregonmusicnews.com/blog/2011/02/02/the-strokes-nikolai-fraiture-talks-about-new-album-reveals-track-listing/ |title=The Strokes' Nikolai Fraiture talks about new album, reveals track listing |publisher=Oregon Music News |date=February 2, 2011 |accessdate=July 9, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723203937/http://oregonmusicnews.com/blog/2011/02/02/the-strokes-nikolai-fraiture-talks-about-new-album-reveals-track-listing/ |archivedate=July 23, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and recorded the rest of the album's material at Albert Hammond, Jr.'s home studio in upstate New York with award-winning engineer Gus Oberg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/49559 |title=The Strokes begin recording fourth album with U2, Beck producer &#124; News |publisher=Nme.Com |date=February 3, 2010 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Strokes confirmed that they would be headlining the [[Isle of Wight Festival]], [[Lollapalooza]], [[Roskilde Festival]],<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2010/03/11/the-strokes-confirm-lollapalooza-slot-report-in-on-next-album/|title=The Stokes Confirm Lollapalooza Slot, Report In on Next Album|magazine=Rolling Stone|last=Kreps|first=Daniel|date=March 11, 2010|accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> [[Hurricane Festival]], [[Splendour In The Grass]], [[Rockness]], [[Outside Lands Music and Arts Festival]],<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/abraham/detail??blogid=95&entry_id=64802 | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | title=Outside Lands Festival San Francisco schedule released today | date=June 1, 2010}}</ref> On The Bright Side,<ref>{{cite web |author=gea-interactive.com.au |url=http://www.onthebrightside.com.au/ |title=Splash |publisher=On The Bright Side |accessdate=July 9, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110822050858/http://onthebrightside.com.au/ |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and [[Austin City Limits Music Festival]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://2010.aclfestival.com/ |title=ACL 2010 |publisher=2010.aclfestival.com |accessdate=July 9, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120707161957/http://2010.aclfestival.com/ |archivedate=July 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> in 2010.  Additionally, the Strokes were announced as the 2011 headliner for the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]] and the [[New Orleans Jazz & Heritage Festival]] in May, [[Festival Internacional de Benic\u00e0ssim]], [[Oxegen]], [[Pal\u00e9o Festival|Pal\u00e9o]], [[Peace & Love (festival)|Peace & Love]] and [[Super Bock Super Rock]] in July, and [[Reading Festival]] and [[Summer Sonic]] in August. They were also sub-headliners to [[Pulp (band)|Pulp]] at [[Leeds Festival]] during the bank holiday weekend in August. On June 9, 2010, at [[Dingwalls]] London, England, the band played a secret show under the name 'Venison' to a crowd of just 487. This was their first live gig since October 2006. The band did not play any new material.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/51445 |title=The Strokes play first gig in four years at intimate London venue &#124; News |publisher=Nme.Com |date=June 9, 2010 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe lead single from the new album, \"[[Under Cover of Darkness]]\", was released on February 9, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/54874 |title=The Strokes to release 'Under Cover Of Darkness' as free download &#124; News |publisher=Nme.Com |date=February 8, 2011 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> The 7\" was officially released on March 1, 2011 and contained another track from ''[[Angles (The Strokes album)|Angles]]'', \"You're So Right\", as the B-side, followed by the album on March 18, 2011.\n\"[[Taken for a Fool]]\" was confirmed as the second single, which was sent to U.S. radio on May 24, 2011. On June 9, the Strokes announced that a music video for \"Taken For a Fool\" was in the works, and that it is directed by Laurent Briet. They revealed that the music video should be finished by the end of the month. The Strokes put out the music video for \"Taken For a Fool\" on July 8, 2011. In mid-March 2011, an interview with ''[[ShortList]]'' magazine revealed that the Strokes had already begun working on their fifth studio album. However, sessions were delayed due to the mixing process of ''Angles''. Julian Casablancas and Nick Valensi both confirmed that there was material in the works as well as plenty of leftover material.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shortlist.com/entertainment/music/article/1144/the-strokes-return#image-rotator-3|title=The Strokes Return / Music / ShortList Magazine|date=February 17, 2011|publisher=Shortlist.com|accessdate=July 9, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110401121042/http://www.shortlist.com/entertainment/music/article/1144/the-strokes-return#image-rotator-3|archive-date=April 1, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Frontman Julian Casablancas claimed that the band was eager to begin working on new material<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/56306|title=The Strokes hit the studio to work on 'new ideas'|date=April 25, 2011|publisher=Nme.com|accessdate=October 22, 2011}}</ref> and were already supposed to, but it took longer than expected to master ''Angles''.\n\n===''Comedown Machine'' (2012\u22122015)===\n[[File:Thestrokes2010.jpg|thumb|320px|left|The Strokes at Austin City Limits Festival in 2010]]\nIn April 2012, bassist Nikolai Fraiture posted a tweet announcing that the band was heading into the studio to work on some new ideas.<ref>{{cite web|last=Breihan |first=Tom |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/42351-the-strokes-at-work-on-new-music/ |title=The Strokes at Work on New Music |website=Pitchfork |date=April 27, 2011 |accessdate=October 22, 2011}}</ref> The Strokes later revealed that they were planning to record a new album as soon as possible. Fraiture added that the band would record their fifth album in the same manner as they put together ''Angles'', with each member bringing in his own ideas and putting them together in the studio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/57464 |title=The Strokes planning to record new album 'as soon as possible' &#124; News |publisher=Nme.Com |date=June 21, 2011 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> On January 17, 2013, Seattle alternative radio station [[KNDD|107.7 The End]] posted on their Facebook page that they were previewing a new song by the Strokes entitled \"[[All the Time (The Strokes song)|All the Time]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Previewing brand new Strokes \"All the Time\" thanks to RCA Records. We'll have to \"leak\" this soon. You won't be disappointed...|url=http://www.facebook.com/1077theend/posts/10151266805345073|accessdate=January 17, 2013}}</ref> It was later confirmed that \"All the Time\" would be the lead single from the untitled fifth album.<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite magazine|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|title=The Strokes To Release Fifth Album Later This Year: Update|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1501292/the-strokes-to-release-fifth-album-later-this-year-update|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=January 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"consequence\">{{cite web|last=Roffman|first=Michael|title=The Strokes to release new single, 'All the Time'|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/01/the-strokes-to-release-new-single-all-the-time/|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|accessdate=January 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"KNDD\">{{cite web|title=Details: New Strokes Album On The Way|url=http://www.1077theend.com/Details--New-Strokes-Album-On-The-Way/11684758?pid=290511|work=[[KNDD|107.7 The End]]|publisher=[[Entercom Communications]]|accessdate=January 17, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121103407/http://www.1077theend.com/Details--New-Strokes-Album-On-The-Way/11684758?pid=290511|archivedate=January 21, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On January 25, 2013, the song \"[[One Way Trigger]]\" was published on their official website, and made available for free download.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/68365|title=The Strokes unveil new song 'One Way Trigger'&nbsp;\u2013 listen|date=January 25, 2013|publisher=NME.com}}</ref> The song was initially met with a mixed reaction from fans of the band.<ref>{{cite web| title = Fans react to \"weird\" return of The Strokes| work = [[NME]]| publisher = [[IPC Media]]| date = January 26, 2013| url = http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/68374| accessdate = January 28, 2013}}</ref> On January 28, a [[Reddit]] user discovered what he correctly assumed to be the new album cover within the subpages of the band's official website, which led to a widespread rumor that the new album would be titled ''Comedown Machine''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/68438|title=The Strokes name new album 'Comedown Machine'?|date=January 30, 2013|publisher=NME.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jan/31/strokes-scooped-new-comedown-machine-album|title=The Strokes scooped on new Comedown Machine album|date=January 31, 2013|work=guardian.co.uk}}</ref> On January 30, the title for the fifth album was revealed to be ''[[Comedown Machine]]'', set to be released on March 26 in the U.S. and March 25 in the UK.<ref name=\"CoS\">{{cite web|last=Young|first=Alex|title=The Strokes to release new album Comedown Machine on March 26th|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/01/the-strokes-to-release-new-album-comedown-machine-on-march-26th/|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|accessdate=January 30, 2013}}</ref> On February 13, 2013, the first single from the band's fifth album premiered on the radio, named \"All the Time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stereogum.com/1259602/the-strokes-all-the-time/mp3s/ |title=The Strokes \u2013 \"All The Time\" |website=Stereogum |date=February 13, 2013 |accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref> The single was released for download on February 19, and was described as a return to the classic Strokes sound of first albums ''Is This It'' and ''Room on Fire''. The album was released on March 25, 2013 in the UK and March 26 in the United States. The band decided to pull a media blackout with the album: no promotion in the form of TV appearances, interviews, photos, shows, or tours. On October 15, 2013, the band revealed that they were looking to \"return to the scene\" in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicblogged.com/the-strokes-new-album-and-tour-2014/ |title=The Strokes new album and tour 2014|publisher=Music Blogged |date=October 15, 2013 |accessdate=October 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, the Strokes performed their first U.S. show in three years at the [[Capitol Theatre (Port Chester, New York)|Capitol Theatre]] in [[Port Chester, New York]], performing songs from ''Comedown Machine'' for the first time. The band played at three other shows in 2014, including two headlining slots at [[Governors Ball Music Festival]] in [[New York City]] and [[FYF Fest]] in [[Los Angeles]]. On November 12, 2014, it was announced the band would headline [[Primavera Sound]] in 2015 for the festival's 15th anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nme.Com |url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/81023 |title=The Strokes confirmed for Primavera Sound festival 2015 |website=Nme.com |date= |accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> On March 2, 2015, the band announced their second 2015 European festival headline appearance would be at [[London]]'s annual [[Hyde Park, London#Events|British Summer Time: Hyde Park festival]] on June 18, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neverenoughnotes.co.uk/2015/03/the-strokes-british-summer-time-hyde-park/ |title=The Strokes to play British Summer Time Hyde Park this summer|publisher=Never Enough Notes |date=October 15, 2013 |accessdate=March 2, 2015}}</ref> the band's first London show in five years.<ref>{{cite news|author=Daisy Wyatt |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/bst-hyde-park-2015-the-strokes-join-taylor-swift-and-blur-as-headliners-10079399.html |title=The Strokes join Blur and Taylor Swift to headline BST Hyde Park 2015 &#124; News &#124; Culture |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date= |accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> The announcement takes the band's number of appearances slated for 2015 up to six, with them also playing Big Guava Music Festival in [[Tampa, Florida]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestrokes.com/us/news/big-guava-music-festival |title=Archived copy |accessdate=March 9, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150303204717/http://www.thestrokes.com/us/news/big-guava-music-festival |archivedate=March 3, 2015 }}</ref> Shaky Knees Festival in [[Atlanta, Georgia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestrokes.com/us/news/shaky-knees-festival |title=Archived copy |accessdate=March 9, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217031553/http://www.thestrokes.com/us/news/shaky-knees-festival |archivedate=February 17, 2015 }}</ref> Landmark Festival in [[Washington, D.C.]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestrokes.com/us/event/2015/09/26/landmark-music-festival |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 15, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150715115725/http://www.thestrokes.com/us/event/2015/09/26/landmark-music-festival |archivedate=July 15, 2015 }}</ref> and Austin City Limits in [[Austin, Texas]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestrokes.com/us/event/2015/10/02/acl-2015 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 15, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150715111805/http://www.thestrokes.com/us/event/2015/10/02/acl-2015 |archivedate=July 15, 2015 }}</ref> as well as the previously announced Primavera Sound 15th Anniversary. During their performance at Landmark Music Festival lead singer Julian Casablancas stated that the band is back in the studio working on a follow up to their 2013 album ''Comedown Machine''. In late 2015, the Strokes announced another date; at Monterrey, Mexico, during the festivities of the newborn festival Live Out.\n\n===''Future Present Past'' EP (2016\u20132017)===\nThe Strokes played their first show of 2016 at Samsung's Galaxy Life Fest in Austin, Texas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sxsw.com/news/2016/samsung-announces-galaxy-life-fest-sxsw-interactive|title=Samsung Reveals Galaxy Life Fest at SXSW Interactive With Public Enemy, The Strokes, and More|website=South by Southwest 2016 Music, Film and Interactive Festivals - Austin Texas|access-date=April 17, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160428040404/http://www.sxsw.com/news/2016/samsung-announces-galaxy-life-fest-sxsw-interactive|archivedate=April 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \nOn May 24, 2016, the Strokes announced another New York show on 31 May at the [[Capitol Theatre (Port Chester, New York)|Capitol Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/thestrokes/status/735146115847200771 |title=The Strokes on Twitter: \"New York\u2026don't make plans next Tuesday. We're playing @capitoltheatre on 5/31, can't wait to see y'all!\" |publisher=Twitter |date=May 24, 2016 |accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:StrokesCorona161119-49 (49081371357).jpg|thumb|320px|right|The Strokes performing at Corona Capital, 2019]]\nOn May 26, 2016, Julian Casablancas premiered \u201cOBLIVIUS\u201d on the debut of his monthly radio show, \"Culture Void\", on [[Sirius XMU]]. [[Cult Records]] announced the release of ''[[Future Present Past]]'', a four-song EP by the Strokes, in addition to the exclusive signing of the band to its roster. The EP includes three original songs (\u201cDrag Queen\u201d, \u201cOBLIVIUS\u201d, and \u201cThreat of Joy\u201d), along with an additional remix of \u201cOBLIVIUS\u201d by drummer, Fab Moretti. The EP was released on June 3, in both digital and physical formats to coincide with the band's headlining performance at [[Governors Ball Music Festival]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-strokes/90667|title=The Strokes confirm first live date of 2016 {{!}} NME.COM|last=NME.COM|website=NME.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=April 17, 2016}}</ref> \"Future Present Past\" was recorded over the past year in Austin and New York with the help of producer, Gus Oberg.\n\nThe band played at the [[Splendour in the Grass]] festival in [[Byron Bay, New South Wales|Byron Bay,]] [[Australia]] on July 22, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diymag.com/2016/04/13/the-strokes-james-blake-the-cure-splendour-in-the-grass-2016|title=The Strokes, James Blake and The Cure to play Splendour In The Grass 2016|website=DIY|access-date=April 17, 2016}}</ref> They followed this performance with the inaugural City of Angels Benefit concert in Los Angeles to support charities such as Waste Not Want Not Now, the Center in Hollywood, and the Downtown's Women's Center on July 25, 2016.\n\nThe band performed a series of festival dates taking place throughout early 2017. Festival dates include performances in [[Est\u00e9reo Picnic Festival]] as well as [[Lollapalooza|Lollapalooza Brasil]], [[Lollapalooza Chile]], and [[Lollapalooza Argentina]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thestrokes.com/|title=The Strokes|website=The Strokes|language=en-US|access-date=April 20, 2017}}</ref> The band's first live performance of the year took place headlining the [[Est\u00e9reo Picnic Festival]]. The crowd in attendance of their Argentina show was reportedly a volume of 90,000 people. After the Lollapalooza Argentina show it was revealed that their headlining slot at the festival was, to this day, their \"biggest show ever\" by Fraiture on social media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/the-strokes-biggest-show-of-career-lollapalooza-argentina-footage-2032607|title=Watch The Strokes play the \"biggest show\" of their career in Argentina - NME|date=April 4, 2017|work=NME|access-date=April 20, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===''The New Abnormal'' (2019\u2013present)===\nIn October 2016, guitarist Valensi indicated that the band were \"slowly but surely working on an album, we\u2019re kind of just in writing sessions\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://diymag.com/2016/10/11/the-strokes-new-album-2017-nick-valensi-interview|title=The Strokes are \"slowly but surely working on an album\"|last=Konemann|first=Liam|date=October 11, 2016|website=DIY|publisher=|access-date=November 16, 2016}}</ref> In July 2017 Albert Hammond Sr. said the Strokes are working with Rick Rubin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewest.com.au/entertainment/music/albert-hammond-strokes-recording-with-rick-rubin-ng-b88549060z|title=Albert Hammond: Strokes recording with Rick Rubin|last=Collins|first=Simon|date=July 27, 2017|website=The West}}</ref> Albert Hammond Jr. took to Twitter to clarify that \u201cwe met and played a few music ideas for Rick to feel out a vibe but even a theoretical album plan would be years away, if at all.\u201d He also tweeted, \"Sorry everyone we are not in the studio recording\" and that there were \"a lot of unknowns and nothing worth speaking about at this time.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7882102/the-strokes-not-recording-rick-rubin-album|title=The Strokes Are Not Recording With Rick Rubin After All|last=Helman|first=Peter|date=July 30, 2017|website=The West}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, the band performed for the first time in over two years at a benefit show in Los Angeles. At this venue, the band debuted a new song entitled \"The Adults Are Talking\".<ref>https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-the-strokes-perform-new-song-the-adults-are-talking</ref> The show kicked off the band's \"global comeback\" tour.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Maicki |first1=Salavatore |title=The Strokes are planning a \"global comeback\" tour for 2019 |url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/12/18/the-strokes-2019-comeback-tour-bilbao |magazine=[[The Fader]] |accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Michallon |first1=Clemence |title=The Strokes 2019 concert: How to get tickets for the 'global comeback' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/the-strokes-tickets-buy-concert-spain-bilbao-bbk-festival-julian-casablancas-albert-hammond-jr-a8687931.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref> However, this tour was met with many obstacles early on, from sound issues<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Connor |first1=Roisin |title=All Points East: The Strokes gig compared to 'underwater karaoke' by fans annoyed over sound issues |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/the-strokes-all-points-east-gig-sound-quality-issues-fans-complaints-a8930761.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> to rained-out shows<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Aswad |first1=Jem |last2=Sabla |first2=Elvin |title=Governors Ball Festival Evacuated Due to Thunderstorms, Multiple Acts Cancelled |url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/governors-ball-evacuated-festival-thunderstorm-cancelled-1203231235/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> to entire festivals being cancelled.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Cantor-Navas |first1=Judy |title=Doctor Music Festival Canceled After Move From Mountain Pastures to Barcelona Racetrack |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/festivals/8515958/doctor-music-festival-canceled-barcelona |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> In September 2019, Valensi, in an interview on C104.3 Out of the Box, hinted at the production of a sixth studio album, stating \"When, I don\u2019t know. If \u2014 I would say, it\u2019s a strong likelihood.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://faroutmagazine.co.uk/the-strokes-new-album-is-finished-teases-guitarist-nick-valensi/|title=The Strokes' new album is \"finished\" according to guitarist Nick Valensi|last=Ellis|first=Nathan|date=2019-09-08|website=Far Out Magazine|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref> During the band's 2019 New Year's Eve show in Brooklyn, Casablancas announced that the band's sixth studio album would be released sometime in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/strokes-confirm-new-album-2020-2591853 |title=The Strokes confirm they have a new album coming in 2020 at New Year's Eve show |last=Lavin |first=Will |date=January 1, 2020 |website=NME |access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref> At the show, they also debuted a new song, titled \"Ode to the Mets\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2068691/the-strokes-confirm-new-album-debut-new-song-mac-demarco/video/ |title=Watch The Strokes Debut New Song \"Ode To The Mets,\" Confirm 2020 Album at Brooklyn NYE Show |last=DeVille |first=Chris |date=January 1, 2020 |website=[[Stereogum]] |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February 2020, the band performed at a rally for presidential candidate [[Bernie Sanders]] at the [[University of New Hampshire]]. At this performance, Casablancas formally announced the band's sixth studio album and that the title would be ''The New Abnormal''. He confirmed the release date of the album to be April 10 of that year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-strokes-announce-new-album-debut-songs-at-bernie-sanders-rally-watch/ |title=The Strokes Announce New Album, Debut Songs at Bernie Sanders Rally: Watch |work=Pitchfork |date=February 10, 2020 |accessdate=February 10, 2020 |author=Bloom, Madison}}</ref> The band reportedly played two new songs at this show. On February 11th, the band released a new song, \"[[At the Door]]\", the first single off of their sixth studio album.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/the-strokes-at-the-door/ |title=\"At The Door\" by The Strokes review |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=February 14, 2020 |accessdate=February 14, 2020 |author=Yoo, Noah}}</ref> Two more singles followed, \"[[Bad Decisions (The Strokes song)|Bad Decisions]]\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-the-strokes-new-song-bad-decisions/|title=Listen to the Strokes' New Song \"Bad Decisions\" |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=February 18, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |author1=Bloom, Madison |author2=Torres, Eric}}</ref> and \"[[Brooklyn Bridge to Chorus]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-strokes-brooklyn-bridge-to-chorus-978812/|title=The Strokes Go New Wave on Latest Single \u2018Brooklyn Bridge to Chorus\u2019|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=April 6, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |author=Shaffer, Claire}}</ref>. Their sixth studio album, ''[[The New Abnormal]]'', was released worldwide on April 10, 2020<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2079865/the-strokes-the-new-abnormal/music/album-stream/|title=Stream The Strokes\u2019 First Album In 7 Years, The New Abnormal|work=[[Stereogum]]|date=April 10, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020|author=DeVille, Chris}}</ref>.\n\n== Musical style ==\n[[File:StrokesOhana270919-79 (48829452577).jpg|right|300px|thumb|[[Eddie Vedder]] singing with The Strokes in Ohana Festival, 2019]]\nThe band's sound has been described as [[indie rock]],<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/artists/the-strokes|title=The Strokes \u2013 They saved Indie!|magazine=[[Clash Magazine|Clash]]|accessdate=March 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/7704-the-decade-in-indie/|title=The Decade in Indie|work=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=May 2, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2012/jan/16/indie-rock-slow-painful-death|title=Indie rock's slow and painful death|last=Lynskey|first=Dorian|date=January 16, 2012|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=April 26, 2012}}</ref> [[garage rock revival]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/472408/top-10-garage-rock-revival-bands-where-are-they-now|title=Top 10 Garage Rock Revival Bands: Where Are They Now?|date=March 23, 2011|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 28, 2016|author=Lipshutz, Jason}}</ref> and [[post-punk revival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/kayley-kravitz/post-punk-revival-_b_2003987.html|title=Revisiting the Post-Punk Revival|date=December 23, 2015|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=December 28, 2016|author=Kravitz, Kayley}}</ref> by the media. Casablancas has cited [[Lou Reed]] of [[The Velvet Underground]] as a major influence on his lyrics and singing style. \"The way Lou Reed wrote and sang about drugs and sex, about the people around him \u2014 it was so matter-of-fact,\" Casablancas stated in a ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' interview. \"Reed could be romantic in the way he portrayed these crazy situations, but he was also intensely real. It was poetry and journalism.\" Additionally, he has stated that [[Bob Marley]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2010/08/drinks-with-julian-casablancas/|title=Drinks With: Julian Casablancas|last=Matheny|first=Skip|date=August 2, 2010|website=American Songwriter|publisher=AmericanSongwriter.com|accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref> [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] and [[Pearl Jam]] are major influences on his work, the latter being the reason that he started making music after hearing the song \"[[Yellow Ledbetter]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-strokes-elegantly-wasted-20031113|title=The Strokes: Elegantly Wasted|last=Strauss|first=Neil|date=November 13, 2003|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=September 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy and influence ==\nThe Strokes' debut album ''Is This It'' was named number one album of the year by [[NME]] and number two by ''[[Rolling Stone]],'' ''Is This It'' earned Casablancas and The Strokes tremendous respect across various artists in the alternative music scene''.''<ref name=\":5\" /> Lead singer of [[LCD Soundsystem]], [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]], has said, \"''Is This It'' was my record of the decade.\"<ref name=\":5\" /> The album won Best International Album in 2002, nominated by NME, and ASCAP College Vanguard Award.<ref>{{Citation|title=List of awards and nominations received by The Strokes|date=2017-11-25|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=List_of_awards_and_nominations_received_by_The_Strokes&oldid=811948429|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref>\n\nThe Strokes have been said to be, \"as influential to their era as the Velvet Underground or the Ramones were to theirs,\u201d by Lizzie Goodman in her book on the New York City music scene, claiming that, \"almost every artist I interviewed for this book \u2014 from all over the world \u2014 said it was the Strokes that opened the door for them.\"<ref name=\":7\" /> The band was named Band of the Year in 2002 by ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' and have heavily influenced bands like [[The Killers]], [[Arctic Monkeys]], and [[Franz Ferdinand (band)|Franz Ferdinand.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/nov/26/the-strokes-is-this-it|title=Albums of the decade No 4: The Strokes \u2013 Is This It|last=Mulholland|first=Garry|date=2009-11-26|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==Band members==\n* [[Julian Casablancas]] \u2013 lead vocals <small>(1998\u2013present)</small>, keyboards <small>(2010\u2013present)</small>\n*[[Nikolai Fraiture]] \u2013 bass <small>(1998\u2013present)</small>\n*[[Albert Hammond Jr.]] \u2013 guitars <small>(1998\u2013present)</small>, backing vocals <small>(2010\u2013present)</small>\n*[[Fabrizio Moretti]] \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(1998\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Nick Valensi]] \u2013 guitars <small>(1998\u2013present)</small>, backing vocals <small>(2010\u2013present)</small>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|The Strokes discography}}\n* ''[[Is This It]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Room on Fire]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[First Impressions of Earth]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Angles (The Strokes album)|Angles]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Comedown Machine]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[The New Abnormal]]'' (2020)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by The Strokes}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{The Strokes}}\n{{Julian Casablancas}}\n{{Albert Hammond Jr.}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Rock music|New York City}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Strokes, The}}\n[[Category:1998 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:The Strokes| ]]\n[[Category:Indie rock musical groups from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from New York City]]\n[[Category:Post-punk revival music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1998]]\n[[Category:RCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:Rough Trade Records artists]]\n[[Category:NME Awards winners]]\n", "name_user": "Hostagecat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe New Abnormal (2019\u2013present):formatting of two periods", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Strokes"}
{"title_page": "Loop Service", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|text=the [[Loop Trolley]] in St. Louis}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name             = Loop Service\n| other_name       = {{plainlist}}\n* A Loop/B Loop\n* Central Loop Line (2012\u20132015)\n{{endplainlist}}\n| color            = {{TMTC color|B}}\n| color2           = {{TMTC color|A}}\n| logo             = Portland Streetcar symbol.svg\n| logo_width      = 30px\n| image            = Streetcar on Tilikum Crossing with fog-shrouded hills in background, 11-2015.jpg\n| image_width      = 250px\n| image_alt        = \n| caption          = B Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015\n| type             = [[Streetcar]]\n| system           = [[Portland Streetcar]]\n| status           = Operational\n| locale           = [[Portland, Oregon]], U.S.\n| start            = \n| end              = \n| stations         = 52\n| routes           = 2\n| daily_ridership  = {{plainlist}}\n* '''A Loop:''' 3,612\n* '''B Loop:''' 3,064\n{{endplainlist}}{{br}}({{as of|2018|September|lc=yes}})<ref name=\"portland-streetcar-ridership-counts-2018-09\">{{cite news |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Ridership-Counts-2018-09.pdf |title=Portland Streetcar Ridership Counts, July 2015 - Present (By Fiscal Year) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=September 2018 |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| ridership2       =\n| open             = {{start date|2012|09|22}}\n| event1label      = \n| event1           = \n| event2label      = \n| event2           = \n| event3label      = \n| event3           = \n| owner            = [[Government of Portland, Oregon|City of Portland]]\n| operator         = Portland Streetcar, Inc.{{br}}[[TriMet]]\n| character        = [[At-grade]], mixed between [[street running]] and exclusive lane\n| depot            = \n| stock            = \n| linelength       = {{convert|5.7|mi|km|abbr=on}} (per direction)\n| tracklength_mi   = \n| tracks           = \n| gauge            = {{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n| old_gauge        = \n| load_gauge       = \n| minradius        = \n| racksystem       = \n| routenumber      = \n| linenumber       = \n| electrification  = 750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct Current|DC]], [[overhead line|overhead catenary]]\n| speed_mph        = \n| elevation_ft     = \n| website          = \n| map              = {{Portland Streetcar CL Line}}\n| map_name         = Route diagram\n| map_state        = collapsed\n}}\nThe '''Loop Service''' is a [[streetcar]] [[circle route|circle line]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States, that is part of the [[Portland Streetcar]] system. Operated by Portland Streetcar, Inc. and [[TriMet]], it consists of two distinct services: the '''A Loop''', which runs [[clockwise]], and the '''B Loop''', which runs counterclockwise. Each service travels a {{convert|5.7|mi|km|1|adj=on}} loop between [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|downtown Portland]] and the [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]], crossing the [[Willamette River]] on the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland)|Broadway Bridge]] in the north and [[Tilikum Crossing]] in the south. The line connects Portland's downtown, [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]], and [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]. It serves the city's various landmarks and institutions, including the [[Rose Quarter, Portland, Oregon|Rose Quarter]], the [[Oregon Convention Center]], the [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] (OMSI), [[Oregon Health and Science University]] (OHSU), and [[Portland State University]] (PSU).\n\nPortland city officials first proposed building an eastside streetcar line in 1997, at the same time the city council authorized the construction of the [[NS Line|first streetcar line]] on the west side. After several years of planning, the city council approved the Eastside Loop extension in 2008 and the project's groundbreaking took place in 2009. The {{convert|3.3|mi|km|adj=on}} extension opened between the Broadway Bridge and OMSI on September 22, 2012. It was inaugurated with the '''Central Loop Line''' ('''CL Line''') service, which ran an additional {{convert|1.1|mi|km}} alongside the NS Line on 10th and 11th avenues. This service split into two and re-branded in 2015 during the opening of Tilikum Crossing, which completed the streetcar loop with a southerly river crossing extension from OMSI to the South Waterfront.\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Broadway Bridge west end.jpg|thumb|left|The Broadway Bridge in 2009, prior to the installation of streetcar tracks]]\n\nPlans to expand the Portland Streetcar east of the [[Willamette River]] emerged in July 1997, at the same time the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|Portland City Council]] authorized the construction of the system's [[NS Line|first line]] on the west side between [[Northwest District, Portland, Oregon|Northwest Portland]] and [[Portland State University|PSU]]. During this time, the council also voted to fund a $16.7&nbsp;million retrofitting of the [[Hawthorne Bridge]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Closure launches bridge make over |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=January 22, 1998 |page=D2}}</ref> which they had anticipated would carry a future streetcar line on the east side between [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry|OMSI]] and the [[Oregon Convention Center]] as proposed by the Buckman Neighborhood Association.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Streetcars will return to Portland; the city council votes to pay for a westside loop of streetcars described as cheaper than light rail |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 31, 1997 |page=D1}}</ref> The Hawthorne Bridge reopened in April 1999, with the outer-lane decks rebuilt to accommodate notches for rails.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Wait no more: Sunday makrs Hawthorne Bridge reopening |date=April 24, 1999 |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=C1}}</ref> In July 2001, another streetcar plan was proposed as part of the Lloyd District Development Strategy.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\">{{cite web |url=https://prosperportland.us/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Lloyd-District-Development-Strategy-Full-2001-07-27.pdf |title=Lloyd District Development Strategy |publisher=[[Prosper Portland|Portland Development Commission]] |date=July 27, 2001 |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Portland grand plans works in works in Lloyd District |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 17, 2001 |page=B3}}</ref> This strategy sought the addition of streetcars to the [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]], which was already being served by buses and [[MAX Light Rail]],<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|20}} to create a [[transit hub]] by adding lines on Broadway and Weidler avenues.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|26}} The extension would connect with the west side via the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland, Oregon)|Broadway Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=New streetcar route follows different mission |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 20, 2001 |page=24}}</ref> This plan was supported by concurrent efforts to revitalize nearby [[Rose Quarter]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Vision for Rose Quarter outlined |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 13, 2001 |page=A1}}</ref>\n\nIn a series of meetings that began in February 2003, an advisory committee composed of eastside residents urged extending this proposed Broadway\u2013Weidler alignment up to 21st Avenue. Meanwhile, Portland Streetcar officials, amid [[TriMet]] plans to construct a new Willamette River crossing as part of a [[MAX Orange Line|MAX extension to Milwaukie]], suggested routing the OMSI\u2013Oregon Convention Center proposal to this planned bridge instead of the Hawthorne Bridge.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar officials seek Eastside desire |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=February 17, 2003 |page=E2}}</ref> The city council, with backing from [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] commissioners, adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in June 2003.<ref name=\"eastside-study\">{{cite web |title=Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study |date=June 25, 2003 |publisher=[[Portland Bureau of Transportation|Portland Office of Transportation]] |url=https://scholarsbank.uoregon.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1794/5259/Portland_Eastside_Streetcar_Study.pdf |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The study outlined a westside\u2013eastside loop project that ran from the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]] through the Broadway Bridge to the Lloyd District, then south through Grand Avenue and [[Oregon Route 99E|Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard]] to Hawthorne Boulevard. A southern crossing back to the west side depended upon whether the new bridge would be constructed, leaving that section undetermined at the time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar backers propose loop through Inner Eastside |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 6, 2003 |page=D2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stern |first1=Henry |last2=Nkrumah |first2=Wade |title=City Council watch |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 26, 2003 |page=C2}}</ref> In 2008, a locally preferred alternative was selected for the Portland\u2013Milwaukie light rail project that included a new river crossing between the South Waterfront and OMSI;<ref name=oreg-2008may2>{{cite news |last=Mortenson |first=Eric |date=May 2, 2008 |title=Panel realigns route of new light-rail span |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D1}}</ref> this led to a decision to extend the first phase of the eastside streetcar segment {{convert|3.3|mi|km}} up to OMSI until the new bridge could be completed, after which the streetcar would cross the bridge back to the west side and thus form a complete loop.<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/transportation/article/408420 |title=Portland Streetcar Loop Development Strategy |publisher=Portland Office of Transportation |date=April 14, 2008 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|1}}<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.oregonmetro.gov/sites/default/files/2014/04/18/070908_portland_streetcar_loop_environmental_assessment_FONSI.pdf |title=Portland Streetcar Loop environmental assessment: Finding of no significant impact |publisher=Metro |date=July 9, 2008 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|2}}\n\n===Funding and construction===\n\n[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] regional government approved the streetcar extension in July 2006 followed by the city council in September 2007.<ref>{{cite news |last=McGrain |first=Maureen |title=Metro says yes to expansion for streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=July 28, 2006 |url=http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/07/31/story11.html |accessdate=May 20, 2009 |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=\"extension-green-light\">{{cite news |last=Mayer |first=James |date=September 7, 2007 |title=Streetcar extension gets green light |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D1}}</ref> The total cost of the phase one project was $148.8{{nbsp}}million (equivalent to ${{Format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|148800000|2012}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}} dollars), including the cost to purchase additional vehicles.<ref name=\"streetcar-loop-fta\">{{cite report |url=https://www.transit.dot.gov/sites/fta.dot.gov/files/docs/funding/grant-programs/capital-investments/115401/2016-oregon-portland-streetcar-loop-project.pdf |title=Streetcar Loop Project Before-and-After Study (2016) |publisher=[[Federal Transit Administration]] |date=2016 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|19}} Just over half would be paid for with federal funds.<ref name=\"wweek20120822\">{{cite web |title=Slow Ride |url=https://www.wweek.com/portland/article-19584-slow_ride.html |first=Aaron |last=Mesh |date=August 22, 2012 |newspaper=[[Willamette Week]] |accessdate=August 29, 2012}}</ref> The city council committed to allocating $27{{nbsp}}million of city funds.<ref name=\"extension-green-light\"/> $20{{nbsp}}million from the state, $15.5{{nbsp}}million from a Local Improvement District, and a combination of various other local or regional sources completed the locally matched financing.<ref name=\"factsheetMay2010\">{{cite web |title=Portland Streetcar Loop fact sheet (May 2010) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |accessdate=August 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821075510/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |archive-date=August 21, 2010 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> On April 30, 2009, U.S. [[United States Secretary of Transportation|Transportation Secretary]] [[Ray LaHood]] announced $75{{nbsp}}million in federal funding for the project, the full amount that had been requested by Portland. This allocation, secured in large part through the efforts of Oregon [[United States House of Representatives|Representatives]] [[Earl Blumenauer]] and [[Peter DeFazio]], was the largest and final component of the financing plan and meant the project could proceed with construction.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pope |first1=Charles |last2=Rivera |first2=Dylan |title=Feds approve $75 million for streetcar expansion |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005165644/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |archive-date=October 5, 2012 |url-status=unfit}}</ref><ref name=\"Fedsgive\">{{cite news |title=Feds give $75 million for Oregon streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2009/04/27/daily46.html?surround=lfn |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:United Streetcar 10T3 prototype for Portland.jpg|thumb|left|Unveiling of the United Streetcar 10T3 prototype in July 2009]]\n\nIn 2005, the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] approved a spending bill that included $4{{nbsp}}million for a locally produced streetcar vehicle.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |last=Hamilton |first=Don |title=Iron firm forges streetcar desire |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=August 5, 2005 |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331125621/https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |archive-date=March 31, 2012}}</ref> That money went to [[Oregon Iron Works]], which created the subsidiary [[United Streetcar]] upon receiving the contract to build new streetcars for the Portland Streetcar.<ref name=\"streetcarcontract\">{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Oregon Iron Works gets contract for streetcar |date=January 26, 2007 |newspaper=[[Portland Business Journal]] |url=https://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2007/01/22/daily45.html |accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> In May 2009, United Streetcar delivered its first prototype to Portland for testing on existing tracks; it was the first U.S.-built streetcar in nearly 60 years.<ref name=\"trib-2009may14\">{{cite news |last=MacKinnon |first=Mary |title=Streetcars soon to be made in Oregon |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=May 14, 2009<!--(later re-dated May 13)--> |url=http://portlandtribune.com/component/content/article?id=49492 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> That August, the city signed a $20{{nbsp}}million contract to purchase six new streetcars from the manufacturer for the eastside extension.<ref name=\"Oreg14Aug09\">{{cite news |last=Rivera |first=Dylan |title=Portland inks $20 million deal for locally made streetcars |date=August 14, 2009 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817123910/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archivedate=17 August 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGroundbreaking for the Eastside Streetcar Loop project took place on June 25, 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/construction-begins-eastside-streetcar-loop/ |last=Baer |first=April |title=Construction Begins On Eastside Streetcar Loop |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |date=June 25, 2009 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The city selected [[Stacy and Witbeck]] to be the project's general contractor and actual construction began the following year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://djcoregon.com/news/2009/02/17/stacy-and-witbeck-wins-streetcar-contract/ |last=Carinci |first=Justin |title=Stacy and Witbeck wins streetcar contract |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=February 17, 2009 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Across the alignment, crews laid tracks in three-to-four-block increments; by February 2010, they were laying tracks on Northeast Grand Avenue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/02/09/streetcar-loop-project/ |title=Streetcar Loop Project |last=Carter |first=Dan |publisher=[[Daily Journal of Commerce]] |date=February 9, 2010 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The Broadway Bridge was closed to all traffic to be renovated from July 19 to September 3, 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |title=Portland \u2013 Broadway Bridge will close |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 18, 2010}}</ref> To maintain the existing weight of the bridge (this was necessary to allow the bridge to continue lifting its spans) and simultaneously add tracks, lighter fiber-reinforced concrete replaced the deck.<ref name=\"streetcar work\">{{cite news|last=Rose|first=Joseph |title=Streetcar work shutting down Broadway Bridge |date=July 5, 2010 <!--(July 4 online edition)--> |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=A10 |url=https://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2010/07/streetcar_work_shuts_broadway.html |accessdate=November 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"wrap-up-broadway\">{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/02/18/streetcar-work-almost-finished-on-broadway-bridge/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Streetcar work wraps up on Broadway Bridge |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=February 18, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In the Pearl District, sections of what had been two two-way streets\u2014Northwest Lovejoy and Northwest Northrup\u2014were converted into one-way streets following the addition of rails. Work completed in this district upon the reopening of the Lovejoy ramp on the west end of the Broadway Bridge in November 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/11/05/pearl-streets-reopen-with-changed-traffic-patterns/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Pearl streets reopen with changed traffic patterns |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=November 5, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In Southeast Portland, crews built a {{convert|425|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} bridge that carried the streetcar to OMSI, the project's eastern terminus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/12/22/portland-streetcar-flyover-bridge-near-omsi/ |last=Carter |first=Dan |title=Portland Streetcar flyover bridge near OMSI |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=December 22, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Barber Block sunlit with streetcar, 2012.jpg|thumb|right|Car 015 in front of the [[Barber Block]] on Southeast Grand Avenue in 2012]] \n\nIn July 2011, the city council agreed to contractual changes that reduced the number of streetcars on order from six to five.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/07/20/eastside-streetcar-loop-will-be-delayed-number-of-cars-reduced/ |last=Webber |first=Angela |title=Eastside streetcar loop will be delayed, number of cars reduced |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=July 20, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> United Streetcar had depended on [[Czech Republic|Czech]] firm [[\u0160koda Transportation|\u0160koda]], which built the system's first streetcars, to build the new streetcars' propulsion system but these failed acceptance testing. Portland officials opted instead to source the propulsion system from [[Wisconsin]]-based [[Rockwell Automation]], but the design was still being developed at the time. They then pursued [[Austria]]n manufacturer Elin to produce a propulsion system for the prototype while they awaited Rockwell. Changes to the propulsion system necessitated changes to the streetcar design in order for the streetcar to accommodate a different form factor; this ultimately delayed the project and raised the cost of manufacturing.<ref name=\"oreg-2011jul19\">{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 19, 2011 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Opening and closing of the loop===\n\nThe streetcar extension opened on September 22, 2012, after a five-month-long delay.<ref name=\"PS-History\">{{cite web|title=Streetcar History |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |publisher=Portland Streetcar |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203013400/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |archivedate=December 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |date=July 19, 2011 |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |accessdate=September 17, 2015}}</ref> Its inaugural service, branded the Central Loop Line (abbreviated as CL Line), ran {{convert|4.4|mi|km}} total from the NS Line tracks at Southwest Market Street in downtown Portland to the Pearl District, then on the new tracks from the Broadway Bridge to OMSI in Southeast Portland.<ref name=\"PS-History\"/> Service along the eastside segment initially operated with frequencies of 18 minutes instead of an originally planned 15 minutes due to funding cuts by TriMet and the City of Portland, as well as delays in streetcar delivery from United Streetcar.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Rose (journalist) |date=September 21, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar's eastside loop gets off to hobbled start Saturday |url=http://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2012/09/portland_streetcars_eastside_l.html |newspaper=The Oregonian |accessdate=September 7, 2015}}</ref> The first car finally arrived in January 2013 and entered service on June 11, 2013.<ref name=\"oreg-2013jun12\">{{cite news|last=Schmidt|first=Brad|title=New streetcar rolls out in Portland<!--(print-edition headline)--> |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 12, 2013 |page=B1 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2013/06/after_repeated_delays_portland.html |accessdate=August 6, 2013}}</ref> Fares were $1 upon opening due to TriMet's elimination of the [[Fareless Square|Free Rail Zone]].<ref>{{cite news |date=October 5, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar Introduces 'Central Loop' Service |url=http://newsmanager.commpartners.com/aptapt/issues/2012-10-05/3.html |work=Passenger Transport |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> Approximately 3,200 riders per weekday used the line during the first two weeks of service.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2012/10/31/eastside-streetcar-carrying-the-wait.html |last=Giegerich |first=Andy |title=Eastside streetcar: Carrying the wait |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=October 31, 2012 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[File:A Lloyd via Peral (21612375879).jpg|thumb|left|An A Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015]]\n\nThe second phase of the Eastside Loop project, referred to as \"Close the Loop\", extended the streetcar {{convert|0.4|mi|km}} from OMSI to the NS Line tracks on Southwest Moody Avenue in the [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/transportation/article/321180 |title=Portland Streetcar System Concept Plan: A Framework for Future Corridor Planning and Alternatives Analysis |publisher=Portland Bureau of Transportation |date=September 9, 2009 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|50}} This phase had awaited the construction of a new bridge for the Portland\u2013Milwaukie light rail project. That bridge, later named [[Tilikum Crossing]], began construction in 2012 and completed in 2015. Construction of the streetcar components began on August 5, 2013, with the installation of a [[turning loop]] on the intersections of Southeast Stephens Street, Grand Avenue, and Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard. From September\u2013November that year, crews closed the OMSI streetcar platform to install the streetcar-track connection with the Portland\u2013Milwaukie light rail. This project had a total cost of $6.7{{nbsp}}million (equivalent to ${{Format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|6700000|2013}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}} dollars), including [[automatic train stop]] upgrades.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/Transportation/article/458059?archive=2013-08 |title=Traffic Advisory: Streetcar track work to close lanes on SE MLK Blvd Aug. 5-9; buses to replace streetcar service during construction |publisher=Portland Bureau of Transportation |date=August 9, 2013 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://efiles.portlandoregon.gov/Record/5449862/File/Document |title=Close the Loop Streetcar |publisher=Portland Bureau of Transportation |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn August 30, 2015, CL Line service was extended {{convert|0.9|mi|km}} south on the west side from Southwest 10th and Market streets along existing NS Line tracks south to Southwest Moody and Meade streets in the South Waterfront.<ref name=\"streetcar-loop-fta\"/>{{rp|19}} A new temporary schedule eliminated the name CL Line in favor of two separate routes: A Loop and B Loop. Streetcars began operating across the newly built Tilikum Crossing, but without carrying passengers across the bridge during a two-week transitional \"pre-revenue service\" phase.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\">{{cite web|title=Portland Streetcar Loop Service |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |publisher=[[Portland Streetcar|Portland Streetcar, Inc.]] |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |archivedate=August 6, 2015 |df= }}</ref> The line was formally re-branded as the Loop Service on September 12, 2015,<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.oregonmetro.gov/sites/default/files/2018/12/07/RTP-Appendix_G_CTP_20160614.pdf |title=2018 Regional Transportation Plan: Coordinated transportation plan for seniors and people with disabilities |publisher=[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] |date=December 6, 2018 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|2\u201313}} when Tilikum Crossing opened to the public and began permitting streetcars to carry passengers on the route section across the bridge.<ref name=\"tilikum-factsheet-2014\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/pdfs/pm/Fact-sheets-timelines/TC_2Page_June2014.pdf |title=Tilikum Crossing, Bridge of the People, brings new connections and new options in 2015 |publisher=TriMet |date=June 2014 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Vincent |first=John M. |date=September 8, 2015 |title=Routes, fares change with expanded streetcar service |url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |newspaper=[[The Portland Tribune]] |publisher=[[Pamplin Media Group]] |page=A3 |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128143529/http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |archivedate=November 28, 2015 |url-status=live |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n==Service==\n\nThe Loop Service operates from 5:30{{nbsp}}am to 11:30{{nbsp}}pm on weekdays, from 7:30{{nbsp}}am to 11:30{{nbsp}}pm on Saturdays, and from 7:30{{nbsp}}am to 10:30{{nbsp}}pm on Sundays. Frequencies in each direction range from 15 minutes between 10:00{{nbsp}}am and 7:00{{nbsp}}pm on weekdays and Saturdays to 20 minutes for all other times.<ref name=\"a-loop-schedules\">A Loop schedules:\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/A-Weekday.pdf |title=A Loop \u2013 Weekday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/A-Saturday.pdf |title=A Loop \u2013 Saturday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/A-Sunday.pdf |title=A Loop \u2013 Sunday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"b-loop-schedules\">B Loop schedules:\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/B-Weekday.pdf |title=B Loop \u2013 Weekday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/B-Saturday.pdf |title=B Loop \u2013 Saturday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/B-Sunday.pdf |title=B Loop \u2013 Sunday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Route===\n[[File:Portland Streetcar car 023 at west end of Broadway Bridge in 2016.jpg|thumb|right|A B Loop streetcar crossing the Broadway Bridge in 2016]]\n\nThe Loop Service runs a {{convert|5.7|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[circle route]] between downtown Portland and the Central Eastside.<ref>{{cite map |url=https://www.transitmap.net/portland-streetcar-2015/ |title=Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=2015 |via=transitmap.net}}</ref> A majority of each service travels on single-track. From their original endpoint on Southwest Market Street, the A and B Loops travel northbound through downtown Portland to the Pearl District along NS Line tracks on 10th and 11th avenues.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+10th+%26+Clay/@45.5150904,-122.6838684,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a1a07f9361b:0x48d11b9676b62d09!8m2!3d45.5144961!4d-122.6849739 |title=SW 10th & Clay |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+11th+%26+Clay/@45.5152692,-122.6853204,18z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a1a1bc20dab:0x5353b61f171ae97b!8m2!3d45.5151856!4d-122.6860428 |title=SW 11th & Clay |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The services meet at the intersection of Northwest 10th and Lovejoy where they proceed east towards the Broadway Bridge using the Eastside Loop extension tracks.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NW+9th+%26+Lovejoy/@45.5300511,-122.6789145,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x549509fe395af473:0x1f39de6a4894f631!8m2!3d45.5300534!4d-122.6806308 |title=NW 9th & Lovejoy |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> After crossing the Willamette River on this bridge, the tracks again split, with the A Loop tracks continuing east on Weidler Street and the B Loop tracks on Broadway Street.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/N+Weidler+%26+Ross/@45.5339555,-122.6694082,17.08z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a7523bc453bf:0xdf7d65ef2959f0dc!8m2!3d45.5344683!4d-122.6694356 |title=N Weidler & Ross |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Broadway+%26+Ross+(Streetcar)/@45.5337533,-122.6705135,17.04z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a7523a89db6d:0x734a73024c507be4!8m2!3d45.53445!4d-122.6695217 |title=NE Broadway & Ross (Streetcar) |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The B Loop turns right on Northeast Grand Avenue and proceeds south through the Central Eastside.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Grand+%26+Broadway/@45.533741,-122.6611424,17.83z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a74cee1672d9:0x4eb3a0bcd277cf43!8m2!3d45.5347981!4d-122.6605477 |title=NE Grand & Broadway |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The A Loop turns right onto Northeast 7th Avenue,<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+7th+%26+Halsey+Southbound/@45.5318626,-122.6610966,17.29z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0b333c19a1d:0x22d53ea9dc86a0cb!8m2!3d45.5334298!4d-122.6585944 |title=NE 7th & Halsey Southbound |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> turns left onto Northeast Oregon street, turns another left onto Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard in front of the Oregon Convention Center, and heads south.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Oregon+%26+Grand/@45.5286027,-122.6627257,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0adec0981b1:0xa2326856bed21290!8m2!3d45.5286869!4d-122.6604364 |title=NE Oregon & Grand |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Both tracks intersect the MAX Light Rail tracks on Holladay Street.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+7th+%26+Holladay/@45.5299588,-122.6609103,17.08z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0b25eeab5ef:0xa0465a316dd28817!8m2!3d45.5308073!4d-122.6586092 |title=NE 7th & Holladay |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The lines connect at a turning loop on Southeast Stephens Street and enter an overpass at Southeast Harrison Street, which carries them to the former OMSI terminus.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SE+Water%2FOMSI+(Streetcar)/@45.5079612,-122.6631697,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a7236697d75:0x40bba82a7a827677!8m2!3d45.5069508!4d-122.663364 |title=SE Water/OMSI (Streetcar) |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom OMSI, the streetcar tracks connect with the MAX tracks just west of the [[OMSI/Southeast Water station|OMSI/Southeast Water MAX station]] as they approach Tilikum Crossing to cross the river back to the west side.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/pdfs/pm/stations/Station-Area-Fact-Sheets/PMLR_OMSI_Fact_Sheet_Oct2014 |title=OMSI/SE Water Ave Station |publisher=TriMet |date=October 2014 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/OMSI%2FSE+Water+MAX+Station/@45.5066305,-122.6640224,19z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a722dc8a09d:0xd76515bef8cb8a74!8m2!3d45.5066092!4d-122.6627414 |title=OMSI/SE Water MAX Station |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> They split at the four-track [[South Waterfront/Southwest Moody station|South Waterfront/Southwest Moody MAX station]], where the streetcar tracks run in the middle of the station's [[island platform]]s but do no stop at the station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/pdfs/pm/stations/Station-Area-Fact-Sheets/PMLR_South_Waterfront_Fact_Sheet_Oct2014 |title=South Waterfront/SW Moody Ave Station |publisher=TriMet |date=October 2014 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The Loop Service returns to the NS Line alignment on Southwest Moody Avenue and heads north towards [[RiverPlace]].<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+Moody+%26+Meade+North/@45.5035053,-122.6718365,17.38z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a6bfaae8bd3:0xf9bd82c053b3079c!8m2!3d45.5031711!4d-122.6726416 |title=SW Moody & Meade North |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The tracks turn left on Southwest River Parkway, which turns into Southwest Harrison Street.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+River+Pkwy+%26+Moody/@45.5081379,-122.6757579,17.38z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a6cc98b810d:0x976c32bfe76b4de5!8m2!3d45.5071392!4d-122.6741398 |title=SW River Pkwy & Moody |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> They turn right on Southwest 4th Street, then left on Southwest Montgomery Street, and split again on Southwest 5th Avenue. The A Loop crosses PSU's [[Urban Plaza]] diagonally for Southwest Mill Street and the B Loop turns right on Southwest 5th Avenue.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/PSU+Urban+Center/@45.5128647,-122.6834114,17.54z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a112fe8f51f:0xb93dc6c9ec4eada!8m2!3d45.5122199!4d-122.6820778 |title=PSU Urban Center |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+5th+%26+Montgomery/@45.5128647,-122.6834114,17.54z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a11485235eb:0x54962f4617846156!8m2!3d45.5117905!4d-122.6812866 |title=SW 5th & Montgomery |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The A Loop turns right at Southwest 10th Avenue and returns to the intersection of Southwest 10th and Market.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+Park+%26+Mill/@45.5137505,-122.6850034,17.38z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a173473d337:0x622c5bb90d4220b2!8m2!3d45.5130549!4d-122.6844931 |title=SW Park & Mill |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The B Loop turns left onto Southwest Market Street and proceeds left until it returns to Southwest 11th and Market.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+Park+%26+Market/@45.5137505,-122.6850034,17.38z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a10b78377eb:0xf708e30d35a2a5c6!8m2!3d45.5137673!4d-122.6840942 |title=SW Park & Market |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Stations===\n\nThe Loop Service serves 52 stations, 24 of which are shared with the NS Line.<ref name=\"maps-schedules\">{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/schedules |title=Maps + Schedules \u2013 Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Each platform is equipped with a [[ticket vending machine]], [[passenger information system|real-time display]] system, and line information signs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/ride-guide/how-to-ride |title=Ride Guide |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 1, 2019}}</ref> All stations are [[Accessibility|accessible]] to users with [[Physical disability|limited mobility]].<ref name=\"accessibility-info\">{{cite web |url=http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |title=Accessibility Info |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=June 6, 2019 |archive-date=February 1, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201000132/http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> Connections to MAX Light Rail are available at ten stops across the line.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |title=Portland City Center and Transit Mall |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210193921/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Station\n! rowspan=2 | Neighborhood\n! rowspan=2 |Connections and notes<ref name=\"maps-schedules\"/>\n|-\n! A Loop{{br}}(clockwise)\n! B Loop{{br}}(counterclockwise)\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 10th & Northrup\n| rowspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 11th & Marshall\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 9th & Lovejoy\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Johnson\n| Northwest 11th & Johnson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Glisan\n| Northwest 11th & Glisan\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Couch\n| Northwest 11th & Couch\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[First Regiment Armory Annex|The Armory]], [[Powell's Books|Powell's City of Books]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Alder\n| Southwest 11th & Alder\n| rowspan=\"10\" align=\"center\" | [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|Downtown]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Central Library\n| Southwest 11th & Taylor\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|Library and Galleria stations]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Central Library (Portland, Oregon)|Central Library]]\n|-\n| Art Museum\n| Southwest 11th & Jefferson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland Art Museum]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Clay\n| Southwest 11th & Clay\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Southwest Park & Mill\n| Southwest Park & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[South Park Blocks]]\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Southwest 5th & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| PSU Urban Center\n| Southwest 5th & Montgomery\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[PSU Urban Center stations]]: [[MAX Green Line|Green]], [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]], [[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest 3rd & Harrison\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Harrison Street\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest River Parkway & Moody\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Moody & Meade\n| align=\"center\" | [[South Waterfront]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[South Waterfront/Southwest Moody station]]: [[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Health and Sciences University|OHSU]] Robertson Life Sciences Building, [[Tilikum Crossing]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | OMSI\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]]\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[OMSI/Southeast Water station]]: [[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]], [[Tilikum Crossing]]\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Mill\n| Southeast Grand & Mill\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Hawthorne\n| Southeast Grand & Hawthorne\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Taylor\n| Southeast Grand & Taylor\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Morrison\n| Southeast Grand & Morrison\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Stark\n| Southeast Grand & Stark\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast MLK & East Burnside\n| Southeast Grand & East Burnside\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Oregon Convention Center\n| Northeast Grand & Hoyt\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Convention Center station (TriMet)|Convention Center station]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Green Line|Green]], and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Convention Center]]\n|-\n| Northeast Oregon & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Holladay\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Holladay\n| Northeast Grand & Multnomah\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Northeast 7th Avenue station]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Green Line|Green]], and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Halsey\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Broadway\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & 2nd\n| Northeast Broadway & 2nd\n| \u2014\n|-\n| North Weidler & Ross\n| North Broadway & Ross\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML |display=title,inline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 Portland Streetcar Loop Service]\n*[http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/3 Portland Streetcar schedule]\n\n{{Portland Transit}}\n{{Streetcars Portland Oregon}}\n{{Portal bar|Oregon|Trains|Transport}}\n\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2012]]\n[[Category:Streetcars in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:TriMet]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|text=the [[Loop Trolley]] in St. Louis}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name             = Loop Service\n| other_name       = {{plainlist}}\n* A Loop/B Loop\n* Central Loop Line (2012\u20132015)\n{{endplainlist}}\n| color            = {{TMTC color|B}}\n| color2           = {{TMTC color|A}}\n| logo             = Portland Streetcar symbol.svg\n| logo_width      = 30px\n| image            = Streetcar on Tilikum Crossing with fog-shrouded hills in background, 11-2015.jpg\n| image_width      = 250px\n| image_alt        = \n| caption          = B Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015\n| type             = [[Streetcar]]\n| system           = [[Portland Streetcar]]\n| status           = Operational\n| locale           = [[Portland, Oregon]], U.S.\n| start            = \n| end              = \n| stations         = 52\n| routes           = 2\n| daily_ridership  = {{plainlist}}\n* '''A Loop:''' 3,612\n* '''B Loop:''' 3,064\n{{endplainlist}}{{br}}({{as of|2018|September|lc=yes}})<ref name=\"portland-streetcar-ridership-counts-2018-09\">{{cite news |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Ridership-Counts-2018-09.pdf |title=Portland Streetcar Ridership Counts, July 2015 - Present (By Fiscal Year) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=September 2018 |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| ridership2       =\n| open             = {{start date|2012|09|22}}\n| event1label      = \n| event1           = \n| event2label      = \n| event2           = \n| event3label      = \n| event3           = \n| owner            = [[Government of Portland, Oregon|City of Portland]]\n| operator         = Portland Streetcar, Inc.{{br}}[[TriMet]]\n| character        = [[At-grade]], mixed between [[street running]] and exclusive lane\n| depot            = \n| stock            = \n| linelength       = {{convert|5.7|mi|km|abbr=on}} (per direction)\n| tracklength_mi   = \n| tracks           = \n| gauge            = {{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n| old_gauge        = \n| load_gauge       = \n| minradius        = \n| racksystem       = \n| routenumber      = \n| linenumber       = \n| electrification  = 750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct Current|DC]], [[overhead line|overhead catenary]]\n| speed_mph        = \n| elevation_ft     = \n| website          = \n| map              = {{Portland Streetcar CL Line}}\n| map_name         = Route diagram\n| map_state        = collapsed\n}}\nThe '''Loop Service''' is a [[streetcar]] [[circle route|circle line]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States, that is part of the [[Portland Streetcar]] system. Operated by Portland Streetcar, Inc. and [[TriMet]], it consists of two distinct services: the '''A Loop''', which runs [[clockwise]], and the '''B Loop''', which runs counterclockwise. Each service travels a {{convert|5.7|mi|km|1|adj=on}} loop between [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|downtown Portland]] and the [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]], crossing the [[Willamette River]] on the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland)|Broadway Bridge]] in the north and [[Tilikum Crossing]] in the south. The line connects Portland's downtown, [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]], and [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]. It serves the city's various landmarks and institutions, including the [[Rose Quarter, Portland, Oregon|Rose Quarter]], the [[Oregon Convention Center]], the [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] (OMSI), [[Oregon Health and Science University]] (OHSU), and [[Portland State University]] (PSU).\n\nPortland city officials first proposed building an eastside streetcar line in 1997, at the same time the city council authorized the construction of the [[NS Line|first streetcar line]] on the west side. After several years of planning, the city council approved the Eastside Loop extension in 2008 and the project's groundbreaking took place in 2009. The {{convert|3.3|mi|km|adj=on}} extension opened between the Broadway Bridge and OMSI on September 22, 2012. It was inaugurated with service from '''Central Loop Line''' ('''CL Line'''), which ran an additional {{convert|1.1|mi|km}} along the NS Line on 10th and 11th avenues. This service split into two and re-branded in 2015 during the opening of Tilikum Crossing, which completed the streetcar loop with a southerly river crossing extension from OMSI to the South Waterfront.\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Broadway Bridge west end.jpg|thumb|left|The Broadway Bridge in 2009, prior to the installation of streetcar tracks]]\n\nPlans to expand the Portland Streetcar east of the [[Willamette River]] emerged in July 1997, at the same time the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|Portland City Council]] authorized the construction of the system's [[NS Line|first line]] on the west side between [[Northwest District, Portland, Oregon|Northwest Portland]] and [[Portland State University|PSU]]. During this time, the council also voted to fund a $16.7&nbsp;million retrofitting of the [[Hawthorne Bridge]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Closure launches bridge make over |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=January 22, 1998 |page=D2}}</ref> which they had anticipated would carry a future streetcar line on the east side between [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry|OMSI]] and the [[Oregon Convention Center]] as proposed by the Buckman Neighborhood Association.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Streetcars will return to Portland; the city council votes to pay for a westside loop of streetcars described as cheaper than light rail |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 31, 1997 |page=D1}}</ref> The Hawthorne Bridge reopened in April 1999, with the outer-lane decks rebuilt to accommodate notches for rails.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Wait no more: Sunday makrs Hawthorne Bridge reopening |date=April 24, 1999 |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=C1}}</ref> In July 2001, another streetcar plan was proposed as part of the Lloyd District Development Strategy.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\">{{cite web |url=https://prosperportland.us/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Lloyd-District-Development-Strategy-Full-2001-07-27.pdf |title=Lloyd District Development Strategy |publisher=[[Prosper Portland|Portland Development Commission]] |date=July 27, 2001 |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Portland grand plans works in works in Lloyd District |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 17, 2001 |page=B3}}</ref> This strategy sought the addition of streetcars to the [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]], which was already being served by buses and [[MAX Light Rail]],<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|20}} to create a [[transit hub]] by adding lines on Broadway and Weidler avenues.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|26}} The extension would connect with the west side via the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland, Oregon)|Broadway Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=New streetcar route follows different mission |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 20, 2001 |page=24}}</ref> This plan was supported by concurrent efforts to revitalize nearby [[Rose Quarter]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Vision for Rose Quarter outlined |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 13, 2001 |page=A1}}</ref>\n\nIn a series of meetings that began in February 2003, an advisory committee composed of eastside residents urged extending this proposed Broadway\u2013Weidler alignment up to 21st Avenue. Meanwhile, Portland Streetcar officials, amid [[TriMet]] plans to construct a new Willamette River crossing as part of a [[MAX Orange Line|MAX extension to Milwaukie]], suggested routing the OMSI\u2013Oregon Convention Center proposal to this planned bridge instead of the Hawthorne Bridge.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar officials seek Eastside desire |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=February 17, 2003 |page=E2}}</ref> The city council, with backing from [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] commissioners, adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in June 2003.<ref name=\"eastside-study\">{{cite web |title=Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study |date=June 25, 2003 |publisher=[[Portland Bureau of Transportation|Portland Office of Transportation]] |url=https://scholarsbank.uoregon.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1794/5259/Portland_Eastside_Streetcar_Study.pdf |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The study outlined a westside\u2013eastside loop project that ran from the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]] through the Broadway Bridge to the Lloyd District, then south through Grand Avenue and [[Oregon Route 99E|Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard]] to Hawthorne Boulevard. A southern crossing back to the west side depended upon whether the new bridge would be constructed, leaving that section undetermined at the time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar backers propose loop through Inner Eastside |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 6, 2003 |page=D2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stern |first1=Henry |last2=Nkrumah |first2=Wade |title=City Council watch |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 26, 2003 |page=C2}}</ref> In 2008, a locally preferred alternative was selected for the Portland\u2013Milwaukie light rail project that included a new river crossing between the South Waterfront and OMSI;<ref name=oreg-2008may2>{{cite news |last=Mortenson |first=Eric |date=May 2, 2008 |title=Panel realigns route of new light-rail span |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D1}}</ref> this led to a decision to extend the first phase of the eastside streetcar segment {{convert|3.3|mi|km}} up to OMSI until the new bridge could be completed, after which the streetcar would cross the bridge back to the west side and thus form a complete loop.<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/transportation/article/408420 |title=Portland Streetcar Loop Development Strategy |publisher=Portland Office of Transportation |date=April 14, 2008 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|1}}<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.oregonmetro.gov/sites/default/files/2014/04/18/070908_portland_streetcar_loop_environmental_assessment_FONSI.pdf |title=Portland Streetcar Loop environmental assessment: Finding of no significant impact |publisher=Metro |date=July 9, 2008 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|2}}\n\n===Funding and construction===\n\n[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] regional government approved the streetcar extension in July 2006 followed by the city council in September 2007.<ref>{{cite news |last=McGrain |first=Maureen |title=Metro says yes to expansion for streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=July 28, 2006 |url=http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/07/31/story11.html |accessdate=May 20, 2009 |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=\"extension-green-light\">{{cite news |last=Mayer |first=James |date=September 7, 2007 |title=Streetcar extension gets green light |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D1}}</ref> The total cost of the phase one project was $148.8{{nbsp}}million (equivalent to ${{Format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|148800000|2012}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}} dollars), including the cost to purchase additional vehicles.<ref name=\"streetcar-loop-fta\">{{cite report |url=https://www.transit.dot.gov/sites/fta.dot.gov/files/docs/funding/grant-programs/capital-investments/115401/2016-oregon-portland-streetcar-loop-project.pdf |title=Streetcar Loop Project Before-and-After Study (2016) |publisher=[[Federal Transit Administration]] |date=2016 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|19}} Just over half would be paid for with federal funds.<ref name=\"wweek20120822\">{{cite web |title=Slow Ride |url=https://www.wweek.com/portland/article-19584-slow_ride.html |first=Aaron |last=Mesh |date=August 22, 2012 |newspaper=[[Willamette Week]] |accessdate=August 29, 2012}}</ref> The city council committed to allocating $27{{nbsp}}million of city funds.<ref name=\"extension-green-light\"/> $20{{nbsp}}million from the state, $15.5{{nbsp}}million from a Local Improvement District, and a combination of various other local or regional sources completed the locally matched financing.<ref name=\"factsheetMay2010\">{{cite web |title=Portland Streetcar Loop fact sheet (May 2010) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |accessdate=August 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821075510/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |archive-date=August 21, 2010 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> On April 30, 2009, U.S. [[United States Secretary of Transportation|Transportation Secretary]] [[Ray LaHood]] announced $75{{nbsp}}million in federal funding for the project, the full amount that had been requested by Portland. This allocation, secured in large part through the efforts of Oregon [[United States House of Representatives|Representatives]] [[Earl Blumenauer]] and [[Peter DeFazio]], was the largest and final component of the financing plan and meant the project could proceed with construction.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pope |first1=Charles |last2=Rivera |first2=Dylan |title=Feds approve $75 million for streetcar expansion |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005165644/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |archive-date=October 5, 2012 |url-status=unfit}}</ref><ref name=\"Fedsgive\">{{cite news |title=Feds give $75 million for Oregon streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2009/04/27/daily46.html?surround=lfn |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:United Streetcar 10T3 prototype for Portland.jpg|thumb|left|Unveiling of the United Streetcar 10T3 prototype in July 2009]]\n\nIn 2005, the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] approved a spending bill that included $4{{nbsp}}million for a locally produced streetcar vehicle.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |last=Hamilton |first=Don |title=Iron firm forges streetcar desire |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=August 5, 2005 |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331125621/https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |archive-date=March 31, 2012}}</ref> That money went to [[Oregon Iron Works]], which created the subsidiary [[United Streetcar]] upon receiving the contract to build new streetcars for the Portland Streetcar.<ref name=\"streetcarcontract\">{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Oregon Iron Works gets contract for streetcar |date=January 26, 2007 |newspaper=[[Portland Business Journal]] |url=https://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2007/01/22/daily45.html |accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> In May 2009, United Streetcar delivered its first prototype to Portland for testing on existing tracks; it was the first U.S.-built streetcar in nearly 60 years.<ref name=\"trib-2009may14\">{{cite news |last=MacKinnon |first=Mary |title=Streetcars soon to be made in Oregon |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=May 14, 2009<!--(later re-dated May 13)--> |url=http://portlandtribune.com/component/content/article?id=49492 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> That August, the city signed a $20{{nbsp}}million contract to purchase six new streetcars from the manufacturer for the eastside extension.<ref name=\"Oreg14Aug09\">{{cite news |last=Rivera |first=Dylan |title=Portland inks $20 million deal for locally made streetcars |date=August 14, 2009 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817123910/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archivedate=17 August 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGroundbreaking for the Eastside Streetcar Loop project took place on June 25, 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/construction-begins-eastside-streetcar-loop/ |last=Baer |first=April |title=Construction Begins On Eastside Streetcar Loop |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |date=June 25, 2009 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The city selected [[Stacy and Witbeck]] to be the project's general contractor and actual construction began the following year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://djcoregon.com/news/2009/02/17/stacy-and-witbeck-wins-streetcar-contract/ |last=Carinci |first=Justin |title=Stacy and Witbeck wins streetcar contract |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=February 17, 2009 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Across the alignment, crews laid tracks in three-to-four-block increments; by February 2010, they were laying tracks on Northeast Grand Avenue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/02/09/streetcar-loop-project/ |title=Streetcar Loop Project |last=Carter |first=Dan |publisher=[[Daily Journal of Commerce]] |date=February 9, 2010 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The Broadway Bridge was closed to all traffic to be renovated from July 19 to September 3, 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |title=Portland \u2013 Broadway Bridge will close |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 18, 2010}}</ref> To maintain the existing weight of the bridge (this was necessary to allow the bridge to continue lifting its spans) and simultaneously add tracks, lighter fiber-reinforced concrete replaced the deck.<ref name=\"streetcar work\">{{cite news|last=Rose|first=Joseph |title=Streetcar work shutting down Broadway Bridge |date=July 5, 2010 <!--(July 4 online edition)--> |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=A10 |url=https://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2010/07/streetcar_work_shuts_broadway.html |accessdate=November 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"wrap-up-broadway\">{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/02/18/streetcar-work-almost-finished-on-broadway-bridge/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Streetcar work wraps up on Broadway Bridge |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=February 18, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In the Pearl District, sections of what had been two two-way streets\u2014Northwest Lovejoy and Northwest Northrup\u2014were converted into one-way streets following the addition of rails. Work completed in this district upon the reopening of the Lovejoy ramp on the west end of the Broadway Bridge in November 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/11/05/pearl-streets-reopen-with-changed-traffic-patterns/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Pearl streets reopen with changed traffic patterns |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=November 5, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In Southeast Portland, crews built a {{convert|425|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} bridge that carried the streetcar to OMSI, the project's eastern terminus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/12/22/portland-streetcar-flyover-bridge-near-omsi/ |last=Carter |first=Dan |title=Portland Streetcar flyover bridge near OMSI |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=December 22, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Barber Block sunlit with streetcar, 2012.jpg|thumb|right|Car 015 in front of the [[Barber Block]] on Southeast Grand Avenue in 2012]] \n\nIn July 2011, the city council agreed to contractual changes that reduced the number of streetcars on order from six to five.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/07/20/eastside-streetcar-loop-will-be-delayed-number-of-cars-reduced/ |last=Webber |first=Angela |title=Eastside streetcar loop will be delayed, number of cars reduced |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=July 20, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> United Streetcar had depended on [[Czech Republic|Czech]] firm [[\u0160koda Transportation|\u0160koda]], which built the system's first streetcars, to build the new streetcars' propulsion system but these failed acceptance testing. Portland officials opted instead to source the propulsion system from [[Wisconsin]]-based [[Rockwell Automation]], but the design was still being developed at the time. They then pursued [[Austria]]n manufacturer Elin to produce a propulsion system for the prototype while they awaited Rockwell. Changes to the propulsion system necessitated changes to the streetcar design in order for the streetcar to accommodate a different form factor; this ultimately delayed the project and raised the cost of manufacturing.<ref name=\"oreg-2011jul19\">{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 19, 2011 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Opening and closing of the loop===\n\nThe streetcar extension opened on September 22, 2012, after a five-month-long delay.<ref name=\"PS-History\">{{cite web|title=Streetcar History |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |publisher=Portland Streetcar |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203013400/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |archivedate=December 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |date=July 19, 2011 |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |accessdate=September 17, 2015}}</ref> Its inaugural service, branded the Central Loop Line (abbreviated as CL Line), ran {{convert|4.4|mi|km}} total from the NS Line tracks at Southwest Market Street in downtown Portland to the Pearl District, then on the new tracks from the Broadway Bridge to OMSI in Southeast Portland.<ref name=\"PS-History\"/> Service along the eastside segment initially operated with frequencies of 18 minutes instead of an originally planned 15 minutes due to funding cuts by TriMet and the City of Portland, as well as delays in streetcar delivery from United Streetcar.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Rose (journalist) |date=September 21, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar's eastside loop gets off to hobbled start Saturday |url=http://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2012/09/portland_streetcars_eastside_l.html |newspaper=The Oregonian |accessdate=September 7, 2015}}</ref> The first car finally arrived in January 2013 and entered service on June 11, 2013.<ref name=\"oreg-2013jun12\">{{cite news|last=Schmidt|first=Brad|title=New streetcar rolls out in Portland<!--(print-edition headline)--> |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 12, 2013 |page=B1 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2013/06/after_repeated_delays_portland.html |accessdate=August 6, 2013}}</ref> Fares were $1 upon opening due to TriMet's elimination of the [[Fareless Square|Free Rail Zone]].<ref>{{cite news |date=October 5, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar Introduces 'Central Loop' Service |url=http://newsmanager.commpartners.com/aptapt/issues/2012-10-05/3.html |work=Passenger Transport |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> Approximately 3,200 riders per weekday used the line during the first two weeks of service.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2012/10/31/eastside-streetcar-carrying-the-wait.html |last=Giegerich |first=Andy |title=Eastside streetcar: Carrying the wait |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=October 31, 2012 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[File:A Lloyd via Peral (21612375879).jpg|thumb|left|An A Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015]]\n\nThe second phase of the Eastside Loop project, referred to as \"Close the Loop\", extended the streetcar {{convert|0.4|mi|km}} from OMSI to the NS Line tracks on Southwest Moody Avenue in the [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/transportation/article/321180 |title=Portland Streetcar System Concept Plan: A Framework for Future Corridor Planning and Alternatives Analysis |publisher=Portland Bureau of Transportation |date=September 9, 2009 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|50}} This phase had awaited the construction of a new bridge for the Portland\u2013Milwaukie light rail project. That bridge, later named [[Tilikum Crossing]], began construction in 2012 and completed in 2015. Construction of the streetcar components began on August 5, 2013, with the installation of a [[turning loop]] on the intersections of Southeast Stephens Street, Grand Avenue, and Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard. From September\u2013November that year, crews closed the OMSI streetcar platform to install the streetcar-track connection with the Portland\u2013Milwaukie light rail. This project had a total cost of $6.7{{nbsp}}million (equivalent to ${{Format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|6700000|2013}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}} dollars), including [[automatic train stop]] upgrades.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/Transportation/article/458059?archive=2013-08 |title=Traffic Advisory: Streetcar track work to close lanes on SE MLK Blvd Aug. 5-9; buses to replace streetcar service during construction |publisher=Portland Bureau of Transportation |date=August 9, 2013 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://efiles.portlandoregon.gov/Record/5449862/File/Document |title=Close the Loop Streetcar |publisher=Portland Bureau of Transportation |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn August 30, 2015, CL Line service was extended {{convert|0.9|mi|km}} south on the west side from Southwest 10th and Market streets along existing NS Line tracks south to Southwest Moody and Meade streets in the South Waterfront.<ref name=\"streetcar-loop-fta\"/>{{rp|19}} A new temporary schedule eliminated the name CL Line in favor of two separate routes: A Loop and B Loop. Streetcars began operating across the newly built Tilikum Crossing, but without carrying passengers across the bridge during a two-week transitional \"pre-revenue service\" phase.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\">{{cite web|title=Portland Streetcar Loop Service |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |publisher=[[Portland Streetcar|Portland Streetcar, Inc.]] |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |archivedate=August 6, 2015 |df= }}</ref> The line was formally re-branded as the Loop Service on September 12, 2015,<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.oregonmetro.gov/sites/default/files/2018/12/07/RTP-Appendix_G_CTP_20160614.pdf |title=2018 Regional Transportation Plan: Coordinated transportation plan for seniors and people with disabilities |publisher=[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] |date=December 6, 2018 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|2\u201313}} when Tilikum Crossing opened to the public and began permitting streetcars to carry passengers on the route section across the bridge.<ref name=\"tilikum-factsheet-2014\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/pdfs/pm/Fact-sheets-timelines/TC_2Page_June2014.pdf |title=Tilikum Crossing, Bridge of the People, brings new connections and new options in 2015 |publisher=TriMet |date=June 2014 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Vincent |first=John M. |date=September 8, 2015 |title=Routes, fares change with expanded streetcar service |url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |newspaper=[[The Portland Tribune]] |publisher=[[Pamplin Media Group]] |page=A3 |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128143529/http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |archivedate=November 28, 2015 |url-status=live |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n==Service==\n\nThe Loop Service operates from 5:30{{nbsp}}am to 11:30{{nbsp}}pm on weekdays, from 7:30{{nbsp}}am to 11:30{{nbsp}}pm on Saturdays, and from 7:30{{nbsp}}am to 10:30{{nbsp}}pm on Sundays. Frequencies in each direction range from 15 minutes between 10:00{{nbsp}}am and 7:00{{nbsp}}pm on weekdays and Saturdays to 20 minutes for all other times.<ref name=\"a-loop-schedules\">A Loop schedules:\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/A-Weekday.pdf |title=A Loop \u2013 Weekday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/A-Saturday.pdf |title=A Loop \u2013 Saturday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/A-Sunday.pdf |title=A Loop \u2013 Sunday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"b-loop-schedules\">B Loop schedules:\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/B-Weekday.pdf |title=B Loop \u2013 Weekday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/B-Saturday.pdf |title=B Loop \u2013 Saturday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Schedule-PDFs/B-Sunday.pdf |title=B Loop \u2013 Sunday Schedule |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Route===\n[[File:Portland Streetcar car 023 at west end of Broadway Bridge in 2016.jpg|thumb|right|A B Loop streetcar crossing the Broadway Bridge in 2016]]\n\nThe Loop Service runs a {{convert|5.7|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[circle route]] between downtown Portland and the Central Eastside.<ref>{{cite map |url=https://www.transitmap.net/portland-streetcar-2015/ |title=Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=2015 |via=transitmap.net}}</ref> A majority of each service travels on single-track. From their original endpoint on Southwest Market Street, the A and B Loops travel northbound through downtown Portland to the Pearl District along NS Line tracks on 10th and 11th avenues.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+10th+%26+Clay/@45.5150904,-122.6838684,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a1a07f9361b:0x48d11b9676b62d09!8m2!3d45.5144961!4d-122.6849739 |title=SW 10th & Clay |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+11th+%26+Clay/@45.5152692,-122.6853204,18z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a1a1bc20dab:0x5353b61f171ae97b!8m2!3d45.5151856!4d-122.6860428 |title=SW 11th & Clay |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The services meet at the intersection of Northwest 10th and Lovejoy where they proceed east towards the Broadway Bridge using the Eastside Loop extension tracks.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NW+9th+%26+Lovejoy/@45.5300511,-122.6789145,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x549509fe395af473:0x1f39de6a4894f631!8m2!3d45.5300534!4d-122.6806308 |title=NW 9th & Lovejoy |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> After crossing the Willamette River on this bridge, the tracks again split, with the A Loop tracks continuing east on Weidler Street and the B Loop tracks on Broadway Street.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/N+Weidler+%26+Ross/@45.5339555,-122.6694082,17.08z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a7523bc453bf:0xdf7d65ef2959f0dc!8m2!3d45.5344683!4d-122.6694356 |title=N Weidler & Ross |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Broadway+%26+Ross+(Streetcar)/@45.5337533,-122.6705135,17.04z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a7523a89db6d:0x734a73024c507be4!8m2!3d45.53445!4d-122.6695217 |title=NE Broadway & Ross (Streetcar) |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The B Loop turns right on Northeast Grand Avenue and proceeds south through the Central Eastside.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Grand+%26+Broadway/@45.533741,-122.6611424,17.83z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a74cee1672d9:0x4eb3a0bcd277cf43!8m2!3d45.5347981!4d-122.6605477 |title=NE Grand & Broadway |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The A Loop turns right onto Northeast 7th Avenue,<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+7th+%26+Halsey+Southbound/@45.5318626,-122.6610966,17.29z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0b333c19a1d:0x22d53ea9dc86a0cb!8m2!3d45.5334298!4d-122.6585944 |title=NE 7th & Halsey Southbound |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> turns left onto Northeast Oregon street, turns another left onto Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard in front of the Oregon Convention Center, and heads south.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Oregon+%26+Grand/@45.5286027,-122.6627257,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0adec0981b1:0xa2326856bed21290!8m2!3d45.5286869!4d-122.6604364 |title=NE Oregon & Grand |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Both tracks intersect the MAX Light Rail tracks on Holladay Street.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+7th+%26+Holladay/@45.5299588,-122.6609103,17.08z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0b25eeab5ef:0xa0465a316dd28817!8m2!3d45.5308073!4d-122.6586092 |title=NE 7th & Holladay |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The lines connect at a turning loop on Southeast Stephens Street and enter an overpass at Southeast Harrison Street, which carries them to the former OMSI terminus.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SE+Water%2FOMSI+(Streetcar)/@45.5079612,-122.6631697,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a7236697d75:0x40bba82a7a827677!8m2!3d45.5069508!4d-122.663364 |title=SE Water/OMSI (Streetcar) |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom OMSI, the streetcar tracks connect with the MAX tracks just west of the [[OMSI/Southeast Water station|OMSI/Southeast Water MAX station]] as they approach Tilikum Crossing to cross the river back to the west side.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/pdfs/pm/stations/Station-Area-Fact-Sheets/PMLR_OMSI_Fact_Sheet_Oct2014 |title=OMSI/SE Water Ave Station |publisher=TriMet |date=October 2014 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/OMSI%2FSE+Water+MAX+Station/@45.5066305,-122.6640224,19z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a722dc8a09d:0xd76515bef8cb8a74!8m2!3d45.5066092!4d-122.6627414 |title=OMSI/SE Water MAX Station |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> They split at the four-track [[South Waterfront/Southwest Moody station|South Waterfront/Southwest Moody MAX station]], where the streetcar tracks run in the middle of the station's [[island platform]]s but do no stop at the station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/pdfs/pm/stations/Station-Area-Fact-Sheets/PMLR_South_Waterfront_Fact_Sheet_Oct2014 |title=South Waterfront/SW Moody Ave Station |publisher=TriMet |date=October 2014 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The Loop Service returns to the NS Line alignment on Southwest Moody Avenue and heads north towards [[RiverPlace]].<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+Moody+%26+Meade+North/@45.5035053,-122.6718365,17.38z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a6bfaae8bd3:0xf9bd82c053b3079c!8m2!3d45.5031711!4d-122.6726416 |title=SW Moody & Meade North |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The tracks turn left on Southwest River Parkway, which turns into Southwest Harrison Street.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+River+Pkwy+%26+Moody/@45.5081379,-122.6757579,17.38z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a6cc98b810d:0x976c32bfe76b4de5!8m2!3d45.5071392!4d-122.6741398 |title=SW River Pkwy & Moody |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> They turn right on Southwest 4th Street, then left on Southwest Montgomery Street, and split again on Southwest 5th Avenue. The A Loop crosses PSU's [[Urban Plaza]] diagonally for Southwest Mill Street and the B Loop turns right on Southwest 5th Avenue.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/PSU+Urban+Center/@45.5128647,-122.6834114,17.54z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a112fe8f51f:0xb93dc6c9ec4eada!8m2!3d45.5122199!4d-122.6820778 |title=PSU Urban Center |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+5th+%26+Montgomery/@45.5128647,-122.6834114,17.54z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a11485235eb:0x54962f4617846156!8m2!3d45.5117905!4d-122.6812866 |title=SW 5th & Montgomery |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The A Loop turns right at Southwest 10th Avenue and returns to the intersection of Southwest 10th and Market.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+Park+%26+Mill/@45.5137505,-122.6850034,17.38z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a173473d337:0x622c5bb90d4220b2!8m2!3d45.5130549!4d-122.6844931 |title=SW Park & Mill |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The B Loop turns left onto Southwest Market Street and proceeds left until it returns to Southwest 11th and Market.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+Park+%26+Market/@45.5137505,-122.6850034,17.38z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a10b78377eb:0xf708e30d35a2a5c6!8m2!3d45.5137673!4d-122.6840942 |title=SW Park & Market |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Stations===\n\nThe Loop Service serves 52 stations, 24 of which are shared with the NS Line.<ref name=\"maps-schedules\">{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/schedules |title=Maps + Schedules \u2013 Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Each platform is equipped with a [[ticket vending machine]], [[passenger information system|real-time display]] system, and line information signs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/ride-guide/how-to-ride |title=Ride Guide |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 1, 2019}}</ref> All stations are [[Accessibility|accessible]] to users with [[Physical disability|limited mobility]].<ref name=\"accessibility-info\">{{cite web |url=http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |title=Accessibility Info |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=June 6, 2019 |archive-date=February 1, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201000132/http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> Connections to MAX Light Rail are available at ten stops across the line.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |title=Portland City Center and Transit Mall |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210193921/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Station\n! rowspan=2 | Neighborhood\n! rowspan=2 |Connections and notes<ref name=\"maps-schedules\"/>\n|-\n! A Loop{{br}}(clockwise)\n! B Loop{{br}}(counterclockwise)\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 10th & Northrup\n| rowspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 11th & Marshall\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 9th & Lovejoy\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Johnson\n| Northwest 11th & Johnson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Glisan\n| Northwest 11th & Glisan\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Couch\n| Northwest 11th & Couch\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[First Regiment Armory Annex|The Armory]], [[Powell's Books|Powell's City of Books]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Alder\n| Southwest 11th & Alder\n| rowspan=\"10\" align=\"center\" | [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|Downtown]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Central Library\n| Southwest 11th & Taylor\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|Library and Galleria stations]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Central Library (Portland, Oregon)|Central Library]]\n|-\n| Art Museum\n| Southwest 11th & Jefferson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland Art Museum]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Clay\n| Southwest 11th & Clay\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Southwest Park & Mill\n| Southwest Park & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[South Park Blocks]]\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Southwest 5th & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| PSU Urban Center\n| Southwest 5th & Montgomery\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[PSU Urban Center stations]]: [[MAX Green Line|Green]], [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]], [[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest 3rd & Harrison\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Harrison Street\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest River Parkway & Moody\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Moody & Meade\n| align=\"center\" | [[South Waterfront]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[South Waterfront/Southwest Moody station]]: [[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Health and Sciences University|OHSU]] Robertson Life Sciences Building, [[Tilikum Crossing]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | OMSI\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]]\n| {{rint|